<FIRST>r a PM-TelevisionWriters     08-15 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Television Writers,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Appoints Two New Television Writers, Expands Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appointment of Jay Sharbutt as a television
writer has been announced by The Associated Press, which also said
it will expand its New York-based TV staff to two writers.
   Sharbutt will join the AP on Sept. 4. He has covered television
for the Los Angeles Times since 1983. The second TV writer will be
Scott Williams, now a national editor in New York for the news
service. Williams will transfer to the television beat later this
year.
   ``This expansion of television coverage for our members is part
of a general enhancement of AP's entertainment report,'' William
Ahearn, executive editor, said Monday.
   Ahearn said Sharbutt will be AP's lead television writer in New
York, covering all aspects of the industry. He succeeds Kathryn
Baker, who resigned to pursue a freelance writing career.
   Jerry Buck will continue as an AP television writer in Los
Angeles, where John Horn also covers TV as part of a general
entertainment beat.
   For Sharbutt, 49, it is a return to the AP's TV beat, which he
covered from 1972 to 1978. He was AP's drama critic until 1983 and
then joined the Times.
   Sharbutt joined the AP in 1966 as a newsman in its Richmond, Va.,
bureau after working for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., and for The
Orlando Sentinel.
   In subsequent years, he served as an AP newsman in Washington,
Los Angeles, and in Saigon during the Vietnam War.
   Williams, 39, has been a member of AP's national editing staff in
New York since 1984. He has supervised filing of the national news
report, and handled feature writing assignments.
   Williams joined the AP at New Orleans in 1978 after work as a
reporter for The Fitchburg-Leominster Sentinel &amp; Enterprise in
Fitchburg, Mass.
</TEXT>
