<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Jeeps     08-15 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Jeeps,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>The American Jeep Is Mark of Prestige to Japanese 4WD Enthusiasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOTOSU, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese have gone wild over four-wheel
drive vehicles and on that score they have shed their prejudices
against American automobiles.
   The American-made Jeep is the mark of prestige.
   Churning up mud, bouncing over dirt moguls, mucking through boggy
sinkholes, enthusiasts careen around a 5.5-acre four-wheel-drive
playground in the shadow of Mount Fuji.
   The equivalent of a ski resort for dirt vehicles, the
pay-by-the-day Motosu Highlands course is flourishing because herds
of four-wheel-drive vehicles were banned from tearing up Mount Fuji
itself.
   But the four-wheel-drive vehicle also has become a status symbol
in Tokyo's high-fashion Harajuku district, where urban dandies
cruise around in chrome-trimmed, jacked-up, jeep-type vehicles with
the tops down, festooned with macho but unused heavy-duty winches
and fog lights.
   And in affluent residential neighborhoods, housewives load
groceries into Jeep Cherokees parked next to Mercedes Benzes and
Saabs.
   In a country eager for ever-more-stylish ways to spend new-found
cash, four-wheel-drive recreational vehicles have become the
ultimate Japanese yuppie vehicle _ and the American Jeep is the one
to own.
   While other American cars are deemed mediocre by the Japanese,
Jeeps evoke an image of American wide-open spaces and outdoor life
that many Japanese long for, says Nobuyoshi Fukushima, editor of 4X4
Magazine.
   Chrysler Jeep sales have doubled in Japan for three years in a
row, but they still totaled only 500 in 1988.
   The vast majority of four-wheel-drive cars on Japanese roads are
still domestic models, such as the Mitsubishi Pajero or Isuzu Big
Horn. And many vehicles with the genuine Jeep insignia were built by
Mitsubishi, which bought the technology from the Willis Overland Co.
more than 20 years ago, before Jeep manufacturing was taken over in
the United States by American Motors Corp. and then Chrysler.
   Four-wheel-drive vehicles are the fastest-growing segment of
Japan's auto market. For the past few years jeep-type sales have
grown 20 to 30 percent annually, or three times as fast as the
entire car market, estimates Fukushima. One in 11 of the 6.7 million
cars produced in Japan last year had four-wheel drive.
   Recreation vehicles are part of a growing leisure industry fueled
by rising incomes and longer vacations. Skiers, surfers, and scuba
divers also are avid drivers of jeep-style vehicles. But 75 percent
of four-wheel-drives in Japan never leave city streets: their appeal
is atmospheric rather than functional.
   Jeep-style vehicles with power steering, leather seats, stereos,
adjustable suspensions and automatic transmissions sell fast, and
dealers say they're getting BMW trade-ins from buyers.
   The top-of-the-line U.S. Jeep Cherokee costs about $35,000 in
Japan, more than double the price of many smaller Japanese
jeep-style cars.
   ``This is really a luxury car, for well-to-do buyers, mostly
professionals in their late 30s or 40s,'' says Masayuki Sakamoto,
director of marketing for Chrysler Japan Sales, Ltd.
   Masaaki Kuroiwa, who has been selling Jeeps and Jeep parts for
more than 20 years from a cluttered suburban garage, finds the fad a
little ironic.
   ``There's no need for these cars in Japan nowadays,'' he said.
``There's hardly any place to really drive them. It's just a
fashion, people like them with all kinds of shiny accessories stuck
on. It's a way to spend money.''
   Kuroiwa fell in love with Jeeps when they were the only vehicles
that could get around in a devastated Japan just after World War II.
As a child he admired the powerful olive-green vehicles driven by
American occupation troops.
   After the U.S. occupation forces left Japan, their Jeeps
continued to serve as all-round vehicles, especially on rough
country roads, but they nearly disappeared in the 1960s, when many
were shipped to poorer countries for another lifetime of service.
   Now Kuroiwa and others are buying vintage American Jeeps as
collectors items from the Philippines, where they are still widely
in use.
   In Kuroiwa's lot, Yuichi Tanaka, 45, proudly pats the hood of his
well-preserved Jeep, which is exactly as old as he is.
   ``It's won a lot of Jeep beauty contests,'' he said.
</TEXT>
