<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-15 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition, Government Hold Third Round of Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition and government held a
third round of talks Monday on the country's political crisis in an
attempt to resolve the impasse over whether Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega will step down and who will govern the country after Sept. 1.
   The opposition is demanding that its victory in the May 7
presidential elections be recognized so it can take power when the
current terms of acting President Manuel Solis Palma and the
legislature expire at the end of August.
   It also wants Noriega to relinquish his post as chief of the
Panamanian Defense Forces, which makes him the country's de facto
leader.
   International observers said Noriega had the election annulled
when it became apparent the opposition was winning. He has resisted
more than a year of U.S. and opposition pressure for his ouster,
ever since he was indicted on drug trafficking charges in 1988 in
Florida.
   The opposition on Monday however refused a government proposal
that the two sides join in demanding an end to U.S. military
maneuvers along the Panama Canal, said Romulo Escobar Bethancourt,
head of the government delegation to the talks. No reason for the
opposition refusal was given.
   Last week there were at least 10 incidents between Panamanian and
U.S. troops near the Panama Canal.
   An Organization of American States mission that is mediating the
talks is to present another progress report on Aug. 23. The last
meeting between the two sides was last Friday.
