<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     08-15 0963</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Machinery Sales Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Better times on the farm are boosting sales of
new tractors and other machinery, the Agriculture Department says.
   Another reason for the increased sales is the relative scarcity
of good used machines. For years, because of tight finances, farmers
had to do with what they had. Thus, says the department's Economic
Research Service, many farmers who might be in the used market are
turning to new models.
   ``Sales in all categories of new farm machinery are expected to
expand in 1989,'' the agency said in a report. ``Farmers appear to
be continuing a trend toward using larger tractors.''
   Analysts said sales of four-wheel-drive tractors are expected to
grow the most this year, up 65 percent from 1988, followed by a 23
percent increase for the larger two-wheel-drive models, those of
more than 139 horsepower.
   Sales of combine harvesters and hay balers are also expected to
gain about 22 percent each this year.
   Overall, farmers are forecast to spend $6.2 billion to $6.7
billion on machinery this year, the third consecutive annual
increase, report said. Last year's expenditures rose to $6.03
billion from less than $5.8 billion in 1987 and $4.6 billion in 1986.
   Machinery sales rose to a record of almost $12 billion in 1979
before sliding seven consecutive years to the 1986 level.
   ``Weather conditions weakened sales growth in 1988, but are not
expected to play a significant role this year,'' the report said.
``Higher net cash income, lower real interest rates, and reductions
in outstanding debt began boosting farm machinery expenditures in
1987 and will continue to increase sales through 1989.''
   Rising land values also are improving farmers' financial
standings, enabling them to replace aging farm machinery.
   Another factor this year is a larger planted acreage, triggered
in part by last year's drought-reduced harvests and rising market
prices of some of the major commodities.
   ``An expansion in planted acres increases the return a farmer
receives from the machine, because it is used on more acres,'' the
report said. ``Furthermore, greater planted acreage makes machine
down time more costly because more acres must be worked within the
same time frame.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defensive war against Africanized honeybees
has helped slow the northward march of the insects across Mexico,
the Agriculture Department says.
   Popularly called ``killer bees'' by some, including movie
writers, the migrating bees were expected to reach the southern
United States in 1987 or 1988. Then, maybe 1989 or 1990.
   But department officials now say the bees won't reach the Rio
Grande Valley of southern Texas ``for another 18 months or later.''
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said Monday that a joint project
with Mexico has delayed the bees' arrival and ``should give
researchers and beekeepers enough time to study the bee and learn
how to manage it.''
   The Africanized honeybee is the hybrid offspring of European
honeybees and pure African queen bees brought to Brazil in 1956 for
research. The African queens escaped and began interbreeding with
native honeybees.
   Africanized bees have been migrating northward since then and
were found in southern Mexico in 1986. Today, they are about 400
miles south of the U.S. border near Tecolutla, Veracruz, Mexico.
   Although the venom of Africanized bees is no more potent than
that of the European bees that are common throughout the United
States, the hybrids can be more dangerous because of their
aggressiveness and the likelihood of them stinging in greater
numbers.
   Besides the notoriety as a fierce pest around humans and animals,
the Africanized honeybee also is feared by many commercial
beekeepers for what it might do to their industry.
   Glosser said his agency began working with the Mexican government
two years ago in a cooperative program to control the Africanized
bees.
   The program includes the detection and tracking of the bees as
they near the U.S. border; trapping and destruction of swarms to
reduce their numbers; and efforts to alter the bees genetically to
they pose less of a threat.
   ``Program personnel in Mexico have hung almost 60,000 traps in
the last 18 months and have caught more than 11,000 swarms of
Africanized bees,'' Glosser said. ``That's millions of Africanized
bees that will never reach the United States.''
   The project in Mexico also uses ``requeening'' to reduce the
transfer of Africanized traits to regular honeybee colonies.
   Beekeepers are encouraged to select queens from desirable genetic
stock and mark them with a bright paint so that it's easy to tell if
they are in the hive. If an unmarked queen is noted, that female is
replaced with a marked queen known to be of good genetic stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarterly report by the Agriculture
Department says the number of workers employed by farmers showed a
seasonal increase in July, but dropped slightly from a year ago.
   The hired work force on farms was estimated at 1,197,000 during
the week of July 9-15, up from 830,000 in April. In July 1988, the
work force was 1,200,000.
   That did not include 351,000 ``agricultural service'' workers
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors. In April, those
totaled 198,000 workers, and in July 1988 they were estimated at
303,000.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $5.23
per hour, up from $4.90 per hour a year earlier but below the
average of $5.35 in April, the report said.
   For workers hired by contractors, there was no national wage rate
available. However, workers in California were reported at $5.80 per
hour, compared with $6.45 in April and $5.74 a year earlier in July
1988.
   Florida workers averaged $5.55 per hour, compared with $6.24 in
April and $5.19 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
