<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Eastern     08-15 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Agrees to $75,000 Fine on Consumer Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines officials say they are
changing some of their business procedures after agreeing to pay a
$75,000 fine for alleged federal consumer violations.
   The Department of Transportation said Monday that the financially
hobbled carrier agreed to pay the civil penalty ``to avoid costly
litigation,'' but was not conceding guilt. The alleged violations
occurred in 1986 and 1987.
   It could take the government years to pocket the funds, however,
because Eastern has been under the protection of federal bankruptcy
laws since March 9, five days after the strike against the carrier
began.
   When a bankruptcy judge approves a schedule for repaying
creditors, the payments might take years.
   The DOT charged the airline with taking more than the required
seven days to issue credit-card refunds to customers. It also
accused Eastern of not informing some consumers that flights listed
by the carrier were operated by independent commuter airlines with
agreements with Eastern.
   Eastern officials said little about the settlement. But
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the company had ``changed our
procedures to better comply with DOT regulations.''
   DOT officials said Eastern uses an express delivery service to
speed the shipment of refund claims to its Miami headquarters.
   Northwest Airlines agreed to pay a $325,000 fine in November
1987, the largest ever. Continental Airlines _ like Eastern a
subsidiary of Texas Air Corp. _ agreed to pay a $250,000 penalty for
similar charges in June 1987.
   Eastern filed a reorganization plan with the federal bankruptcy
court July 21. Its goal is to emerge from reorganization by the end
of this year.
   Under the agreement with the DOT, the government would receive
its payment after all creditors have been repaid but before
Eastern's debts to Texas Air are repaid.
   If the agreement isn't approved by the court by Nov. 30, it would
be voided and the government would have to renew its efforts to
press its case against Eastern.
   Sam Podberesky, a DOT assistant general counsel, said the fine
could be repaid in the next few months or could be delayed until
sometime in the 1990s.
   Typically, he said, fines levied against financially healthy
airlines are paid within anywhere from 15 days to two years. Claims
against carriers in bankruptcy can take years, he said.
   Eastern, which operated 1,100 flights daily before the strike,
operated 350 flights Monday and planned to increase that to 390
Tuesday, Ceremsak said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
