<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Leland-Hunger 490   08-15 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland-Hunger, 490</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Obvious Successor to Leland Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Leland-US</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mickey Leland's crusade against hunger
will live on despite his death, says House Speaker Thomas S. Foley,
but there appears to be no obvious successor to carry the torch.
   ``There will be a determination on the part of members of the
House to work for those goals that Mickey Leland sought to achieve _
the alleviation of hunger and suffering here and in Africa and
elsewhere in the world,'' Foley said Monday.
   However, Foley, D-Wash., didn't say who would become chairman of
the House Select Committee on Hunger, the panel Leland founded in
1984. Leland, a Texas Democrat, died in a plane crash last week
while on a fact-finding mission in Ethiopia.
   Foley aide Jeff Biggs said a new committee chairman was not
expected to be named until next month when Congress returns from a
month-long recess.
   Leland's efforts were credited with getting $800 million in
relief for victims of famine in Africa.
   ``Whenever a member wanted to do something (on hunger) they would
go to him,'' Miranda Katsoyannis, chief of staff of the hunger
committee, said Monday. ``This committee served as a focus. The
Congress became more sensitive as a result.''
   Leland parceled out responsibilities and several members of the
committee were leaders in specific areas, Katsoyannis said.
   The senior member is Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, who shared Leland's
concern for hunger in the Third World. Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y.,
another committee member, was one of Leland's closest associates and
among the first to go to Ethiopia to strengthen search efforts last
week.
   Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., is known for his work with the hungry
of Central America, while Rep. Mike Espy, D-Miss., has been a leader
in nutrition efforts among the rural poor of the United States. Rep.
Albert Bustamante, D-Texas, is known for his work on hunger problems
among the Hispanic poor.
   Seniority rules don't apply to select committee chairmanships
which, like standing committees, are made by the speaker.
   Select committees don't act on legislation, but do initiate
studies, hold hearings and influence other committees to make
changes or additions to the federal statutes.
   ``Select committees at their best, offer us a flexibility and a
sense of focus that we may otherwise not find in our standing
committees,'' House Republican Leader Bob Michel of Illinois said
during debate in February on whether to continue the committees.
   Leland said during the same debate that his committee's work was
extensive during the 100th Congress.
   ``Thirty-two hearings, nine basic human needs seminars and
numerous briefings were held; nine reports were published and
monthly status reports on international and domestic hunger were
issued and widely distributed,'' he said.
   The House Select Committee on Hunger was instrumental in setting
up the Child Survival Fund, part of the U.S. foreign assistance
program. It also provided impetus to expanded research into the
effects of vitamin A on child mortality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
