<FIRST>r w PM-SovietMissile 530   08-15 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Missile, 530</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Distressed Soviets Didn't Heed Appeals on Missile Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is upset that the
Soviet Union ignored two high-level U.S. appeals to change its plans
to test a long-range missile that passed near the Hawaiian islands.
   ``There was no danger, but there is always a risk, however
slight,'' a U.S. official said Monday after Friday's 8,000-mile
flight of an unarmed intercontinental ballistic missile was
disclosed.
   The missile didn't pass over land while flying over the island
chain, but a U.S. official said the point of the complaint was that
``it was too close for comfort.''
   The missile was launched from the Tyuratam installation deep in
the Soviet Union and splashed down some 1,250 miles south of Oahu,
officials said.
   Two U.S. officials told The Associated Press the missile had
passed over waters between two tiny Hawaiian islands, Neckar and
Nihoa. A third official confirmed that the Soviets conducted the
test Friday despite U.S. appeals that it posed potential political
and safety problems.
   The Soviets announced Aug. 7 that they intended to conduct a test
between Aug. 11 and Aug. 21, but neither of the two private U.S.
appeals to Deputy Ambassador Serge Chetverikov nor the test itself
were made public.
   ``It's somewhat disturbing the Soviets didn't take our concerns
into account,'' a U.S. official said Monday. ``There was no danger,
but there is always a risk, however slight, it might be that
something would go awry. That is why we felt it was inappropriate.''
   Assistant Secretary of State Raymond R. Seitz and his deputy,
Curtis W. Kamman, held separate meetings last Monday and Tuesday
with Chetverikov to complain that the missile was likely to pass
over the Hawaiian Island chain before splashing down in the ocean.
   Seitz and Kamman are the senior officers in the State
Department's Bureau of European and Canadian Affairs.
   ``The U.S. government expressed its deep concern to the Soviets
over the planned test and asked that it be modified,'' a U.S.
official said.
   Chetverikov returned to the State Department on Wednesday to say
the test would be conducted strictly over water, not over any U.S.
territory. He said it would involve only international airspace and
water.
   ``We did not find that response persuasive or sufficient, because
the Soviet missile test would pass over the Hawaiian Island chain,''
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It is not
a legal issue but an issue of political and safety considerations.
Once again, we strongly urged the Soviets to reconsider their
plans.''
   Two years ago, in a similar situation, the Soviets revised a
missile test near Hawaii when the Reagan administration objected.
   In the U.S. appeals to the Soviets, the planned test was
described as a ``provocation,'' said another U.S. official, who also
requested anonymity.
   U.S. relations with the Soviet Union have been on the upsurge on
most fronts, although there have been recent disagreements over U.S.
assistance to rebels in Afghanistan and Soviet overtures to Iran.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze will meet in Wyoming next month to plan a summit
between President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
