<FIRST>r w PM-US-China     08-15 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Envoy Bids Adieu With Round of Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's ambassador to the United States, whose
tenure marked a steady expansion in U.S.-Sino relations until the
massacre of pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing, is ending his
tour with meetings and parties.
   Clues to how the administration and corporate America view China
two months after troops marched into Tianamen Square may be found in
the attendance at Ambassador Han Xu's farewell reception at the
Chinese Embassy on Wednesday.
   Han has invited an array of officials, businessmen, academic
experts and diplomats. China-watchers will size up the
representation and observe which members of Congress, on vacation
for the August recess, return to Washington for the affair.
   President Bush said after the Tianamen Square massacre that
relations with China were important and that dialogue would continue
in the hope that Chinese leaders would end repression.
   However, the president said it would not be ``business as
usual,'' suspending military and top-level exchanges.
   Han, 65, has made farewell visits to Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, four other Cabinet members and other senior officials. No
meeting is scheduled with Bush, who knew Han Xu when he headed the
U.S. liaison office in Beijing.
   Han's call on Baker last Friday was ``strongly personal, based on
a friendship that they've had for many, many years ... a one-on-one
meeting,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   The Chinese Embassy said Han and Baker ``expressed a desire to
preserve and develop'' U.S.-China relations.
   Han, in meetings with U.S. officials since June, has faithfully
echoed his government's line condemning U.S. criticism of its
pro-democracy crackdown as interference in internal Chinese affairs.
   A State Department expert, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said U.S.-China relations had been moving ahead until June. But he
said the United States had continued to communicate with Han.
   ``How are you going to tell them you're upset about things if you
don't talk to them?'' he asked. ``Nothing has altered our dismay
about events, but the way to express that view is to have contacts
at a sufficient level so you know you're getting through.''
   Han also paid farewell calls to Secretary of Agriculture Clayton
Yeutter, Secretary of Commerce Robert Mosbacher, U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills, National Security Adviser Brent
Scowcroft, Senate Democratic and Republican Party leaders George
Mitchell and Bob Dole and other senior officials, the Chinese
Embassy said.
   Former President Nixon, who met Han during his historic 1972 trip
to China, gave a dinner Aug. 3 for the ambassador, said Nixon aide
John Taylor.
   Han, who has been in Washington for more than four years, will be
replaced by Vice Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
