<FIRST>r w PM-SEC-Breeden     08-15 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Breeden,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Aide Breeden Chosen for SEC Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters and detractors of Richard C. Breeden
agree his nomination as chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission could define the Bush administration's response to the
internationalization of financial markets.
   President Bush on Monday named Breeden, point man on the new
multibillion-dollar plan to bail out the savings-and-loan industry,
to head the five-member SEC.
   ``He's an important member of the Bush team. It seems to me that
Bush has placed a high priority on the SEC,'' said Lee Polson,
executive director of the North American Securities Administrators
Association, a national organization of state-level securities
regulators.
   Joseph R. Hardiman, president of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, said Breeden ``would be one who would be readily
acceptable to the securities industry and one who would readily
resolve the issues'' facing the industry.
   The White House announcement ended speculation about a successor
for SEC Chairman David S. Ruder, who announced in May that he was
stepping down.
   The SEC post requires Senate confirmation.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the securities
subcommittee, said the challenges faced by the commission include
``growing internationalization of financial markets and whether the
SEC will have adequate resources in the 1990s.''
   ``I look forward to the committee's hearings on Mr. Breeden, and
to the opportunity they will afford to closely examine the Bush
administration's plans in a number of key areas,'' Dodd said in a
statement.
   Created in 1934 during the Depression, the SEC oversees
securities markets and regulates the sale of stocks, bonds and other
securities as part of its mission to keep the markets honest while
protecting investors.
   Most recently, Breeden served as one of the architects of the S&amp;L
restructuring legislation, submitted in February, and guided it
through Congress. The final plan, a sweeping rewrite of banking laws
and the largest single-industry government bailout, was signed into
law by Bush last week.
   Securities industry leaders and Republicans generally hailed
Bush's choice, but some Senate Democrats were less enthusiastic.
   ``I think it's a splendid appointment,'' said Roderick M. Hills,
a former SEC chairman under President Ford.
   ``It's going to be a very hard time at the commission in these
next few years,'' said Hills, now in private legal practice in New
York. ``The focus is going to be different. Our companies are going
to seek capital abroad and foreign companies are going to be seeking
capital here.''
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, also praised Breeden's intelligence and work on the
savings and loan bailout but said, ``He brings a limited direct
market experience to this critical assignment and that is a matter
of some concern when the SEC faces a time of epic challenge.''
   Breeden, a 39-year-old lawyer and banking specialist, said
through an aide he will not speak with reporters until after his
Senate confirmation.
   Breeden, whose job as presidential assistant for issues analysis
made him something of a White House trouble shooter, also helped
fashion administration policy for dealing with the Alaska oil spill.
   Breeden was deputy counsel to Vice President Bush from 1982 to
1985.
   Earlier, he was a securities specialist with a New York law firm,
and between government assignments worked in the Washington office
of a Houston law firm.
   He was also directed a task force on deregulation headed by Bush
as vice president, and wrote the panel's report on the deregulation
of financial services.
   But Polson said he saw no irony in a former deregulator's
appointment to a major regulatory agency.
   ``When Chairman Ruder was picked, he was widely characterized as
a deregulator, too,'' said Polson ``I don't think it's useful in
determining how he's going to perform as chairman of the SEC.''
   Bush announced he would nominate Breeden to the commission seat
held by Charles C. Cox, whose term has expired. After Breeden's
confirmation by the Senate, Bush would immediately designate Breeden
as the new chairman.
   Ruder said Monday he plans to resign effective Sept. 30 unless
Breeden is confirmed before that. His resignation would create
another vacancy on the commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
