<FIRST>r w PM-AgedPurse     08-15 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aged Purse,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purse Turns Up 18 Years 10 Months Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was hardly a typical time capsule _ black
vinyl packed with lipstick, makeup and old photos.
   It was a purse that had been stolen Oct. 18, 1970.
   Construction workers in an old department store being converted
to apartments found the purse behind a storage cabinet last
Wednesday. The money was gone, but there was an address book with
some telephone numbers.
   After 18 years and 10 months, Alice Wilson had the purse she had
long since given up for lost.
   Inside was her driving learner's permit, photos of her high
school sweetheart and her high school girlfriends, her Social
Security card, voter registration card and lipstick and makeup.
   ``It brought back memories,'' said Wilson, who had been working
in the department store when the purse was stolen.
   She said the thief took $60, her weekly pay. The bag apparently
was tossed on the tall, wooden cabinet in the basement of the store.
And there it stayed until the workers moved that cabinet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
