<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0226EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Botha-Chronology     08-15 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botha-Chronology,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Dates in Botha's Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key dates in the life of P.W.
Botha.
   Jan. 12, 1916 _ Born on farm in the Orange Free State.
   May 1, 1936 _ Quits university to take job as an organizer for
the National Party in the Cape province.
   1939-1940 _ Helps form Cape province branch of the Ossewabrandwag
(Ox-Wagon Fire Guard), a group sympathetic to the Nazis and opposed
South Africa joining the Allied side in World War II. Threatened
with internment but turns against the Ossewabrandwag when it split
with National Party leaders.
   March 13, 1943 _ Marries Elize Rossouw.
   May 26, 1948 _ Becomes a member of Parliament from George, in
Cape province as his National Party comes to power.
   October, 1958 _ Is appointed deputy minister of the interior.
Duties include close involvement with administering the Group Areas
Act, which segregates residential and business areas by race.
   Aug. 2, 1961 _ Becomes a Cabinet minister in charge of community
development and colored (mixed-race) affairs.
   April 5, 1966 _ Becomes minister of defense, and is instrumental
in making South Africa nearly self-sufficient in arms despite a
United Nations arms embargo.
   1966 _ Is elected leader of the National Party in Cape province,
one of four powerful provincial leadership posts from which party
leaders are chosen.
   Sept. 28, 1978 _ Becomes National Party leader and prime
minister, following resignation of B.J. Vorster.
   1979 _ Becomes first national leader to visit a black township,
Soweto.
   1982 _ National Party right-wing breaks away, forming
Conservative Party, in response to Botha's plans to include Indians
and people of mixed-race in Parliament, in separate chambers. Meets
with Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda.
   1984 _ New constitution is adopted, creating the three-chambered
Parliament that excludes the black majority, and changes Botha's
title from prime minister to president, with wide-ranging powers.
Tours Europe and declares, ``Apartheid is dead.''
   June 12, 1986 _ Declares national emergency to subdue unrest and
nationwide violence that erupted in black communities in response to
the new constitution.
   Jan. 18, 1989 _ Suffers a stroke and subsequently gives up
leadership of National Party.
   March, 1989 _ Under pressure from party leaders, agrees to resign
from presidency following Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
   July 5, 1989 _ Invites imprisoned African National Congress
leader Nelson Mandela to his official Cape Town residence for
conversation.
   Aug. 14, 1989 _ Announces his resignation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
