<FIRST>r a PM-Leland-Replacement     08-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland-Replacement,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland's Wife Could Win His Vacant House Seat, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Leland-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Leland's widow could take over her
husband's House seat almost without opposition, but some politicians
are pondering a race for the post if she chooses not to run,
observers say.
   ``So many people know her personally and out of respect for
Mickey and her, she could walk in,'' Jack Carter, Harris County
Democratic Party chairman, said of Alison Leland.
   ``In the great Southern tradition, it's the wife who would come
forward,'' said Robert Stein, a political science professor at Rice
University. ``If Mickey Leland's wife is in there, you're not going
to have anyone running against her.''
   Mrs. Leland is a 30-year-old investment banker with Shearson
Lehman Hutton. Observers also noted that she is two months pregnant
and has a 3-year-old son.
   ``I would think her first concern is her health and child,''
Stein said.
   Members of Leland's family have remained in seclusion since the
wreckage of his plane was found Sunday in a remote area of Ethiopa.
   ``She is a very strong young woman, but she has been badly
shaken,'' said the Rev. William Lawson, a family friend. ``All in
all, she has been extremely courageous and she has taken it
extremely well.''
   Gov. Bill Clements has not made a decision on a special election
date. It must be held on or before Nov. 7.
   If Mrs. Leland chose to succeed her husband, she would not be the
first.
   In October 1972, a plane carrying Hale Boggs, a Louisiana
Democrat and then House majority leader, crashed in Alaska. Boggs'
wife, Lindy, was elected to his seat in 1973 and continues to serve.
   If Mrs. Leland chooses not to run for the seat, three Houston
councilmen with ties to Leland are among the most likely candidates,
observers said.
   Rodney Ellis, a former top Leland aide and close friend, was
viewed as the strongest candidate, Stein said. Other potential
aspirants include Anthony Hall, a friend who lost a 1978 runoff
against Leland, and Ben Reyes, another Leland friend who went to
Ethiopia to be close to the search.
   ``Everybody in Houston is reluctant to discuss this, out of
respect for Mickey and his family,'' Carter said. ``But the
practical side is that of the people who have looked at the district
before _ the two named most are Hall and Ellis.''
   Ellis is out of his office this week and has not discussed
running for the seat, said Rhonda Belt, his office coordinator. Hall
said it was inappropriate to comment on a possible race this soon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
