<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Against Yen, Tokyo Shares Up 139 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened higher but fell slightly in
Tuesday afternoon trading against the Japanese yen, while share
prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange firmed.
   The dollar opened at 142.40 yen, up 0.47 yen from Monday's close
of 141.93 yen, and moved between 142.20 yen and 142.70 yen. It
finished at 142.20 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which declined
41.34 points Monday, added 139.07 points, or 0.40 percent, to close
at 34,810.69.
   ``There was no market-affecting news'' this morning, said a
foreign exchange dealer at The Dai-ichi Kangyo Bank.
   He said the Bank of Japan had intervened during the morning
session but with little effect.
   ``The dollar is robust,'' but should not rise over 144 yen, he
said.
   The dealer predicted the market would not fluctuate much the rest
of the week, which is a holiday for many market participants.
   The stock exchange firmed in the morning session, even though the
volume of transactions was only 200 million shares, said a trader at
Nomura Securities, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``High-tech stocks and steels were the focus'' of this morning's
trading, he said.
   High-tech ``is very important to Japanese future growth. As for
steels, they are very important for infrastructure expansion and
should be bought in large amounts, but until now they were being
sold cheaply,'' he said.
   He also said machine issues such as Yamatake-Honeywell firmed on
a report in the economic newspaper Nihon Keizai Shimbun that said
orders for machine tools had increased 30 percent the first six
months of this year.
