<FIRST>r a PM-RapeRecant-Chronology     08-15 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Recant-Chronology,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Rape Recant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of key events in the case of
Gary Dotson, cleared Monday of rape and aggravated kidnapping
charges.
   
   _July 9, 1977: Cathleen Crowell, 16, of suburban Homewood is
found by police, her body cut and clothes ripped. She later
identifies Gary Dotson as the man who raped her.
   _May 24, 1979: A Circuit Court jury in suburban Markham finds
Dotson guilty of rape and aggravated kidnapping after Miss Crowell
testifies that he was her attacker.
   _July 12, 1979: Circuit Judge Richard Samuels sentences Dotson to
25 to 50 years in prison.
   _March 26, 1985: Dotson's accuser, now Cathleen Crowell Webb, 23,
of Jaffery, N.H., files an affidavit saying she had sex with a
17-year-old boyfriend in 1977 and concocted the rape story because
she feared she was pregnant. Warren Lupel, Dotson's attorney, files
a motion asking Samuels to vacate the conviction and free Dotson.
   _May 12: Gov. James R. Thompson commutes Dotson's sentence to
time served but refuses to grant a pardon proclaiming Dotson's
innocence. Dotson is freed.
   1986-87: Dotson arrested several times on charges ranging from
drunken driving to assault, imprisoned for violating parole on
drunken driving conviction.
   Nov. 12, 1987: State appeals panel upholds Dotson's rape
conviction, despite Mrs. Webb's recantation.
   Jan. 7, 1988: Circuit Judge Richard Fitzgerald approves an
agreement that allows genetic tests of evidence in rape case.
   Aug. 17, 1988: Dotson released from prison after serving six
months for parole violation; enters court-ordered alcohol treatment
program.
   July 25, 1989: Fitzgerald rules that the two-year statute of
limitations barring tardy prosecution does not preclude Dotson from
getting a new trial.
   Aug. 14, 1989: Fitzgerald grants Dotson new trial; prosecution
immediately drops all charges against Dotson.
</TEXT>
