<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DNARuling     08-15 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DNA Ruling,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules DNA Test Inadmissible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled that genetic tests linking a
double-murder suspect to a slain pregnant woman and her toddler are
inadmissible as evidence at trial.
   State Supreme Court Justice Gerald Sheindlin on Monday urged
lawyers in previous DNA cases to re-examine their trial records to
see if appeals were warranted on the basis of his opinion, believed
to be the first of its kind.
   Genetic tests have been used in at least 80 cases of rape and
murder in 27 states.
   Sheindlin found that a genetic testing company, Lifecodes Corp.,
had failed to properly perform DNA tests.
   The tests were ordered after Joseph Castro, who is charged with
killing a pregnant woman and her 2-year-old daughter, told police in
a statement that blood found on his wristwatch was his.
   Experts witnesses concluded that the blood on the watch was not
Castro's blood, but said the tests showing the blood was that of the
slain woman were not conducted properly.
   Sheindlin said the flaws made the Lifecodes test inadmissible as
evidence.
   ``The testing laboratory failed in several major respects to use
the generally accepted scientific techniques and experiments for
obtaining reliable results, within a reasonable degree of scientific
certainty,'' the judge said.
   Ed McCarthy, a spokesman for District Attorney Robert Johnson in
the Bronx borough, said the prosecution conceded there was a flaw in
the testing.
   Vilma Ponce and her daughter were murdered on Feb. 5, 1987. A
trial date has been set for Sept. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890815-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     08-15 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Valdez Moving Into Drydock For Nine Months Of Repairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Operation scheduled to begin at 7 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers will get their first look at the
damaged hull of the Exxon Valdez after the crippled tanker goes into
drydock for a nine-month repair job.
   The Exxon Valdez was scheduled to be moved during the afternoon
high tide today from Pier 6 at the National Steel and Shipbuilding
Co. to the dock from which it was launched in 1986, said NASSCO
spokeswoman Debby Torbol.
   Actual repairs were likely to begin in September, because it will
take time to remove water from the repair dock so the ship can be
examined in detail.
   ``I suspect there will be a two-week period in which the only
people in there will be lawyers and engineers,'' said NASSCO senior
vice president Al Lutter.
   Repair costs are estimated at $25 million, but the shipyard's
director of support services, Dick Grothen, said the price tag could
change after a thorough inspection of the damage.
   Dockmaster Frank Russell, a veteran of more than 40 dockings,
said he will coordinate the vessel's movement by using up to eight
tugs while monitoring the tanker's position through a team of divers
and surveying instruments.
   The 166-foot wide Valdez, which spilled about 11 million gallons
of crude in Alaskan waters when it hit a reef March 24 in Prince
William Sound, must squeeze inside a dock with just three feet of
clearance.
   ``It's the first time NASSCO has done this,'' Russell said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. officials have said they plan to return the
987-foot-long tanker to service, possibly under a different name,
after repairs are completed.
   Nearly one-third of the ship's bottom either is gone or has been
severely weakened, and 24 brackets had to be welded to the hull so
the tanker wouldn't collapse under its own weight in drydock.
   After being towed 2,000 miles from Prince William Sound, the
Exxon Valdez waited offshore for three weeks after officials
detected oil slicks around it. Before the ship could navigate the
42-foot-deep channel of San Diego Bay, divers removed massive steel
slabs that dangled from the hull as far as 70 feet below the surface.
   The ship finally arrived at NASSCO on July 31.
   Though booms have remained in place since then to contain
possible spills, NASSCO officials say no discharges or slicks have
appeared.
</TEXT>
