<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianRuling     08-15 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Ruling,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Judge Rules Judges Retain Fishing Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of the Abenaki Indians said a
judge's decision to grant the group fishing rights is one step
toward winning back land claimed by the tribe.
   ``This victory is for fishing rights,'' said tribal chief Homer
St. Francis. ``Now we'll be fighting for our land.''
   The ruling by Vermont District Judge Joseph Wolchik recognized
the Abenaki's aboriginal fishing rights dating back 11,000 years.
   It dismissed fish and game violations filed two years ago by the
state against several tribe members. The state contended the
tribespeople had no right to fish without the state license required
of other people.
   The Abenakis number about 2,500 and live primarily in
northwestern Vermont.
   Wolchik said the state failed to prove the tribe ``abandoned or
ceded their Missisquoi homeland or that their aborginal rights were
extinguished by either an express act or an act clearly and
unambiguously implying any sovereign's intent to extinguish those
rights.
   ``Accordingly, the Missisquoi's aborginal right to fish in their
Missisquoi homeland continues to exist today,'' he wrote.
   Although the ruling dealt only with the issue of fishing rights,
Gabor Rona, the tribe's lawyer said ``what makes this so monumental
for the Abenakis is that the issues the court needed to address and
did address in this fishing case are precisely the same as would be
addressed in a land claim.''
   But it was not clear whether the special status that Wolchik
granted the tribe would translate into anything more than the right
to fish.
   The judge found the Abenakis do not meet the federal definition
of a dependent Indian community, a finding that could impact any
future land claims.
   ``The available evidence leads this court to conclude that
neither the Missisquoi homeland or any part of it is Indian
country,'' the judge said. ``The thrust of the evidence is that the
Missiquoi community is thoroughly mixed if not blended into the
non-native American community.''
   Andrew Eschen, an assistant attorney general, said that while the
Abenakis had contested the state's criminal jurisdiction over the
tribe, Wolchik found the state does have jurisdiction.
   St. Francis said he would push, through the United Nations, for
total autonomy for the tribe.
   The Abenakis trace their tribe back to 9300 B.C. In recent
decades they have begun pushing to assert their right over land in
northern Vermont.
   The fight has split the tribe itself, with one faction favoring
more militant stands such as tribal courts, schools and law
enforcement. That faction, led by St. Francis, is in power today.
   The case originated in 1987, when Abenakis held a fish-in on the
banks of the Missisquoi River in Swanton. More than 30 people were
charged with fishing without a license or failure to display a
license.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890815-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     08-15 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Student, Priest Detained After Crossing Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities took into custody today a
South Korean student and a New York-educated Korean priest who
crossed the border from North Korea to dramatize national
unification efforts.
   Twenty-year-old Im Su-kyong, nicknamed ``The Flower of
Unification,'' held the hand of the Rev. Moon Gyu-hyon as they
crossed the border at Panmunjom, officials said.
   Ms. Im and Moon were taken into immediate custody and flown to
Seoul by police helicopter, where she was reportedly sneaked into
Seoul National University Hospital for a check-up and is expected
later today to be turned over to the national intelligence agency.
   The hospital would not confirm the report, but it was ringed by
riot police who blocked the entrance of reporters. The priest was
under arrest, officials said.
   Government officials said Ms. Im and the priest would be charged
with violating national security laws for making illegal trips to an
enemy country.
   The two were detained by South Korean officers assigned to the
U.N. Command as soon as they walked across the border at Panmunjom,
the truce village in the demilitarized zone separating the two
Koreas, officials said.
   The United Nations, a signatory to the 1953 Korean Armistice that
ended their bloody war, has jurisdiction over the southern half of
the truce village.
   Speaking to a rally of about 70 people in the northern sector of
Panmunjom, Ms. Im said her return across the border was intended to
promote the re-unification of the Korean peninsula, divided since
1945, the officials said.
   ``I hope my act will contribute to advance the unification of
South and North Korea,'' she was quoted as saying. ``Korea is one
forever and we must work to unify our fatherland.''
   North Korean news reports received in Tokyo said the South Korean
radical student was cheered by tens of thousands of people today
when she left the border town of Kaesong for the truce village.
   ``Taking into consideration the firm determination of Ms. Im to
return to South Korea with ardent desire for unification, our side
decided to open the door of our area at Panmunjom and will
thoroughly guarantee their safety,'' the North Korean reports said.
   In Seoul, about 1,000 people, including about a dozen foreigners,
marched in downtown Seoul shouting ``Drive out Yankees who block
unification'' and ``Safe passage for Miss Im _ the unification
flower!''
   South Korean officials said about 3,000 riot police were deployed
along the road leading to Panmunjom to block a possible attempt by
radical students and dissidents to march to the border.
   In a speech marking Korea's liberation from Japan, President Roh
Tae-woo asked that the communist North immediately resume all
channels of suspended dialogue.
   ``North Korea must realize that the only thing they can gain by
agitating the extremists and radicals within our society and by
enticing a few of them to secretly visit Pyongyang is the abhorrence
of our people,'' Roh said.
   Dialogue between the two Koreas has been sporadic but meetings
have been held the last year in an effort to improve relations. The
talks, however, bogged down after secret trips to the North by a
South Korean dissident clergyman, a lawmaker and the student, Ms. Im.
</TEXT>
