<FIRST>r a PM-McCoySentencing     08-15 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCoy Sentencing,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sentence for Robber-Killer-Counterfeiter Off the Charts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man found guilty of murder,
counterfeiting, and West Virginia's largest bank heist had been
convicted only once before this summer, but the courts decided he
was no stranger to crime.
   Judges on Monday bypassed a federal act under which John P. McCoy
could have been eligible for leniency and gave him the stiffest
sentence in the memory of prosecutors in southern West Virginia.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Haden II sentenced McCoy to life in
prison plus 43 years on robbery, murder, jail escape and
murder-for-hire charges.
   ``Mr. McCoy is certainly one of the most, if not the most,
dangerous criminal in the district,'' U.S. Attorney Michael Carey
said. ``There are other people who have had the potential, but he's
the one who had it all come up in the same summer.''
   McCoy, 43, was convicted in June of staging West Virginia's
largest bank robbery and with killing a federal witness.
   In July, he and his girlfriend were found guilty in a
counterfeiting plot that made $800,000 in bad bills.
   This month, he and three others were convicted in a jail-escape
and murder-for-hire scheme.
   ``He told preposterous stories to three separate juries. He's a
pathological liar,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Ben Bryant.
``There's no act that this man wouldn't do. This man should set no
foot in public for the rest of his life.''
   Federal Judge Robert Staker, who handled the counterfeiting
trial, imposed a nine-year sentence to run concurrent with Haden's
penalty. McCoy, of Slater's Branch, Ky., was fined a total of
$262,500.
   The McCoy case challenged the limits of the Sentencing Guidelines
Act of 1987, established to help trim jail populations and grant
leniency to newcomers to the world of crime.
   McCoy, with only a 1982 mail fraud conviction behind him, began
the summer eligible for leniency under the guidelines.
   The sentence imposed by Haden is the stiffest in memory in
southern West Virginia, Carey said. The district doesn't have
complete records on sentencings.
   McCoy maintained his innocence and claimed Bryant had a vendetta
against him because he used legal knowledge gained in prison to help
others.
   In addition to robbing the Matewan National Bank branch at
Kermit, McCoy was convicted of intimidating federal witnesses and of
killing Russell Davis, an accomplice in the robbery, in 1987.
   Co-conspirator Harold D. ``Boonie'' Runyon, 39, of Forest Hill,
Ky., pleaded guilty to the killing and testified for the government
against McCoy. Runyon was sentenced last month to life plus five
years.
   McCoy and his girlfriend, Debbie Farley, 36, used a color
photocopying maching to make what federal agents said were
relatively poor copies of U.S. and Canadian currency.
   McCoy and three others, including his 21-year-old son, Kennis,
were convicted two weeks ago of hiring a man to kill witnesses and
family members. No one was killed or injured. McCoy also was
convicted of concocting a jail-escape plot that failed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
