<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     08-15 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alligator-like reptile took a stroll in
this Los Angeles neighborhood, giving neighbors a jolt before
authorities provided gator aid by roping it.
   Los Angeles County sheriff's deputies got a report of a roaming
reptile on Monday and arrived to find a 3{-foot caiman, a type of
Central or South American crocodile similar to an alligator, Deputy
Chris Wahla said.
   ``The alligator was busily walking northbound on Clovis Avenue
approaching the intersection of 130th Street,'' he said.
   With rope supplied by a neighbor, deputies Allen Sarpy and
Richard Lucas lassoed the caiman, Wahla said.
   The deputies kept a tight rein on the crocodile for 20 minutes
until animal control officers showed up and took it to an animal
shelter. Wahla said he doubted the owner would step forward to claim
it.
   ``Animal control said the caiman variety was illegal to possess
in the United States,'' the deputy said.
</TEXT>
