<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Strikes     08-15 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Blasts Baltics for `Nationalist Hysteria'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Communist Party daily Pravda today
blasted extremists and growing ``nationalist hysteria'' in the
Baltic region for labor unrest that is now its seventh day in
Estonia.
   ``Openly anti-Soviet groups have become activized'' in the three
Baltic republics and ``a situation is building up of nationalist
hysteria,'' the newspaper said in an unsigned commentary.
   In two other Soviet areas threatened by labor unrest, the
Caucasus republics of Georgia and Azerbaijan, officials said today
that all was quiet.
   Estonia's Communist Party chief called Monday for Russian workers
in his tiny republic to end the strike and negotiate differences.
   But in the Estonian capital of Tallinn, strike committee member
Mikhail Lysenko said today that thousands of Russian workers at
about 50 factories stayed off the job to protest a new law that
tightens residency requirements for voters and candidates.
   Pravda aimed its criticism at the law rather than the strikers,
saying ``the passage of discriminatory acts has an extremely
destabilizing influence on the political situation.''
   Pravda's comments reflected Moscow's unease with the grassroots
nationalist movements that have swept the Baltic republics of
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
   The movements, known as People's Fronts, have moved from focusing
on support for President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms to ``narrow
nationalist positions,'' Pravda said.
   It complained that the fronts had taken to attacking the
Communist Party for neglecting the interests of non-Russian
populations, and that ``certain forces'' were pushing for complete
secession from the Soviet Union.
   Pravda also criticized the Baltic movements for sending
emissaries around the country to spread their ideas, and ``using
foreign ties more and more often for the same destructive goals.''
   It proposed political dialogue as the only means of defusing the
situation.
   Estonian party chief Vaino Vyalyas said Monday that dialogue had
not succeeded in resolving the strike, but that he was not ready to
give up.
   ``We met with strike committee representatives and they later
said they were not satisfied with the results. If so, let's continue
the talks,'' Vyalyas said in an Estonian television interview.
   State-run Moscow Radio said the Estonian law will take the right
to vote away from more than 100,000 non-Estonians in the republic of
1.6 million people.
   The new law limits voting to residents who have lived in the same
district for two years, or anywhere in Estonia for five years.
Candidates must live in the same place for five years, or in Estonia
for 10 years.
   Vyalyas admitted the rights of Estonia's minorities _ whom he did
not identify but presumably including Russians _ had not been taken
into account. ``This is our mistake and it must be corrected,'' he
said.
   Estonians say residence requirements for voters and candidates
are legitimate measures used around the world.
   But one strike leader said if Americans had a similar law, they
would have to wait five years to be able to vote after moving from
one state to another.
   The strike has already cost millions of dollars, Moscow Radio
said.
   The striking Russians, most of whom work in heavy industrial
plants, also object to a new national decision to give Estonia free
rein over its economy. The workers are demanding that factories with
a predominantly Russian-speaking labor force remain the property of
the national government rather than be handed over to Estonia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
