<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0543EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BattleshipExplosion-Truitt     08-15 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battleship Explosion-Truitt,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Seeks Payment of Insurance Policy Held By USS Iowa Shipmate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy petty officer has filed suit to
collect the $100,000 life insurance benefit of a shipmate who died
as a result of the April 19 gun-turret blast aboard the USS Iowa.
   The lawsuit filed Monday in U.S. District Court in Miami seeks
payment of a $50,000 double-indemnity policy to Kendall Truitt from
Amex Life Assurance Co. of San Rafael, Calif., according to Ellis
Rubin of Miami, Truitt's attorney.
   Truitt, now stationed at Mayport Naval Station near Jacksonville,
is the sole beneficiary of the policy held by his fellow gunners
mate, Clayton Hartwig, one of 47 sailors killed in the Iowa
explosion.
   The life insurance company has refused to pay the claim on
Hartwig's death until the Navy completes its investigation into the
accident, Rubin said.
   ``They are waiting for the Navy's report and they said the Navy
is indicating they have circumstantial evidence that it might have
been a suicide,'' Rubin said.
   Amex, a division of American Express, would not comment on the
lawsuit.
   Amex had two months to pay the benefit from the filing of the
loss, which occurred June 12, Rubin said.
   ``I think they will settle with us as soon as the Navy report
does not reach the conclusion there was a suicide, and it won't,''
Rubin said.
   ``We are very upset that the Navy report is taking so long to
come out. Either the Navy is planning a whitewash or a coverup, I
don't know which of the two. That's why it is taking so long,''
Rubin said.
   News reports after the explosion indicated that investigators,
suspicious of the life insurance policy, at one point were focusing
on Truitt. But Rubin said in June that Naval Investigative Service
agents had apologized to his client for news leaks suggesting that
Truitt was involved in the explosion.
   Last month, NBC News reported that the Navy had determined that
the explosion aboard the Iowa was the result of sabotage by a
suicidal sailor.
   NBC said the Navy investigation reached that decision after
ruling out mechanical malfunctions, accidental detonation,
electrical flaws and all other technical causes for the explosion.
   Navy spokesman Lt. Greg Smith said July 19 that the conclusion of
suicide ``was not based on official reports of the Navy.''
</TEXT>
