<FIRST>r a PM-EmergencyLanding     08-15 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emergency Landing,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Lands Safely After Mobile Phone Sets Off Smoke Detector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An incoming call to a mobile phone in
luggage aboard a commuter plane apparently triggered a smoke alarm,
forcing the pilot to make an emergency landing, a federal official
said.
   The Express Airlines I plane carrying seven passengers and two
crew members landed without incident Monday and no one was injured,
said Bob Spencer, a Federal Aviation Administration supervisor at
Port Columbus International Airport.
   The Columbus-to-Milwaukee flight was about three miles outside
Columbus when a detector light was activated, indicating smoke in
the baggage area, Spencer said.
   The pilot of the twin-engine, turbo-prop plane radioed the
airport about 5:30 p.m. and emergency vehicles were called out to
the runway, he said.
   After the plane landed, the crew discovered a cellular telephone
in a passenger's suitcase, and determined a call had caused the
problem, Spencer said.
   The flight continued to Milwaukee after the telephone was shut
off, Spencer said.
   Express Airlines I, based in Memphis, Tenn., operates the plane
under a marketing agreement with Northwest Airlines.
</TEXT>
