<FIRST>r a PM-Marine-AIDS     08-15 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine-AIDS,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine With AIDS Suing Navy for Medical Malpractice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine has filed a $55 million suit against the
U.S. Navy charging that malpractice forced his wife to have a blood
transfusion that left her infected with AIDS, which she passed on to
him and their son.
   Martin Gaffney, 40, a chief warrant officer at the South Weymouth
Naval Air Station, contends that Navy doctors mishandled his wife's
pregnancy in 1981, resulting in a stillbirth and the need for a
transfusion.
   At the time, little was known about AIDS, and donated blood was
not routinely screened for the virus. But Gaffney's suit, which is
scheduled to go to trial Aug. 21 in federal court, says the
transfusion would not have been needed had doctors properly treated
his wife, Mutsuko.
   Mrs. Gaffney died of AIDS in 1987, shortly after the lawsuit was
filed. The Gaffneys' son, Johnny, was born with AIDS and died in
1986 at the age of 13 months.
   The only member of the family to be spared infection was their
6-year-old daughter, Maureene. Gaffney himself has tested positive
for the virus, although he has not yet shown any symptoms.
   Marianne Bowler, an assistant U.S. attorney who is representing
the Navy, declined to comment on the case.
   Gaffney's attorney, Jaclyn McKenney, said Navy investigators
traced one of the units of blood that Mutsuko Gaffney received to a
discharged Marine.
   A deposition from the blood donor, identified as ``John Doe'' in
court records, shows he has refused to be tested for AIDS because he
fears the result might prevent him from getting jobs and health
insurance.
   Mrs. Gaffney was under the care of doctors at Long Beach Naval
Hospital in California when she delivered the stillborn baby four
weeks overdue. The doctors had declined to induce labor earlier or
to perform a caesarian section to deliver the baby, the lawsuit says.
</TEXT>
