<HEAD>Israeli Jets Buzz Palestinian Refugee Camps Outside Sidon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police saying Israeli jets buzzed
Palestinian camps, details. Mieh Mieh cq in 4th graf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes buzzed Palestinian
refugee camps near this southern port today, drawing heavy
anti-aircraft fire from guerrillas, police reported.
   The Moslem Voice of the Nation radio in Beirut earlier reported
the Israeli fighter-bombers hit targets near Sidon, 25 miles south
of Beirut.
   But a police spokesman in Sidon, who cannot be named under
standing regulations, said the Israeli jets ``did not attack.''
   The spokesman said two Israeli jet fighters flew at ``a very low
altitude'' over the Ein el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh camps on the city's
eastern edge at 12:15 p.m. (4:15 a.m. EDT).
   Guerrillas in the sprawling shantytowns opened up on the jets
with twin-barrelled anti-aircraft guns, but no hits were observed
when the jets made a single pass over the camps.
   Witnesses in Sidon said the Israeli action triggered panic in the
city. Several motorists jumped from their vehicles and took cover in
bomb shelters, entrances to buildings and fields.
   The Israeli air force has carried out nine raids this year
against targets in Lebanon, including Sidon's refugee camps. Eight
people have been killed and 67 wounded in the air strikes.
