<FIRST>r a PM-LoggingProtests     08-15 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Logging Protests,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Climb Trees Across Nation to Protest Forest Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental activists from Massachusetts to
California took to the treetops to voice their opposition to logging
in the country's remaining virgin timberlands.
   Protesters set up camps in trees to coincide with the first of
four hearings by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service on its proposal
to list the northern spotted owl as a threatened species.
   Environmentalists say the owl requires old-growth forests for its
habitat; the forest-products industry says many logging and mill
jobs would be lost if the owl is protected by setting aside forest
in protected zones.
   ``This is obviously spotted owl week throughout the Northwest,''
said Darryl Cherney, an Earth First! spokesman involved in the
protests near Ukiah, Calif. ``The timber crisis is culminating to
such an extent right now, that now's the time'' for action.
   Earth First!, known for putting spikes in trees to discourage
logging, said its ``aerial occupations'' had protesters sitting on
3-by-6-foot platforms suspended in trees. They were equipped with
food, water and other gear, and supported by ground crews, Cherney
said.
   The protests began Sunday or Monday in Washington, Oregon,
California, Colorado, New Mexico and Massachusetts, Cherney said.
Others were planned in British Columbia, Georgia and Montana. Some
protesters said they were prepared to stay in the trees for weeks.
   Jay Ward, 31, lodged himself 50 feet high in an evergreen outside
U.S. Sen. Mark Hatfield's office in Portland, Ore. He said he had
enough food and water to last at least four days.
   Portland was the site Monday of the first hearing, at which a top
official in the U.S. Forest Service said the spotted owl can survive
without being listed as a threatened species under federal wildlife
protection law.
   Hal Salwasser, deputy director for wildlife and fisheries, said
his agency is managing timberlands with the aim of ensuring the
owl's long-term survival.
   Although the hearings were supposed to center on the biological
concerns of the owl, many loggers testified about the economic
consequences they feared if logging is restricted. Federal judges
already have halted timber sales in the region because of lawsuits
filed by environmentalists.
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm scared to death,'' said Scott Hall
as he held his 3-year-old son, Adam, in his arms. Hall, a
superintendent for High Cascade Lumber in Skamania County, Wash.,
said his mill is expected to run out of logs _ and jobs _ in
November.
   Cherney said the demonstrations were not just about the spotted
owl, but included concerns over forest resources in general.
   ``If someone's sitting in a second-growth tree our message is:
Let some of these second-growth forests become old-growth forests,''
he said.
   In Washington's Mount Baker-Snoqualmie National Forest, three
demonstrators climbed trees in the Goodman Ridge timber sale in an
attempt to stop logging, said Janine Blaeloch, an Earth First!
spokeswoman in Seattle.
   Gary Cordova, a Forest Service spokesman in Portland, said he
knew of no agency policy for dealing with such protests and that
decisions were made at the scene.
   ``We don't want to violate anyone's constitutional rights to free
expression, but we also want to guarantee ... that logging
operations are able to continue,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
