<HEAD>Democrats Square Off For Nomination to Replace Claude Pepper</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1 and 2 to RESTORE dropped word `years' and CORRECT
that Kennedy is former sted current commissioner; picks up 3rd graf, `Richman
defeated ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats in the district Claude Pepper represented
for 27 years hoped to emerge from today's primary runoff with a
candidate strong enough to defend the U.S. House seat against a
formidable Republican opponent.
   Dade County Elections Supervisor David Leahy predicted about 15
percent of the 18th District's 100,198 registered Democrats would
vote in the special runoff election pitting former city commissioner
Rosario Kennedy and attorney Gerald Richman.
