<FIRST>r a PM-Kidnap-Slaying     08-15 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kidnap-Slaying,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnapping Suspect Turns Himself In, Police Arrest Him in Mother's
Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDINER, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect was charged with murder and
kidnapping for allegedly beating a man in his home, abducting his
wife and two small children and leaving the children near the
women's body in a wooded area, police said.
   Byron Raynes, 21, was charged after turning himself in to police
in Greenville, 110 miles north of Augusta. He was flown to Augusta
late Monday and was being held in the Kennebec County Jail awaiting
District Court arraignment today or Wednesday, state police
spokesman Randy Nichols said.
   Authorities said family members identified the dead woman as Peg
Shaw, 35.
   The state medical examiner's office scheduled an autopsy for
Monday night, but the findings were not immediately available,
Nichols said.
   Nichols identified her husband as John Shaw, who is employed at
the Augusta Mental Health Institute. The couple's children _ son,
Sam, 3, and daughter, Julia, 1 _ were reunited with their father,
police said.
   Police declined to say if Raynes knew the family or if any motive
for the crime had been established.
   Before he turned himself in, police had put out an all-points
bulletin for Raynes. Nichols refused to say whether there was any
evidence in the Shaw's home in the Augusta suburb of Gardiner
linking Raynes to the assault.
   Raynes has longstanding family ties in Gardiner, where he was
living with his parents, Nichols said. He was employed by an
electrical contractor in the Augusta area, he said.
   At about 6:30 a.m. Monday, an assailant entered the Shaw's home,
striking John Shaw in the head with a wooden mallet and handcuffing
him in the basement, Nichols said.
   About an hour later, neighbors heard Shaw screaming for help, he
said. Police were called and as they were questioning Shaw, the
family's van drove past the house, he said.
   ``We feel at that point that the suspect was alone,'' Nichols
said.
   Police soon found the van abandoned at some railroad tracks in
Gardiner, Nichols said.
   Early in the afternoon, a state police trooper noticed some
tracks coming from a muddy road in South Gardiner. Nearby, the
trooper found the woman's body and her two children huddled together
nearby.
   During the day, police used an airplane and boats on the Kennebec
River in their search for the suspect, Nichols said.
   Authorities also had set up roadblocks on U.S. 201 in the area,
Gardiner Deputy Police Chief Craig Marshall said.
</TEXT>
