<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WhyBitter?     08-15 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Why Bitter?,0320</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Bitterness May Be Natural Poison Alarm, Taste Expert Says ^By MALCOLM
RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ability to taste bitterness may be a
natural defense against poisoning, says a prominent taste researcher.
   For one thing, bitterness and toxicity tend to appear together
strikingly often, although there are exceptions, said Linda
Bartoshuk of Yale University.
   For another, scientists have found that the tongue contains more
than one kind of sensor to detect bitterness, she said. That would
make sense if the system were set up to detect multiple types of
poisons, she said.
   Bartoshuk discussed research in taste Monday at the annual
meeting of the American Psychological Association.
   Bitterness and sweetness are detected when substances bind to
specialized proteins, while saltiness and sourness are sensed in a
different way, she said.
   She demonstrated the multiple types of bitterness detectors by
having audience members taste postage-stamp-sized squares of paper
impregnated with a substance called 6-n-propylthiouracil. About half
the audience tasted it as bitter. The other half sensed no taste at
all.
   Yet everybody in the audience could have tasted the bitterness of
quinine, Bartoshuk said. So the two kinds of bitterness are picked
up by different sensing proteins, she said.
   The ability to taste the chemical on the paper is determined
genetically, she said. About two-thirds of the general population
are ``tasters'' on this test, she said.
   Tasters find Swiss cheese more bitter than non-tasters do, she
said. They also perceive sugar placed on the front of the tongue to
be twice as sweet as non-tasters do, she said.
   Non-tasters find caffeine less bitter, and so are not likely to
notice the difference between regular and decaffeinated coffee, she
said.
   Just what difference the responsible genes make in the taste buds
is not clear, but perhaps tasters have some bitterness-sensing
proteins that non-tasters lack, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
