<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0427 08-15 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Stage Strike; At Least 28 Killed This Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with strike beginning, more deaths.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, `The posters...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers drove public buses to get
workers to offices today at the start of a daylong strike called by
Sinhalese radicals protesting the continuing deployment of Indian
troops in Sri Lanka.
   Shops in Colombo were closed and hundreds of employees began
returning home because most offices and businesses were not
functioning. Soliders in camouflage uniforms patrolled the city and
policemen were posted at major intersections and near bus stops.
   At least seven people were killed by Sinhalese radicals today and
Monday, according to military officials. The officials, who cannot
be identified under briefing rules, said the victims included two
soldiers ambushed early today in the central town of Nuwara Eliya.
   The other killings were in the Sinhalese-dominated south, they
said.
   The strike coincides with the 42nd anniversary of India's
independence from Britain. At least two Colombo-based newspapers
refused to carry special supplements to mark the occasion, sources
in the dailies said on condition of anonymity.
   The call for the strike came in posters signed by the National
Worker's Federation, which the government describes as a radical
group.
   The posters in the Sinhalese language denounced the presence of
an estimated 43,000 Indian soldiers, deployed in the northeast to
oversee a 1987 peace accord aimed at ending a Tamil insurrection for
an independent nation.
   The ultra-nationalist front says the Indian troops compromise the
country's sovereignty. It also says the government has made too many
concessions to the Tamil militants, who began their separatist
campaign in 1983.
   The Tamils argue they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese,
who comprise 75 percent of the population. Tamils are 18 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa on June 1 asked India to withdraw
its soldiers, but so far India has pulled out only 2,200 troops and
the results have failed to appease the extremists.
   India has said a quick withdrawal of troops could lead to more
violence but that it will withdraw soldiers in phases, pulling them
all out by February.
   Sinhalese extremists have killed at least 4,000 people over the
past two years, according to the government. About 11,000 other
people have died in the 6-year-old Tamil revolt.
</TEXT>
