<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Corruption     08-15 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Corruption,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Policewoman Executed for Taking Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have executed a policewoman in Canton
for taking tens of thousands of dollars in bribes, official reports
said today.
   Major state newspapers and television reports said the
policewoman, Zhang Mayun, took bribes worth $56,150 in exchange for
allowing people to remain in the southern city illegally.
   She was sentenced to death on June 19, but the reports did not
say exactly when she was executed. Death sentences in China are
usually carried out within a day or two with a bullet to the back of
the head.
   In another report, the English-language China Daily said
authorities had received 172,000 tips from informants at corruption
reporting centers from January to June. The centers are part of a
major government anti-corruption drive.
   The reports mentioned three pending cases of officials also
accused of taking bribes.
   About 22,000 officials were accused of wrongdoing by the
informants.
