<FIRST>r a PM-DrugAgentSlain     08-15 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Agent Slain,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brother-In-Law of Former Mexican President Held in Camarena Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of former Mexican President
Luis Echeverria was held without bail today as a witness in the 1985
torture-murder of a U.S. drug agent.
   Ruben Zuno-Arce was flown from Texas to Los Angeles on Monday and
ordered held pending a hearing next Monday.
   Investigators believe he has information about the slaying of
Enrique Camarena, according to papers filed by the Drug Enforcement
Administration.
   Camarena and his pilot were kidnapped and slain after the DEA
agent led a series of damaging raids on marijuana plantations
allegedly run by reputed Mexican drug lord Rafael Caro-Quintero.
   Zuno-Arce, whose sister is the wife of Echeverria, Mexico's
president from 1970 to 1976, was arrested Wednesday night in San
Antonio by U.S. immigration agents as he tried to cross into Mexico.
An inspector recognized Zuno-Arce as one of those on a list of
suspected drug traffickers, authorities said.
   Jeremiah Handy, Zuno-Arce's lawyer, said he knows the Mascota,
Mexico, resident as a successful dealer in lumber and vegetables,
with no history of drug trafficking.
   Zuno-Arce does not know Caro-Quintero ``except as a name in the
paper like anyone else,'' Handy said. He called the unusual no-bail
order ``a government tactic to in fact hammer on him, put him in
jail and cause grief to his family.''
   Camarena's slaying strained U.S.-Mexican relations, and the DEA
has vowed to bring in every person involved in the murders. Several
members of the Mexican federal police force were linked to the
killings. One was convicted last year.
   Eight more men are charged with murder and conspiracy in the
case, including Caro-Quintero, who is in custody awaiting trial in
Mexico City.
   Camarena and his pilot are believed to have been killed at
Caro-Quintero's home in Guadalajara. Zuno-Arce formerly owned the
home, according to his arrest warrant. The agent's body was found on
a ranch 65 miles from Guadalajara.
</TEXT>
