<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Hit Kabul Airport, Injuring Soldier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barrage of rockets crashed down on
the capital's airport today, injuring a soldier, forcing passengers
to scurry for cover and disrupting flights, airport officials said.
   Such attacks on Kabul, which have occurred almost daily since
late June, have been blamed by the government on U.S.-backed
guerrillas. The guerrillas say they attack only military targets.
   Several other rockets also struck other parts of the capital
today, but there was no immediate word on casualties.
   One airport official said nine rockets hit the airport.
   Several struck near the main passenger terminal during busy
morning hours, airport officials said on condition of anonymity.
   They reported one government soldier injured. They said no
passengers were injured and a runway was slightly damaged.
   There was no report of damage to civilian airplanes.
   The airport also has a military section, and it was not known if
anything was damaged there.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said today that
299 rockets had been fired on Kabul in the past four weeks, killing
188 civilians and injuring 483.
   The guerrillas are fighting to overthrow the country's
Soviet-backed Marxist government.
