<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0951EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianBones     08-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Bones,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bones Show Indians Led Harsh Life Under Spaniards But Lived Longer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of the skeletons of 268
Indians buried in the 17th century on Amelia Island shows they were
overworked and underfed by their Spanish masters, scientists say.
   But the researchers are puzzled because the Indians lived longer
than ancestors who were better fed and didn't have to carry burdens
for the Spanish, said Rebecca Saunders, supervisor of the
archaeologists.
   The study of the bones, she said, showed that the Guale and
Yamasee Indians' diets were nutritionally deficient and that they
suffered from arthritis in their vertebrae and feet, indicating they
had carried many heavy loads.
   ``What we have learned from this is that both the Guale men and
women were used as bearers by the Spanish,'' Ms. Saunders said in
Monday's Florida Times-Union in Jacksonville.
   The remains were unearthed at the sites of two mission
graveyards. Excavation began four years ago when a backhoe, clearing
land for a house, uncovered a graveyard.
   Researchers found that many of the Indians lived to what was then
the ripe old age of 40, Ms. Saunders said. The Indians who lived in
the area in the 1400s ate better but rarely reached that age.
   ``It's a contradiction that we have not been able to solve,''
said Ms. Saunders, who is writing a dissertation on the missions for
the University of Florida.
   Ten archaeologists from the university plan to excavate areas
where once stood the house where the Franciscan missionaries lived;
their cookhouse, and a circular structure that might have been part
of the mission village.
   The scientists also will attempt to locate the site of the
mission church.
</TEXT>
