<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     08-15 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Apologizes for Reporting Prime Minister Had Illegitimate
Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper has apologized for reporting that
Toshiki Kaifu, the new prime minister, fathered an illegitimate
child, and it said the story was nothing more than ``groundless
rumors.''
   The Nagoya Times, which is published in Kaifu's central home
district, printed the story Aug. 4 as he was emerging as the most
likely successor to Sousuke Uno.
   Uno resigned after 69 days in office amid allegations he kept
paid mistresses. His predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, quit to take
responsibility for an influence-peddling scandal involving
high-ranking members of the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
   In its apology Monday, The Times said the story originated in a
letter from a reader. The paper said it later investigated the woman
who supposedly had the illegitimate child and found no evidence to
back her claims.
   Kaifu, elected prime minister by Parliament's lower house on
Wednesday, angrily denied the newspaper report. He said he had asked
the paper to apologize and publish a retraction.
   Sueo Ishida, editor of the 140,000-circulation evening newspaper,
told The Associated Press in a telephone interview that the paper's
president, Tadashi Yokouchi, met with Kaifu chief secretary Shozen
Kanaishi in Tokyo on Monday to apologize for the report.
   Ishida said details of the talks were not known, but Kanaishi
accepted the apology.
</TEXT>
