<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Housing     08-15 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Rates, Prices Keep Resales Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High mortgage rates and rising prices continued
to plague sales of existing homes in the second quarter, a real
estate trade group reported today, with 41 states and the District
of Columbia posting declines.
   At the same time, the National Association of Realtors said
booming prices made housing most expensive on the West Coast and the
Northeast in the April-June period.
   The median price of a home in the San Francisco Bay area, the
most expensive market, was $265,700, the Realtors said, compared
with Peoria, Ill., which had the lowest median price of $47,700.
   The median price means half of the houses sold for more and half
for less.
   The Realtors said their quarterly survey of sales of previously
owned homes showed a seasonally adjusted annual resale rate of 3.72
million units, down 3.1 percent from the January-March quarter.
   NAR President Ira Gribin said the sales reflected a lagging
response to drops in interest rates that began in May.
   ``It took some time for the market to turn,'' he said. ``Now, the
people who can afford to get in the market are house-hunting.''
   But Gribin said the survey also indicates that home ownership is
slipping further out of reach for first-time buyers in areas with
expensive housing.
   ``High-cost areas are losing their entry-level market,'' he said,
and in some high-cost markets, mortgage rates are forcing buyers to
purchase less-expensive homes.
   Washington, D.C., was the only area outside of the West Coast and
Northeast ranking near the top of the price list. The nation's
capital had a median price of $139,900.
   Ranked second in the median price list behind San Francisco was
Honolulu, with a price of $265,500, followed by Orange County,
Calif., $247,600; Los Angeles, $218,000; and Boston, $188,600.
   The report said 22 metropolitan areas recorded median prices
exceeding the national median of $92,900 for the second quarter.
Forty-three areas recorded annual median price increases exceeding
the national price increase of 4 percent.
   By region, the West posted an 18.7 percent median price increase
in the second quarter over the April-June quarter of 1988. It was
followed by the Midwest, up 4.9 percent; the South, up 4.6 percent;
and the Northeast, up 3.5 percent.
   The Northeast was the only region to post an increase in sales of
existing homes, up 1.3 percent to an annual rate of 790,000 units,
the Realtors said.
   The West, paced by California, registered a 7.2 percent decrease
to a 640,000 annual pace. California's resale pace, 523,700 units
and highest of all the states, dropped 14.9 percent.
   In the Midwest, sales of existing homes fell 3.1 percent to a
rate of 950,000 units and in the South, they were down 2.9 percent
to a resale pace of 1.35 million units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
