<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceMisconduct     08-15 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Misconduct,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Reinstates Murder Charges Despite Police Misconduct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts' highest court reinstated murder
charges against a man accused of killing a detective, despite what
the justices called ``contemptible and disgusting'' police
misconduct in the case.
   Police cheered the decision Monday by the Supreme Judicial Court
that Albert Lewin can be tried for the 1988 slaying of Sherman
Griffiths. But defense attorneys said the ruling would encourage
police to fabricate evidence.
   Three Boston detectives threw the murder investigation into
turmoil last spring when they admitted they had created a fictitious
informant to obtain a search warrant for the drug raid in which
Griffiths was shot.
   In March, Superior Court Judge Charles M. Grabau dismissed the
murder charge against Lewin, 33, saying police had prevented a fair
trial by repeatedly lying about the informant.
   Writing for the majority in the high court's 4-2 ruling, Justice
Herbert Wilkins said, ``In order to express its outrage at the
reprehensible police conduct in this case, society need not punish
itself by freeing a man who may be guilty of murder in the first
degree and other serious crimes.''
   Wilkins said the ``contemptible and disgusting misconduct by
police officers in blatant violation of their sworn duties'' would
not prevent a fair trial.
   Griffiths, 36, was shot to death as he tried to break in the door
of Lewin's apartment. Lewin has been in jail for more than a year
awaiting trial.
   The three officers who testified about the fictitious informant
have been suspended pending a perjury investigation.
   Police Commissioner Francis M. Roache applauded the court's
decision, saying he was happy for Griffiths' widow that Lewin would
be brought to trial.
   He said Boston police officers ``are ordinary human beings'' who
work under extraordinary pressure.
   A lawyer for Lewin, Patricia Garin, said the ruling ``sets a
precedent for toleration of massive perjury by the police and it
vindicates them in their `anything goes' strategy.''
   Harvey Silverglate, co-chairman of the Massachusetts Association
of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said the decision will ``make it
increasingly likely that police will be allowed to frame innocent
citizens.''
   In two dissents, Chief Justice Paul Liacos and Justice Ruth
Abrams said the majority opinion essentially condoned police
misconduct.
   ``Because of the officers' lies, the defendant languished in jail
while court proceedings continued with what the court has
characterized as `perfidious' police conduct,'' Abrams wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
