<FIRST>r a PM-BeautyFraud     08-15 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beauty Fraud,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Tells of Ordeal at Beauty School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inessa Stateikim had flowing red hair until a
bargain permanent at a beauty college burned her scalp and caused
her hair to fall out in clumps, she testified in a $6 million fraud
trial against the school.
   ``I was bald,'' she told jurors. ``I couldn't stop crying. ... I
stayed home for a year.''
   Ms. Stateikim testified Monday in a federal class-action lawsuit
accusing the D'Or Beauty College of consumer fraud and seeking
damages for 1,404 students who attended D'Or's two schools since
1983.
   The students charge the school with misrepresentation and failing
to provide adequate training. They say few students graduate or pass
the state licensing examination.
   The school has been barred from participating in federal student
aid programs.
   Ms. Stateikim was a student in D'Or's three-month manicurist's
course when she received a permanent in 1984. No supervisor was on
hand, she said.
   Ms. Stateikim said she had to see a doctor for her burning scalp.
She got a wig and became a recluse until her hair grew back.
</TEXT>
