<FIRST>r w PM-Robinette     08-15 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robinette,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Witness in Hospital With Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former CIA operative who was a key figure in
the Iran-Contra trial of Oliver L. North is hospitalized after
suffering a heart attack.
   Glenn Robinette, now a security consultant, said in a telephone
interview today that suffered the attack last Friday and is expected
to remain hospitalized until the weekend.
   Robinette testified at North's trial that he and the former
National Security Council aide created phony documents to disguise
the fact that someone else had paid for a $16,000 security fence at
North's home.
   North was convicted on three counts in the Iran-Contra affair,
including the acceptance of an illegal gratuity _ the fence.
   Robinette, who testified under a grant of immunity, said he
received money for the fence from arms dealer Richard V. Secord.
Secord, who worked with North in the plan to divert money from the
sale of weapons to Iran to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, is
scheduled to go on trial Nov. 13.
</TEXT>
