<FIRST>r a PM-ChildShot     08-15 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Shot,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Shot To Death, Body Stuffed In Friend's Closet Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old boy shot and killed his
best friend and kept the body in his bedroom closet for two days,
authorities say.
   Sheriff's Sgt. John Faile said the slaying of 10-year-old Darrell
Dwayne Dockery may have been an accident.
   Officers began looking for the boy Saturday night and found the
body late Monday, shot once in the side, in the home of his
unidentified friend, who was taken into custody on juvenile charges
of manslaughter and negligent homicide.
   ``They were good friends, always together here or at the other
boy's house,'' said Raymond Boisclair, Dwayne's stepfather. ``But
the whole time we were looking for Dwayne, that boy never called or
offered to help. I thought that was kind of odd.''
   Dwayne was last seen by his family Saturday morning, when he said
he was going to his friend's house two blocks away to see if he
wanted to go fishing.
   Ronnie Bowen, director of the youth aid division of the sheriff's
office, said officers questioned the 13-year-old, who said the
10-year-old had left the house.
   But the older boy came under suspicion because he ``didn't act
like a normal 13-year-old,'' Bowen said. The boy eventually told
officers where to find the body, Bowen said. He said it appeared
Dwayne was shot with a rifle.
   Boisclair said the boys ``never had a fight that we ever heard
them in.''
</TEXT>
