<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Birds     08-15 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Birds,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Birds Freed in Protest Against Bird-catching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of birds captured in the
forests and jungles to be sold as pets were set free Tuesday on
India's Independence Day to dramatize a campaign against cruelty to
animals.
   The freeing of the birds was led by environmental activist Maneka
Gandhi, sister-in-law and political foe of Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi.
   About 500 people watched as the birds were set free along the
Yamuna River at the cremation site of Mohandas K. Gandhi, leader of
the non-violent freedom struggle that culminated in India's
independence from Britain in 1947.
   Mrs. Gandhi, a leading member of the Janata Dal opposition party
that seeks to unseat the prime minister's Congress Party in
elections later this year, called the freeing of the birds ``a
soaring triumph for bird lovers.''
   The birds were bought from dealers with contributions from animal
rescue groups.
</TEXT>
