<HEAD>Algeria's Second-Largest City Quiet After Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police patrolled suburban Constantine,
Algeria's second-largest city, after demonstrators blocked a road
and destroyed public buildings, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The eastern Algerian suburb was calm Tuesday, but police remained
in the village after a day of demonstrations that turned violent
Sunday, according to the daily newspaper El Moudjahid.
   There were no details on the cause of the demonstration or on
injuries or arrests.
   Algeria was rocked last year by violent demonstrations in the
capital brought on by a declining standard of living in the
financially-strapped North African nation. The demonstrations led to
a series of constitutional reforms, a diminishing of the power of
the ruling party and a restructuring of the government of President
Chadli Bendjedid.
 
