<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     08-15 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish-American Activist Arrested for Entering British Province</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American pro-IRA activist
was arrested Tuesday for violating a 5-year-old order barring him
from British territory, police said.
   Lawyer Martin Galvin, publicity director of the New York-based
Irish Northern Aid Committee, or NORAID, was bundled into a police
jeep and driven away after taking a high-profile walk through
Northern Ireland's second-largest city.
   The British government said Galvin would be deported after being
flown to London's Heathrow Airport and handed over to immigration
authorities there.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd ``has no reason to alter his decision
in relation to the exclusion order made in July 1984,'' the Home
Office said. ``As an illegal entrant and the subject of an exclusion
order, Mr. Galvin will be removed from the U.K.''
   Galvin's arrest came only hours after masked rioters marked the
20th anniversary of the arrival of British troops in Northern
Ireland by throwing rocks and homemade bombs at police. Riot squads
fired plastic bullets, slightly injuring two men, police said.
   Galvin, 39, has visited Northern Ireland at least four times
since 1984 despite being under a British exclusion order. He said he
arrived for this latest visit three days ago.
   ``It would have been unconscionable for me not to have been with
the nationalist people on the 20th anniversary of the arrival of the
troops,'' he told reporters.
   The exclusion order against Galvin was signed in July 1984
following a speech at Toomebridge, County Londonderry, in which he
encouraged violence the day after a soldier was killed in
Londonderry.
   A month later, police tried to arrest Galvin when he appeared on
a platform of speakers in west Belfast. Police killed a young man
with a plastic bullet when fighting broke out in the crowd of
thousands of IRA supporters. Galvin was lifted over the heads of
people in the crowd and vanished up a back street.
   The ban is difficult to enforce because movement between Northern
Ireland and the Irish Republic is easy. There are many unpatrolled
roads across the border, no passport requirements and only random
checks of cars.
   In the latest incident, officers grabbed Galvin as he stood with
officials of Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican army's legal political
wing, at Free Derry Corner, a symbol of Irish nationalist resistance
to British rule.
   As he was led away, Galvin shouted: ``This will attract
international attention!''
   Britain says NORAID collects funds to buy arms for the IRA.
Galvin denies this, saying the money goes to families of victims of
20 years of violence in the province.
   Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams called for Galvin's release,
saying the arrest was ``ironic testimony to British repression which
relies upon exclusion orders, the denial of human rights and
censorship, as well as military force to maintain its presence
here.''
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force,
said violence flared early Tuesday in the Bogside, a Roman Catholic
stronghold and scene of some of the worst sectarian violence when
the ``troubles'' broke out 20 years ago.
   Police said one homemade bomb was thrown at an armored car,
rocking the vehicle and breaking windows in nearby homes.
   In north Belfast, a bomb exploded in the Catholic Ardoyne area
and a bus and a car were hijacked and burned.
   In Coalisland, County Tyrone, a crowd of 30 people hurled
gasoline bombs at the town's police station and a bomb exploded at a
gas station in Dungannon, in the center of the province.
   Several thousand IRA supporters marked the 20-year anniversary on
Monday by marching peacefully from Creggan, another Catholic
stronghold, to Bogside. They walked into Londonderry's old walled
city, a Protestant area, and past a building wrecked by an Irish
Republican Army bomb recently.
   The IRA is fighting to unite the province and its Protestant
majority with the predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland under
socialist rule. More than 2,700 people have been killed in 20 years
of fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
