<SECOND>BC-Bush-Glance,360</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are points made by President
Bush at his news conference Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOSTAGES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said has not taken armed or diplomatic retaliation
for the death of hostage Lt. Col. William Higgins in Lebanon because
he does not have enough information to do so. He said diplomatic
efforts are continuing to win freedom for Americans held hostage in
the Middle East but could not give an assessment of how effective
the initiatives have been.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DRUGS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While giving no specifics, Bush said that a new strategy to
combat illegal drugs, to be released next month, is ``balanced,
decisive, effective and achievable.'' He said, ``It will call for
commitment and sacrifice and understanding, but it's clear to me
that the American people demand no less.'' The president said the
government would be spending more money to attack drugs but would do
so without raising taxes. He would not say where the money would
come from.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CONGRESSMEN MOURNED</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush expressed sympathy at the deaths of Reps. Mickey Leland,
D-Texas, and Larkin Smith, R-Miss., who were killed in recent
airplane crashes. ``These two fine individuals represented a deep
caring for the poor, the disadvantaged, the victims of drug abuse
and crime and many other areas of our society that need improving,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>NORIEGA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush repeated his call for the removal of Panamanian leader Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega but admitted he does not look for that to
happen soon. ``I'm not holding my breath on his voluntary
departure,'' he said, refusing to rule out possible abduction of
Noriega to face drug-trafficking indictments in Florida. He also
repeated his support for Guillermo Endara, whom the United States
considers to be the winner of Panama's May 7 presidential election.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>INTEREST RATES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president endorsed the views of his budget director, Richard
Darman, who contended over the weekend that the Federal Reserve was
keeping interest rates too high to permit sustained economic growth.
``I feel very comfortable with his (Darman's) sallying forth,'' Bush
said. ``I think I have said the same things in the past.''
</TEXT>
