<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalDerailment     08-15 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Derailment,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brakeman on Derailed Train Used Cocaine, Feds Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brakeman on a train that derailed and
caught fire July 22, forcing 3,000 people from their homes for up to
a week, had used cocaine sometime in the 48 hours before the
accident, a federal agency says.
   Blood and urine samples provided by the unidentified brakeman
tested positive for the drug, the Federal Railroad Administration
said Monday in a statement. Samples from the engineer and conductor
tested negative.
   The agency did not say how much cocaine the brakeman had used and
said it had not determined exactly when use occurred.
   ``His role in the cause of the accident, if any, has yet to be
determined,'' said agency spokeswoman Claire H. Austin in Washington.
   Austin said the brakeman was in the lead locomotive of the 37-car
CSX Transportation Co. train when 14 cars derailed and caused a
chemical fire. Twelve people were injured.
   Two days later, CSX spokesman R. Lindsay Leckie said, the
brakeman admitted himself to a drug and alcohol rehabilitation
center.
   The National Transportation Safety Board determined that the
first car to derail was an oversized flatbed. Investigators also
discovered worn wheels and brakes and a variety of operating
violations.
</TEXT>
