<FIRST>u i PM-Ethiopia-Leland 1stLd-Writethru a0472 08-15 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Leland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Efforts to Recover Bodies on Ethiopian Mountain Begin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with all 16 bodies recovered. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Leland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of U.S. Rep. Mickey
Leland and the 15 others in his delegation were lifted off a
mountainside in southwestern Ethiopia today, officials said.
   ``We've got them all,'' Air Force Capt. Kevin Krejarck told
reporters in the capital upon his return from Gambela, a town near
the crash site. ``The site has now been cleared.''
   The bodies, lifted one by one from the wreckage by helicopters
hovering near the face of a sheer cliff, were flown to Gambela,
where they were placed aboard an Ethiopian air force C-130 cargo
plane for the return to the capital.
   U.S. Marine Lt. Col. David Titus said the bodies would be
identified in Addis Ababa by a team of U.S. forensic experts, a
process he said could take up to a week.
   Two C-130 Hercules cargo planes carrying rescue teams and fuel
left the capital shortly after dawn for Gambela, about 35 miles
southeast of the crash site, where joined two Blackhawk helicopters
in the operation, said U.S. Embassy spokesman James Haley.
   Heavy clouds, rain and low visibility were believed to have led
to the crash of the Twin Otter carrying Leland, eight other
Americans and seven Ethiopians to the Fugnido refugee camp in
southwestern Ethiopia on Aug. 7.
   Persistent bad weather also slowed the 6-day search as well as
the recovery effort after the twin-engine plane was found Sunday,
and the director of operations said the recovery operation could
take two more days.
   ``The recovery is proving to be extremely difficult because of
slippery rock, thick undergrowth and tall savannah grass,'' Air
Force Maj. Gen. James Record, of the U.S. Central Command, told a
news conference in Addis Ababa Monday night. ``The cliff inclines at
an 80 degree angle.''
   Gambela has served as the recovery coordination base since 12
bodies were found Sunday on the three-quarters the way up the slopes
of a 5,500-foot mountain where the Twin Otter crashed, about 350
miles southwest of Addis Ababa.
   Record said Ethiopia had accepted an offer from the U.S. National
Transportation and Safety Board to participate in an investigation
into the cause of the crash.
   He said a team of experts already was on its way to Ethiopia,
including representatives of the Boeing and Pratt and Whitney
aircraft companies, which manufactured the plane's body and engine.
The aircraft, which carries up to 20 passengers, was built by the
Canadian Boeing subsidiary de Havilland.
   A four-man congressional delegation also planned to fly to
Ethiopia to escort the bodies home but officials have said they will
not leave Washington until the bodies have been identified.
   Leland, 44, was on his fifth visit to Africa and his second this
year when the accident occurred en route to the refugee camp, one of
four in southwestern Ethiopia run by the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees that house more than 300,000 Sudanese fleeing war and
famine in their neighboring country.
   The six-term Texas Democrat was traveling to the camps in his
capacity as chairman of the House Select Committee on Hunger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
