<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Noriega     08-15 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Noriega,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Won't Rule Out Abducting Panamanian Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today refused to rule out
abducting Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to bring him
to trial on drug-trafficking charges, say, ``I have an obligation to
try to bring people to justice.''
   The president also said at a news conference that he has told
Guillermo Endara, who was widely considered the victor in Panama's
May 7 presidential election that ``We will continue to support what
the people of Panama voted for.''
   A senior State Department official said that Bush's vow of
support for Endara did not put the administration at odds with an
Organization of American States agreement to promote new elections
Sept. 1, conditioned on a transfer of power from Noriega's regime to
a transitional government.
   The United States supports that plan, although it continues to
believe that Endara fairly won the election, said the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The president was asked about comments he made in a recent Hearst
Newspapers interview in which he seemed to indicate in answer to a
question that kidnapping would be an acceptable option to bring
Noriega to this country to face a federal indictments in Florida.
   Asked today if kidnapping would be appropriate, Bush said:
   ``We have an indictment out against General Noriega for drug
trafficking. I'm told that it's a good indictment ... I'm not saying
what I would do or wouldn't do ... I have an obligation to try to
bring people to justice.''
   Mediation efforts by the OAS and economic and diplomatic
sanctions against Panama by the United States have failed to get
Noriega to give up power. There are no indications he will step down
as Panama's de facto ruler in the face of the OAS call for a
peaceful transfer of power next month.
   ``I'm not holding my breath on his voluntary departure,'' the
president told reporters.
   Asked what the administration plans are with regard to Panama, he
said, ``I don't know for sure what we are going to do.''
   Noriega unilaterally invalidated the May election, after
initially claiming it was won by his handpicked presidential
candidate.
   Various independent international and U.S. observer groups said
Endara won the election by as much as a 3-1 margin despite
widespread fraud allegedly engineered by Noriega's forces.
   Bush said he had recently told Endara, ``who was duly elected by
the people of Panama, that we will continue to support what the
people of Panama voted for.''
</TEXT>
