<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea Bjt   08-15 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea, Bjt,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Student Arrested After Return From North</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean student called ``the
flower of unification'' by supporters returned home Tuesday from
communist North Korea, clutching the hand of a clergyman who came to
escort her. Both were arrested.
   Im Su-kyong, 20, went to North Korea six weeks ago as a symbol of
the peninsula's reunification and had been told she would be
arrested for violating a law against visiting an enemy country.
   Tears streamed down Miss Im's face Tuesday as she addressed a
small crowd a few yards from from the demarcation line in the
Panmunjom truce zone. She said she was prepared for arrest.
   A South Korean soldier using a megaphone told her and the Rev.
Moon Gyu-hyon, a Roman Catholic priest studying in the United
States, to halt as they stepped over the raised cement line that
bisects the oval-shaped Panmunjom area.
   Miss Im dropped a bouquet of flowers she was carrying and grabbed
Moon's hand as they walked toward two South Korean border guards.
   The radical student left Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, in
a motorcade Monday, seen off by thousands of screaming people waving
flowers.
   On Tuesday, what appeared to be much of the population of Kaesong
City, just outside the Demilitarized Zone, repeated the scene as her
open limousine pulled away from a guesthouse and headed for the
crossing. A loudspeaker van followed, blaring Miss Im's words of
farewell.
   Just before crossing the line, she told the crowd:
   ``Reunification of our motherland will come in the near future if
all Korean students North and South struggle together. If there are
forces that stand in my way, I will tell them of your sincere and
peaceful desire for reunification.''
   ``When our country is reunited, we will meet again!'' Miss Im
shouted.
   A North Korean army officer, Lt. Col. Yun Kiun, said, ``She is
brave.''
   She, Moon and officials of North Korea's Peaceful Reunification
Comittee then linked arms and sang ``Our Wish Is Reunification,''
swaying from side to side.
   Several Westerners in the northern sector of Panmunjom were seen
holding large placards that read ``Korea is one.''
   Officials in South Korea said Miss Im and Moon were the first
people to cross the border against the wishes of either government
since the Korean war ended in 1953.
   South Korea had said repeatedly that the crossing would violate
the Korean Armistice Agreement. Officials of the U.S.-led United
Nations Command, a signatory to the armistice, said they would file
a formal protest with North Korea of the violation.
   The U.N. Command, consisting of the United States and 15 other
nations that supported South Korea in the 1950-53 war, has
jurisdiction over the southern half of the Panmunjom truce area 35
miles north of Seoul.
   North Korean reports quoted Maj. Gen. Choi Ui Ung, chief delegate
to the Armistice Commission, as saying: ``Allowing them to go to the
South through Panmunjom is in full accord with the armistice
agreement and the spirit of humanitarianism.''
   Miss Im, who studies French at Hankook University in Seoul,
entered North Korea on June 30 to attend the World Festival of Youth
and Students in Pyongyang.
   Her original plan was to return July 27, but she stopped short of
the demarcation line when Seoul refused permission, and went on a
hunger strike for five days. North Korean officals said she became
ill during the fast and had only recently been released from a
hospital.
   Moon visited North Korea in June and returned there after a trip
to the United States, where he studies with the Maryknoll Order in
New York state.
   After their arrests, Miss Im and Moon were were flown to Seoul by
helicopter and she was given a medical checkup before being turned
over to the national intelligence agency, South Korean officials
said.
   They said the priest was questioned about his trip and about
anti-South Korea statements he allegedly made while in North Korea.
   If the two are convicted under the national security laws, they
could receive prison sentences of up to 10 years, legal experts said.
   In a speech in Seoul marking both Korea's liberation from
Japanese rule and its division in 1945, President Roh Tae-woo said
the Koreas should ``recognize each other, seek coexistence and
coprosperity and restore and develop a single national community
through mutual opening-up, exchanges and cooperation.''
   Roh also cautioned North Korea against agitating radicals in the
South.
   ``North Korea must realize that the only thing they can gain by
agitating the extremists and radicals within our society and by
enticing a few of them to secretly visit Pyongyang is the abhorrence
of our people,'' he declared.
   Dialogue between the nations has been sporadic. Several meetings
were held during the past year, but negotiations bogged down after
the illegal trips to North Korea.
</TEXT>
