<HEAD>DEA Official Arrested in Cocaine Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD that agent works at DEA headquarters
setting up DEA museum; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Investigators said ...';
SUBS last graf to CORRECT that DEA says agent dealt with informants sted
undercover agents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal Drug Enforcement Administration agent was
arrested in a sting by his own agency after delivering 62 pounds of
cocaine to informants at Logan International Airport, authorities
said today.
   Edward K. O'Brien, 44, headed the DEA's Springfield office from
1982 to 1988 and works at DEA headquarters in Arlington, Va.,
helping set up a DEA museum, said agency spokesman George Festa.
   O'Brien, who lives in Fairfax County, Va., was arrested Monday.
Officials said drug charges would be filed today.
   Investigators said O'Brien had received the drugs in Miami
earlier Monday from a DEA informant. O'Brien was paid $14,000 to
transport the drug and was expecting another $14,000 on delivery in
Boston, officials said.
   O'Brien was placed on leave.
   DEA spokeswoman Kathi Sullivan refused to elaborate on how the
sting worked.
   Also arrested in the case were O'Brien's brothers, Paul, 34, and
John, 39, both from Cape Cod, the DEA said. They were accused of
taking part in the deal
   The DEA alleged that this was the second such delivery. On July
27, while under surveillance, O'Brien picked up 55 pounds of sham
cocaine in Miami and brought it to Boston, receiving $25,000 from
informants, officials said.
</TEXT>
