<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--DC-10Crash-Crew     08-15 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--DC-10 Crash-Crew,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crew Member from Crashed DC-10 Goes Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Records, the first officer of the
United Airlines DC-10 that crashed, killing 111 people, has been
released from Marian Health Center.
   Records is the last of the crew of Flight 232 to leave the
hospital. He flew home Monday to Washington state on a chartered
Lear jet, said Joe Hopkins, a spokesman for United in Chicago.
   Flight 232 attempted an emergency landing at Sioux Gateway
Airport on July 19 about 40 minutes after its No. 2 engine
apparently exploded. Officials believe pieces of the disintegrating
engine severed the aircraft's three hydraulic systems, making the
jet almost impossible to steer.
   Pilot Al Haynes, 57, and second officer Dudley Dvorak, 51, were
released July 25 from Marian Health Center.
   Pilot Dennis Fitch, 46, of Bartlett, Ill., who helped guide the
crippled airplane to the airport, was released from Aug. 5. Fitch
was a passenger on Flight 232 but volunteered to help after the
engine explosion.
   One hundred eighty-five of the 296 passengers aboard Flight 232
survived the crash. Six passengers remained in Sioux City hospitals
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
