<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker 1stLd-Writethru a0532 08-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Night Stalker' Juror Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with alternate appointed, judge
warning jury that slaying is unrelated; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Prosecutors
allege ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 6-month-old trial of ``Night Stalker''
murder defendant Richard Ramirez took another bizarre twist when a
juror deliberating the case was slain in an apparent domestic
dispute.
   The body of Phyllis Singletary, a 30-year-old telephone employee,
was found Monday afternoon in her home. Neighbors reported hearing
fighting and gunshots in her apartment Friday night and early
Saturday.
   Authorities were seeking her live-in boyfriend, James Cecil
Melton, 51, for questioning, said sheriff's Deputy Bill Wehner.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan, who dismissed a juror last
week for sleeping during deliberations at Ramirez's trial on 13
murder charges, replaced Ms. Singletary with an alternate today and
sent the panel home for the day.
   The judge warned that the slaying apparently ``had nothing to do
with this case'' and ``does not add or diminish to the evidence of
whether Mr. Ramirez is guilty or innocent.''
   Both the defense and prosecution expressed a desire to avoid a
mistrial. But defense attorney Ray Clark said he wants jurors to be
polled on whether they feel they are able to go forward. The jury
returns Wednesday.
   Prosecutors allege Ramirez, a 29-year-old drifter from El Paso,
Texas, is the devil-worshiping ``Night Stalker'' who raped, robbed
and murdered people in their Southern California homes in 1985.
   The jury began deliberations July 26 but was ordered to start
over after the one member was dismissed. Monday was to have been the
first day of the new deliberations, but Ms. Singletary didn't show.
</TEXT>
