<FIRST>r w AM-InfantMortality     08-15 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Mortality,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Early Infant Attention Saves Long-Term Care Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for improved pre-natal health care
said Tuesday that spending $400 for expectant mother services can
save a thousand times that amount in lifetime care costs for a low
birthweight infant.
   Pointing out that the infant mortality rate in the United States
is the worst of any of the 18 industrialized nations, the National
Commission to Prevent Infant Mortality called for ``universal
access'' to early maternity and pediatric care for all mothers and
infants.
   In a report issued this month, the commission said employers
should make sure the health insurance they offer covers maternity
and well-baby care, and called on the government to assume the
responsibility for those who don't have insurance.
   ``We can spend the money now or we can spend a lot more later,''
said the report. ``The costs of prenatal care _ care that can
prevent low birthweight _ can be as little as $400 per mother.
   ``The lifetime costs of caring for a low birthweight infant can
reach $400,000.''
   Low birthweight is the leading cause of infant deaths and chronic
and disabling illness, the commission said. Low birthweight babies
are those born at less than five and a half pounds.
   ``This is very serious business,'' Dr. Reed Tuckson, commissioner
of health for the District of Columbia. He said the infant mortality
rate for blacks is twice that for whites and named the crack cocaine
problem as the reason for a recent increase in infant deaths in the
district.
   He and other panelists appeared for an infant mortality symposium
sponsored by the Congressional Black Associates and the Young Black
Professionals at the Capitol.
   The group acknowledged that a tight federal budget meant little
money for pre-natal care programs, and Tuckson pointed out that much
of the funding for public health concerns was now going to find a
cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   But the panel said publicity could do a lot to get expectant
mothers to available health care facilities.
</TEXT>
