<FIRST>r a AM-LorainLanding     08-15 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lorain Landing,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marines Receive Warm Welcome at Amphibious Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORAIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people cheered, and 15 quietly
protested, as Marines stormed a city-owned beach on Lake Erie on
Tuesday in a recruitment drive.
   ``Just to see the vast majority of people here getting up early
and watching us makes me proud of the service I do in the Marine
Corps,'' said Staff Sgt. Sam Adkins of Chattanooga, Tenn.
   ``I feel it's my job to protect the people I see here,'' said
Adkins, dressed in full combat gear and with his face blackened with
camouflage.
   Police Capt. Cel Rivera estimated that 10,000 people turned out
at Lakeview Beach to watch a company of about 100 Marines board four
landing craft from the USS Boulder and land on the beach in a
morning mist.
   Fifteen people staged a silent protest at a gazebo overlooking
the beach, holding anti-war placards and distributing literature.
   ``This whole thing is so silly, the idea that you can make a war
a carnival,'' said the Rev. Steve Hammond, a co-pastor at First
Baptist Church in Oberlin.
   The protesters represented various groups, including the Lorain
County Peace and Justice Commission, Clergy and Laity Concerned and
the Baptist Peace Fellowship.
   But most of the crowd cheered the Marines and scampered across
the beach to inspect the landing craft.
   ``I liked it,'' said Gary Jones of Westlake, who was holding his
1-year-old son, Bradford. Jones said he wanted to see ``where your
tax dollar goes.''
   Gov. Richard Celeste had refused the Marines permission to land
June 24 at Cleveland's Edgewater State Park as part of a 20-city
recruiting promotion tour of the Great Lakes region.
   Celeste, whose action was denounced by veterans' groups, said the
landing would be an inappropriate use of the park.
   After the Marines landed and held a brief formation, they mixed
with the crowd, which included families sitting on picnic blankets
and a Navy band playing jazz music.
</TEXT>
