<HEAD>Bush Pays Tribute to Mickey Leland, Larkin Smith</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush paid tribute anew Tuesday to
Reps. Mickey Leland of Texas and Larkin Smith of Mississippi,
calling them ``outstanding public servants'' who gave their lives
trying to ``better the lot of mankind.''
   The president, opening a news conference, spoke out again on the
``tragic aircraft accidents'' that killed the two lawmakers six days
apart.
   Leland, a Democrat from Houston, perished Aug. 7 with 15 others
on a mercy flight in Ethiopia, while Smith, a Republican from Long
Beach, Miss., was killed Sunday night with his pilot in Mississippi.
   ``I want to note again the passing of two outstanding public
servants,'' said Bush.
   ``Their passing is mourned by everyone who knew them, and Barbara
and I extend our sympathies to their families and friends during
this difficult period,'' he said.
   ``Their death also reminds us that there are outstanding men and
women in public life who are working at every level of government to
better the lot of mankind. And these two fine individuals
represented a deep caring for the poor, the disadvantaged, the
vistims of drug abuse and crime, and many other areas of our society
that need improving.''
