<FIRST>r a AM-Crack-Life     08-15 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack-Life,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Time Crack Dealer Gets Life in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-year-old crack dealer with no prior
police record has been sentenced to life in prison without
possibility of parole on his first conviction.
   Ernest ``Polo'' Staley ``had a decision to make, and that was
whether to deal in crack or not,'' U.S. Attorney Mike Moore said.
``And he chose to deal in crack. He got exactly what Congress wanted
for that decision.''
   At Monday's sentencing hearing, U.S. District Judge William
Stafford was unswayed by Staley's pleas for mercy.
   ``It seems to me your activity was the type you could stop at any
time,'' Stafford said. ``You were the wheel on which this whole
operation spun.''
   But defense attorney Robin Rosen argued for mercy.
   ``I've represented people who took lives and received less of a
sentence,'' Rosen said. ``It's a tragedy. I'm not saying this as an
attorney, I'm saying this as a human being: Everybody has worth and
dignity. Everybody should have a chance at rehabilitation.''
   Staley, convicted June 1, made as much as $25,000 a week, one
witness estimated. Staley ferried cocaine from Fort Pierce, cooked
the powder into crack rocks in a microwave oven, then kept the
street dealers supplied, witnesses said.
   Prosecutors argued that Staley's case met federal guidelines for
a life sentence. Besides heading the drug ring, the case involved
more than one kilogram of crack, a firearm was found, and Staley
tried to bribe a witness not to testify by offering $10,000 or a
Mercedes Benz. He also refused to reveal the source of his cocaine.
   Staley implored the judge for a second chance.
   ``I can remember J.F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King saying every
man and woman makes a difference. In order to make a difference, you
have to be given a chance,'' he told the judge.
   Staley said he'd already begun rehabilitation while in federal
custody for the past 14 months.
   ``My intention is to set up a drug foundation to help somebody
with a drug problem,'' Staley said. ``I know drugs are a terrible
problem, destroying our nation.''
</TEXT>
