<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Panama     08-15 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Panama,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hints Abducting Noriega Might Be Justifiable</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, saying ``I'm not holding my
breath'' waiting for Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to step aside,
Tuesday hinted that abduction of the Panamanian leader might be
justifiable.
   ``I have an obligation to try to bring people to justice,'' Bush
told a news conference. He cited the FBI's 1987 abduction of a
Lebanese highjacker as precedent for such long-arm tactics.
   Noriega remains under 1988 indictments on U.S. drug-conspiracy
charges.
   While declining to say whether abducting Noriega was actually
being considered, Bush said: ``We have an indictment out against
Gen. Noriega for drug trafficking. I'm told that it's a good
indictment, that it's an in-depth indictment.''
   Expanding on remarks he made in an interview last week with
reporters from Hearst Newspapers, Bush told the nationally broadcast
news conference: ``I'm not saying what I would do or wouldn't do,
but there was a case where a man named Younis was apprehended and
brought to justice.''
   It was a reference to the FBI hostage rescue squad's grabbing on
Sept. 13, 1987, of Lebanese hijacker Fawaz Younis in the
Mediterranean Sea.
   U.S. agents lured Younis aboard a yacht 13 miles off the coast of
Cyprus with the prospect of a drug deal and a party. He was later
convicted in U.S. District Court in Washington of leading five
heavily armed men in hijacking Royal Jordanian Airlines Flight 402
and holding 70 passengers and crew hostage for 30 hours in Beirut.
   Bush reaffirmed the longstanding U.S. view that normal relations
with Panama cannot resume so long as Noriega remains in power.
   However, Noriega, whose regime annulled a May 7 presidential
election that international observers said was won by opposition
candidate Guillermo Endara, has shown no signs of yielding to U.S.
demands that he step down.
   A team of international mediators is in Panama now negotiating
terms of a resolution by the Organization of American States (OAS)
calling for new elections on Sept. 1.
   ``Part of our understanding on the OAS agreement was that Noriega
would be out,'' Bush said. But, he added: ``I'm not holding my
breath on his voluntary departure.''
   Bush also told reporters that he had recently told opposition
candidate Endara that ``We will continue to support what the people
of Panama voted for.''
   A senior State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that Bush's vow of support for Endara did not put
the administration at odds with the OAS agreement to promote new
elections Sept. 1, conditioned on a transfer of power from Noriega's
regime to a transitional government.
   The United States supports that plan, said the official, although
it continues to believe that Endara fairly won the election.
   Noriega, commander of Panama's defense forces and de facto
leader, said last week that he was not going to step down, despite
the OAS agreement. He has been in power for six years.
   Last Wednesday, Bush told reporters from Hearst Newspapers that
``I wouldn't rule out any option'' when asked if he would consider
seizing Noriega to bring him to trial in the United States.
   According to some published accounts, former President Reagan
considered a plan to abduct Noriega while he was visiting his
daughter in the Dominican Republic, but rejected it as too risky.
</TEXT>
