<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Murder     08-15 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Murder,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Murders Stir Concerns Over Violent Videos, Comics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun didn't shine into Tsutomu Miyazaki's room.
   The single window of the room where police believe Miyazaki
mutilated the body of 5-year-old Ayako Nomoto was blocked by piles
of comic books, pornography and children's cartoon videotapes.
   Police announced Tuesday that the 26-year-old print shop worker
had confessed to killing and mutilating three girls in what
television news is calling the worst murder case in Japan's postwar
history.
   Miyazaki was arrested Friday in connection with the killing of
Ayako in June.
   Police said Miyazaki also confessed to strangling Mari Konno, 4,
in August 1988, burning the body and leaving it on her parents'
doorstep; and strangling Erika Namba, also 4, in December and
dumping her body on a mountain.
   Television and newspaper coverage, including images of the
suspect's room, has stirred fear in the homes of Japanese unfamiliar
with the level of violent crime in many other societies.
   The child slayings are the latest in a series of murders of
startling brutality by Japanese youth.
   Experts have been filling the airwaves with analyses of the
impact of violent sex imagery that is perhaps more pervasive in
Japanese popular culture than in any other developed country.
   Japanese barely blink at the graphic scenes of rape and murder
they see in sports newspapers and comic books. They usually ignore
the ads plastering telephone booths for prostitution services.
   Now, the extraordinary attention given the Miyazaki case, which
has dominated the front pages of national newspapers for days, has
stunned the Japanese and stirred concern about sex and violence in
the media.
   Police told local newspapers that the videos Miyazaki collected
ranged from cartoons to child pornography and violent movies.
   Authorities say Miyazaki confessed that in early June, he
kidnapped the 5-year-old near her suburban apartment, killed her,
mutilated her body and dumped it in a cemetery.
   Members of Miyazaki's video club told newspapers he was an
obsessive collector of cartoon tapes. His main hobbies, news reports
say, were copying tapes and doing pornographic photography.
   His parents simply described him as shy. ``He was always so quiet
that we wanted him to hurry up and get married so we could stop
worrying about him,'' they told the Mainichi Shimbun newspaper.
   Some experts blame violent videos for contributing to his mental
state and that of other people like him.
   ``If such videos were not so widely available, crimes like this
might not have happened,'' said Susumu Oda, professor of mental
health at Tsukuba University. ``For people with this kind of
disposition, videos can help put plans in their heads.''
   Another reportedly obsessive video hobbyist, Yoshiaki Kataoka,
21, was arrested Monday on suspicion of videotaping and sexually
abusing more than 30 girls.
   Kozo Hida, a 22-year-old mechanic who reportedly spent most of
his free time playing video games with neighborhood children, was
arrested earlier this year on suspicion of strangling one of them.
   Gang violence also is worrying many Japanese.
   In June, a young man received the death sentence _ a rarity for a
minor _ for his role in slaying a young couple out for a drive. A
group of teen-agers beat the couple with iron rods, raped the woman,
and killed both of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
