<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Refugees     08-15 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Refugees,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Asylum-Seekers Move Vigil in Budapest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of East Germans who want to
flee to the West moved their vigil Tuesday from the closed West
German Consulate to a nearby church, while German and Hungarian
officials negotiated their fate.
   These and other East Germans, who demand permission to emigrate
via West German diplomatic facilities in the East bloc, have created
a standoff involving their communist homeland, West Germany and
Hungary.
   West German diplomats closed their Budapest consulate and embassy
Monday because they said they could not handle the crush of East
Germans demanding asylum.
   Rezsoe Stuchlik, head of the Hungarian Red Cross foreign section,
said Tuesday about 200 East Germans had come from the consulate to
the courtyard of a Roman Catholic church about two miles away.
   An East German outside the church grounds said later the number
had risen to about 300.
   About 30 East Germans remained in front of the consulate. They
said West Germany diplomats had given them money.
   ``I'm staying here as long as it takes,'' said a 47-year-old man
from the Berlin area who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``One
month, two months, I don't care.''
   Varying numbers of East Germans have been maintaining a vigil in
front of the embassy and consulate for at least a week. They had
been allowed inside at night until the buildings closed Monday.
   In Bonn, Foreign Ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher said Monday
that 141 other adults and 40 children were holed up inside the
embassy in Budapest. Political opposition figures estimate that 400
East Germans have overstayed their visas and gone underground.
   West Germany closed its East Berlin mission Aug. 8 after 131 East
Germans seeking guarantees that they can go to West Germany sought
refuge there.
   Negotiations involving both German states and Hungary continued
Tuesday, the Hungarian Foreign Ministry said. It gave no details.
   In Bonn, government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling said Chancellor
Helmut Kohl wrote a letter on the problems in Hungary to East German
leader Erich Honecker. He did not say what the letter said.
   Red Cross officials said they didn't know how long the East
Germans at the Budapest church would continue their vigil. ``We have
means of taking care of them for about two weeks, but we're
considering longer-range plans,'' said Stuchlik.
   Speaking by telephone, Stuchlik said tents may be erected in the
courtyard by Wednesday. He said the Red Cross and the Hungarian
Maltesian Caritas Service, a charity group, were providing three
meals a day for the East Germans.
   Hungarian authorities were not consulted about the move to the
church, he said.
   He said the Hungarian Red Cross could turn to the International
Red Cross if it ran out of money and food for the East Germans.
   An East German consulate statement carried by the Hungarian news
agency MTI urged all East Germans staying here illegally to return
home. It also repeated a pledge that they would not be prosecuted
for escape attempts or overstaying visas.
   East Germans began asking for asylum in Budapest last month after
failed attempts to escape across the Austrian border, where liberal
Hungarian authorities have removed fences. The East Germans say they
fear persecution at home because they tried to flee.
   At least 1,600 East Germans are estimated to have crossed
illegally into Austria from Hungary since the fences came down in
May. Once in Austria, they try to obtain papers from the West German
Embassy in Vienna for travel to West Germany.
   East Germans can easily visit Hungary, but it is difficult for
them to travel legally to the West.
   The East German who commented at the church said West German
diplomats on church grounds were issuing West German passports to
the East Germans.
   According to West German law, all East Germans have a right to
West German passports. Consulate and embassy personnel routinely
issued passports to all East Germans seeking them before the two
compounds closed.
   However, Hungarian border authorities have not allowed bearers of
West German passports made out in Budapest to cross into Austria.
</TEXT>
