<FIRST>u w AM-Hills-Savings     08-15 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hills-Savings,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hills Urges Increased Personal Savings to Close Trade Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills on
Tuesday expressed support for increasing tax benefits for individual
savers, contending that expanded Individual Retirement Accounts
would help boost the country's low savings rate and reduce America's
huge trade deficit.
   Hills stressed that her endorsement did not mean that the
administration had decided to propose such a change, which has the
potential of benefiting millions of Americans.
   But other officials have said the administration is readying a
fall campaign to address the chronically low U.S. savings rate and
that expanding tax benefits to individual investors who use IRAs was
one of the ideas being considered.
   Hills said that expanding IRAs would ``highlight the great need
for private savings to go up. It sends up a flag saying, this is
very important, not only to your nation, but to your own future and
to your children.''
   One reason long advanced for America's high trade deficits is
that Americans consume more than the country can produce
domestically. If Americans could be persuaded to cut back on
consumption and save more, then it would limit the need for foreign
goods, economists reason.
   Higher U.S. savings rates would also lower the cost of capital
for U.S. businesses and make their products more competitive on
overseas markets.
   Hills said she did not know anyone in the administration who
opposed increasing IRA tax benefits but she said there was concern
over such questions as the potential loss of federal revenue.
   The huge cost to the treasury of IRAs was one reason that they
were greatly scaled back by the 1986 Tax Reform Act. As a result,
the number of tax returns claiming IRA deductions fell from 15.5
million in 1987 to 7.4 million last year.
   The administration is considering a variety of proposals to boost
U.S. savings rates as part of a fall initiative designed to address
long-range problems facing the country. Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady is scheduled to kick off the campaign with a series of
speeches, officials have said.
   The personal savings rate, savings as a percent of after-tax
income fell to a 40-year low of 3.2 percent in 1987 and increased
only slightly to 4.2 percent last year. By contrast, the savings
rate in Japan was 16.5 percent in 1987.
   Hills said that increasing the U.S. savings rate would help her
answer charges from Japanese trade negotiators that the United
States has not done enough on its own to solve its huge trade
deficit.
   Currently, Hills is holding negotiations with Japan, Brazil and
India in an effort to get those nations to lower trade barriers
cited by the administration last May when it issued a ``hit list''
of the countries with the most harmful barriers to sales of American
products.
   The Japanese have countered that America should make progress in
boosting its savings rate and cutting its huge federal budget
deficit as a way of lessening its dependence on foreign capital.
   The administration's various trade opening initiatives are aimed
at lowering the country's huge trade deficit, which measured $126.5
billion last year on a current account basis covering trade in both
merchandise and services.
   Hills said the current account deficit over the next 18 months
may actually rise ``a little,'' reflecting the rise in the value of
the dollar, which makes American goods less competitive on overseas
markets.
   ``It is hard to predict, but I do not look for a dramatic drop in
the trade deficit,'' she said.
</TEXT>
