<FIRST>r a AM-MonkeyHerpes     08-15 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monkey Herpes,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Lab Worker Treated for Deadly Monkey Virus That Killed Third</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A research lab worker has been
hospitalized with a probable case of a deadly monkey virus that
killed one co-worker and infected another.
   Gary Merkle, 32, of Mattawan, was in fair condition Tuesday in
Bronson Methodist Hospital in Kalamazoo, hospital spokesman William
Russell said.
   Test results for Merkle, who was admitted Saturday, are pending.
He is ``considered a probable case of herpes B virus,'' Russell said.
   Thomas McGeorge, 23, of Kalamazoo died in June from the virus
after he was infected through a bite or scratch from a research
monkey at International Research and Development Corp. of Mattawan,
an independent contract lab.
   Another former IRDC employee is infected with the virus, which is
present in more than 50 percent of rhesus monkeys, a type of Old
World monkey commonly used in experiments.
   The virus is harmless to animals, but attacks the brain and
central nervous system in humans and has an estimated 70 percent
mortality rate once symptoms appear.
   IRDC corporate officials are out of town and Merkle's employment
status could not be confirmed, company spokesman James Webb said.
   On July 28, the public health department levied $30,600 in fines
against IRDC for alleged violations of worker safety regulations and
for failing to tell all employees who worked with the monkeys about
the risks they faced.
   IRDC officials have denied the allegations and are appealing.
   The company, which employs about 350 people, uses thousands of
animals, including monkeys dogs, rabbits and rats, to test drugs and
chemicals for pharmaceutical, veterinary and agricultural companies.
</TEXT>
