<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     08-15 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Roseanne' Leads Comedy Sweep of Television Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedy shows, led by ABC's ``Roseanne,''
claimed all the places in the Top 10 of the Neilsen television
ratings for the week ended Aug. 13.
   In second place was NBC's ``Cheers,'' which has been running a
close race all summer with ``Roseanne'' for first.
   NBC, the No. 1 network for the 60th straight week, had six shows
in the Top 10 and second-place ABC had four. CBS, running third, was
squeezed completely out of the top slots and had only three shows in
the first 20.
   The sitcoms in the Top 10 were: ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's
``Cheers,'' ABC's ``Wonder Years,'' NBC's ``Dear John,'' NBC's ``A
Different World,'' NBC's ``Golden Girls'' and ABC's ``Coach'' tied,
NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' ABC's ``Who's the Boss?'' and NBC's
``Empty Nest.''
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of
10.9. ABC was second with 9.8 and CBS was third with 9.1.
   For the season to date, from Sept. 19, 1988, NBC leads with 14.6,
ABC is second with 11.8 and CBS is third with 11.7. The rating is
the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes with television
in the United States. The share is the percentage of sets in use.
   Two NBC summer shows continued to do poorly in the ratings.
``Knight &amp; Daye'' was in a tie for 44th place and ``13 East'' fell
again to a tie for 47th place. ``13 East'' made its debut in 10th
place, then dropped to 35th place last week.
   ABC's new magazine show ``Primetime Live'' was in 43rd place,
after its premiere the week before in 37th place.
   ``Married...With Children'' was again Fox Broadcasting's
highest-rated show, finishing 36th. Fox's ``Totally Hidden Video''
was 39th and ``America's Most Wanted'' was tied for 47th with ``13
East.''
   ``The CBS Evening News'' was first among the news shows, giving
CBS its only consolation for the week. CBS had a rating of 9.0, ABC
was second with 8.7 and NBC was third with 8.3.
   The lowest-rated network show was ABC's ``Incredible Sunday.''
Here are the five bottom network shows: CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' CBS'
``Beauty and the Beast,'' ABC's ``A Man Called Hawk,'' ABC's ``The
Devil and Max Devlin'' and ABC's ``Incredible Sunday.''
</TEXT>
