<FIRST>u i AM-Poland Bjt   08-15 0953</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, Bjt,0981</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Calls For Meeting to Solve Government Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski called
Tuesday for an emergency meeting of Poland's political leaders to
seek ``rational solutions'' to a growing government crisis that he
said threatens the nation's stability.
   The call was seconded by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, who also
said that ``if society wants it,'' he would agree to serve as prime
minister.
   If Solidarity succeeds in winning the prime minister's post, it
would be the first non-communist government in the East bloc since
the late 1940s.
   Prime minister Czeslaw Kiszczak said Monday he is ready to resign
and abandon efforts to assemble a Cabinet in the face of
Solidarity's opposition to any communist-led government. Kiszczak
became prime minister 12 days ago.
   He urged that United Peasant Party Chairman Roman Malinowski, a
communist loyalist, be selected by Jaruzelski to form a ``grand
coalition'' government that would include communists and members of
Solidarity.
   But the proposal of Malinowski drew little interest from other
political groups, and Malinowski himself by late Tuesday had not
answered whether he wants to be considered a candidate.
   Walesa reiterated his proposal to form a government based on a
coalition of Solidarity, the Peasant Party and the Democratic Party,
with some sensitive posts left to the communists.
   In the confused political situation, the state PAP news agency
said Jaruzelski ``expresses his concern over the deepening
instability of Poland's political and economic situation.''
   ``The president intends to appeal to representatives of the main
political forces in the country for participation in a joint meeting
devoted to seeking rational solutions ... as soon as possible,'' PAP
said.
   Jaruzelski also asked for restraint in ``political and social
emotions, which make national accord more difficult.'' He contacted
Walesa through private channels to ask him for a meeting, possibly
on Wednesday, said Walesa aide Krzysztof Pusz.
   The joint meeting was likely to bring together representatives of
the three parties and Solidarity, who were the main figures in last
spring's successful talks that led to an accord on elections and
legalizing the independent trade union movement after a seven-year
ban.
   Walesa said he welcomed Kiszczak's decision to abandon forming a
government but rejected Malinowski as prime minister. He said the
parties in the coalition discussions should decide on a candidate.
   ``If society wants it, I will have to go for the prime minister's
office,'' Walesa said. ``But I would prefer someone else.''
   Walesa also told state TV: ``After we sit down and reach
agreement on deep reforms, then we will find the names (to head the
government) too.''
   He said any Solidarity-led government would guarantee the
sensitive ministries of defense and interior to the communist party
and would do nothing to endanger ``the functioning of the Warsaw
Pact'' military alliance.
   Walesa said a Solidarity coalition would be ``a government of
national responsibility, nominated with respect for the rights of
the Polish president'' _ referring to the constitutional rights of
Jaruzelski to control foreign policy and the armed forces.
   Despite such assurances, the prospect of a Solidarity-led
government has alarmed the communist party and the Soviet Union,
which has said it could destabilize Poland and Europe.
   The party may also fear a Solidarity government would purge the
``nomenklatura'' _ party loyalists who hold tens of thousands of
government and management posts _ and undermine the communist
party's main base of support.
   The Democratic Party, which along with the Peasants holds the
parliamentary balance of power, on Tuesday endorsed Walesa's bid to
form the next government.
   ``We think that we should do everything to realize Lech Walesa's
proposal, which has broad support,'' said the secretariat of the
party, which historically has been allied to the communists.
   Walesa said Aug. 7 that only a government headed by Solidarity
and dominated by non-communists will have the credibility to solve
Poland's political and economic problems
   On the economic front, Kiszczak's caretaker Cabinet said extra
food supplies are to be directed to larger cities, and publicly
owned shops are to be sold or rented to private food vendors.
   Walesa praised Kiszczak's decision to resign, saying it reflected
a ``feeling of responsibility'' and could solve the government
crisis. He said he had nothing personally against Gen. Kiszczak, the
interior minister for eight years.
   The resignation of a communist premier because the opposition
won't endorse him _ as well as the bid by Solidarity to form a
government against the wishes of the Polish and Soviet party
authorities _ demonstrates how radically East bloc politics have
changed. The events would have been unthinkable a year ago.
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the country's Roman Catholic primate, noted
the changes during an annual Assumption Day sermon in Czestochowa.
   ``These events and changes of great significance were made
finally without violence and destruction. ... And we should thank
God for that,'' he said. But he warned the crowd of 150,000 of ``new
concerns,'' including the economy.
   Solidarity began coalition talks Thursday with lamakers from the
two minor parties, which have a combined strength of 103 seats and
hold the balance of power in parliament. Normally obscure and once
regarded as little more than communist fronts, the parties have been
thrown into the role of kingmakers.
   Aleksander Bentkowski, the leader of the Peasant Party's
parliament delegation, said he favors Solidarity's concept for the
next government.
   About a third of the Peasant Party legislators are leaning to
Solidarity and want greater independence from the communists.
Malinowski represents the more traditional, pro-communist wing of
the party that claims 500,000 members.
   Since partially free elections in June, many of the minor-party
lawmakers feel that in order to survive they must distance
themselves from the generally unpopular communists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
