<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-15 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uprising Leaders Order Strike to Protest Gaza Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of the anti-Israeli uprising Tuesday
ordered West Bank Palestinians to boycott their jobs in Israel for a
week to protest restrictive new measures imposed on Arabs in the
Gaza Strip.
   The order for a seven-day strike, which would be the longest in
the 20-month-old uprising, came along with a call for ``more stones
and knives'' in fighting Israeli occupation.
   A Palestinian man died Tuesday of a gunshot wound suffered a day
earlier in a clash with soldiers, the army said.
   The death brought to 536 the number of Palestinians killed by
soldiers or Jewish settlers since the uprising began in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip in December 1987. Thirty-eight Israelis have
been killed.
   Sixteen other Palestinans were reported shot and wounded Tuesday
in confrontations with soldiers in the occupied lands, according to
Arab reports. One of the victims, a 14-year-old girl from the Askar
refugee camp near Nablus, was reported in critical condition with a
bullet in the head.
   The PLO-backed underground leaders of the uprising said in a
communique that the strike should begin Friday, the day the army
begins enforcing a new rule that requires Gaza Strip Palestinians to
show computerized ID cards to enter Israel.
   Cards are denied anyone considered a security risk.
   More than 50,000 Gazans work in Israel, as do about 60,000
Palestinians from the West Bank.
   The uprising leaders called the cards ``a policy of starvation''
that would deny Arabs work and said West Bank Palestinians who did
not strike in sympathy for those in the Gaza Strip would be
considered ``betrayers.''
   It also called for an escalation of the fight against Israeli
occupation and ordered Palestinians not to meet with Israelis who do
not support the goals of an independent Palestinian state. It said
``anybody who breaks this decision will be outside the national
line.''
   Israeli officials have held a series of meetings with Palestinian
leaders to try to persuade them to accept the government's peace
plan, which calls for elections in the occupied lands but rules out
an independent Palestinian state.
   The 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied territories closed
their shops and offices Tuesday in response to a strike call by the
Moslem fundamentalist Hamas movement.
   Another commercial strike has been called Wednesday by the
underground leadership.
   The Palestinian who died Tuesday was identified by an army
spokeswoman as Ahmed Abdel Khaled Ayub, 23, of the Fara refugee camp
near Nablus.
   The spokeswoman said Ayub was shot in the back Monday when
soldiers opened fire on youths who attacked an army patrol ``at
close range with large stones and concrete blocks.''
   Several thousand camp residents raised Palestinian flags and
chanted pro-PLO slogans at a funeral procession for Ayub, Arab
reporters said.
   The army ordered a curfew on the camp after the funeral,
confining the 5,000 residents to their homes.
</TEXT>
