<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleTest     08-15 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ignition Test on Shuttle Rocket Motor Called Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary results show that an ignition
test Tuesday of the space shuttle's redesigned solid rocket motor
was a success, officials at the Marshall Space Flight Center said.
   The center is continuing to test the redesigned engine to check
the performance of joints that were blamed for the 1986 Challenger
explosion, even though the engine is currently used in flights. The
lastest was by Columbia, which returned Sunday from a space voyage.
   The tested rocket motor contained intentional flaws, including a
lack of adhesive on one of the joints and a small hole in another.
But the test worked as predicted with no leaks passing expected
points, said Chuck Vibbart, project manager for the test.
   Further testing on the rocket motor will be done in the next few
days to determine if any possible leaks occurred, officials said.
   The test was the initial one in the second phase of trials of the
redesigned solid rocket motor. Officials expect to conduct several
more years of testing, including some work on the next generation of
rocket motors to be built at a National Aeronautics and Space
Administration site in Iuka, Miss.
   ``We feel that we have tested the redesigned rocket motor
sufficiently to demonstrate its flight readiness,'' Vibbart said
after Tuesday's test. ``But we're also cautious technical engineers
that feel we need to continue to gather data to make sure there are
no surprises lurking out there.''
</TEXT>
