<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     08-15 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Speaks on Independence Day, 27 Injured by Grenade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi used his
independence day speech Tuesday to attack Parliamentary opponents
and accuse them of slowing the nation's progress.
   Also Tuesday, authorities blamed Pro-Pakistani extremists for a
grenade that injuring 27 people in the city of Srinagar, a popular
tourist resort in the northern Jammu-Kashmir state. Moslem
extremists there are waging a campaign to support Pakistan's claim
to part of the state.
   Gandhi delivered his annual speech amid tight security after
police warned that Sikh militants might launch attacks.
   In his speech, Gandhi attacked ``traitorous forces'' in
Parliament.
   He has accused political groups opposed to his Congress Party of
espousing religious fundamentalism, especially within the country's
majority Hindu faith.
   He is scheduled to call general elections in the next four
months, and he suggested repeatedly these groups are hindering the
nation's development.
   The prime minister was elected to a five-year term in December
1984, two months after his mother and predecessor, Indira Gandhi,
was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
   Gandhi spoke from the ramparts of the 17th century Red Fort. He
was flanked by foreign diplomats, Cabinet ministers, and senior
government officials.
   Authorities checked for hidden explosives in vehicles arriving
for the ceremony. Visitors were frisked and sent through metal
detectors.
   Gandhi wore a white, bulletproof jacket over a white tunic and
trousers during his speech celebrating Indian independence from
Britain in 1947. A bulletproof glass shield on his podium was
removed minutes before he began his 50-minute speech.
   Police officials said security was strengthened after they
received reports that nine militants had entered the capital for
terrorist attacks.
   Sikh militants in the northern state of Punjab have been fighting
for an independent nation since 1982. They have been blamed for
1,200 killings in Punjab this year and for bomb attacks in New Delhi.
   Tuesday's violence, however, was blamed on Moslem militants who
apparently were trying to enforce a general strike in the Kashmir
Valley of Jammu-Kashmir state.
   Government spokesman Mohammad S. Pandit said 27 people were
injured when a hand grenade exploded at a vegetable market in
Srinagar.
   Pandit said the grenade, thrown at a police jeep, missed and
instead exploded among morning shoppers.
   He said no one was injured in three other bomb attacks around the
area.
   Pandit blamed the attacks on ``Kashmiri militants and
secessionists,'' which are terms used by the government to describe
pro-Pakistani groups.
   Srinagar, a predominantly Moslem city, is about 62 miles west of
the border with Pakistan, which claims part of the state as its own.
   Three Moslem militant groups called the strike in Srinagar to
protest what they said was ``forcible occupation of Kashmir by
India.''
</TEXT>
