<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1634EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     08-15 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Enforce One-Day Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals enforced a one-day
general strike Tuesday, the latest in a series to protest the
presence of Indian soldiers trying to end an ethnic civil war.
   Traffic virtually halted in Colombo and other parts of this
island off the tip of India. Most businesses closed.
   Soldiers patrolled the city and policemen stood guard at major
intersections and bus stops.
   Sinhalese militants of the People's Liberation Front, who have
conducted a campaign of strikes and assassination against the
government for two years, had distributed posters warning people to
stay indoors.
   The campaign began after Indian troops were deployed in Sri Lanka
two years ago to try to help end the war involving separatists in
the Tamil minority demanding a homeland in northern and eastern Sri
Lanka.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who has been negotiating with
India for a phased withdrawal of the estimated 43,000 soldiers,
urged people to refrain from violence.
   ``No room should be left for the slightest undermining of the
sovereignty of Sri Lanka,'' he said in a reference to India's
declaration that it would not withdraw while the Tamil insurrection
continues.
   ``Every practical step should be taken to ensure total peace in
the north and east by taking into consideration the realities of the
situation,'' Premadasa said in a statement released by the
government.
   Most Tamil rebel groups laid down their arms, but the largest,
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, continued the fight against
the Indian soldiers.
   A military official, who cannot be identified under standing
rules, said the Tigers ambushed and killed four Indian soldiers
Tuesday in Morawewa, 145 miles northeast of Colombo.
   At least 1,000 Indians have been killed since they arrived after
the peace accord of July 29, 1987, and the Tamil war has cost 10,000
Sri Lankan lives since it began in 1983.
   The Indians are deployed only in the northeast, where most Tamils
live, but the People's Liberation Front says their presence
compromises Sri Lankan independence. It also claims the accord made
too many concessions to Tamils.
   Premadasa's government blames the Sinhalese radicals for 4,000
killings since June 1987, including at least seven on Tuesday, which
brought the total to 79 in four days.
   Tuesday's strike coincided with the 42nd anniversary of India's
independence from Britain. At least two Colombo dailies refused to
carry special supplements on the occasion, sources at the newspapers
said privately.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese. Most Tamils are
Hindus and Sinhalese are predominantly Buddhist.
   India, an overwhelmingly Hindu nation, became involved because it
is the regional power and 60 million of its people are Tamils.
</TEXT>
