<FIRST>r a AM-SmellyPassengers     08-15 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smelly Passengers,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Kicked Off Flight Because of Odor Want Apology, Free Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple kicked off a USAir flight after
an attendant complained they smelled badly are asking the airline
for an apology and the price of two of its most expensive tickets.
   ``Personally, I don't think we smelled any different than anybody
else on the plane,'' Randi Freeman said Tuesday. She claimed the
airline fabricated the accusation as a ploy to regain two seats on
an overbooked flight.
   USAir spokesman Larry Pickett said airline employees followed
company policy in removing Freeman, 27, and her husband, Amir
Omrani, 30, from Flight 252 on July 31. Pickett denied the flight
was overbooked.
   Pickett said the head attendant and gate supervisor told the
couple to leave because their body odor was offensive. He said
passengers also had complained.
   ``If passengers are offending other passengers with their odor or
anything else, we have every right to remove them from the plane,''
he said.
   Freeman said airline employees eventually told the couple that
only Omrani had an offensive body odor, and they gave the couple
toiletries and put them on a later flight.
   ``Nothing changed from the time we got off the first plane until
we got on the next one. My husband washed up and put on my
deodorant, but he didn't take a shower. When we got on the next
flight, I asked a woman sitting next to me if we smelled and she
said no,'' she said.
   Freeman said she has written USAir President Edward Colodny
seeking an apology and $3,528, the cost of first-class round trip
tickets for two from New York to Los Angeles.
