<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Japan     08-15 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Japan,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese in Beijing Take Precautions Against Terrorist Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese living in Beijing took special
precautions Tuesday against possible attackd by an obscure terrorist
group calling itself the ``Blood-Bright Dare to Die Squad.''
   The group had said in death threats received as long as a month
ago that on Tuesday its members would start killing two Japanese
businessmen or tourists a week to retaliate for Japan's ``economic
invasion'' of China.
   The threats, contained in letters sent to Japanese in cities
nationwide, have led hotels and businesses to tighten security,
Japanese businessmen said.
   An official at Japan Air Lines, which received the first threat
in July, said arrangements had been made to improve security at the
Beijing airport.
   ``We haven't done anything special ourselves, but stricter
security measures are being taken by the public security office at
the Beijing airport,'' said Shigeki Suetsugu, a JAL manager.
   Additional plainclothes and uniformed guards were posted at the
Jinglun Hotel, which is popular with Japanese businessmen and where
the airline's ticket and reservations office are located, Suetsugu
said.
   About 230 Japanese businessmen living and working at the Minzu
Hotel in Beijing met with the hotel staff to plan extra security
precautions. The measures included hiring additional guards and
implementing mandatory registration of visitors in the evenings,
said Toshimi Inoue, manager of a trading company operating from
offices in the hotel.
   ``All the hotels are looking out for the Japanese,'' Inoue said.
``Of course we don't really expect anything to happen, but it's
better to take precautions.''
   Japanese Embassy officials said no special measures were planned
beyond earlier warnings to nationals to take precautions such as
varying their routes to work and staying indoors at night.
   As of late Tuesday, no attacks or incidents involving Japanese
nationals had been reported, the embassy said.
   Japanese Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama said Thursday his
ministry was considering lifting an advisory against non-essential
travel in China. He said the advisory would remain in effect for
Beijing, which has been under martial law since May 20. Martial law
was imposed because of the pro-democracy movement that was crushed
by military forces on June 3-4.
   Most of the Japanese living in China left following the military
suppression of the student-led movement. Airline employees said
virtually no Japanese tourists are traveling to China, but most
Japanese businessmen have returned to their jobs.
   ``We're just going ahead with our work as usual,'' said Kenji
Ishii of the Japan Association for Promotion of International Trade.
   ``You can't spend all day worrying. After all, there are
extremists in Japan, too.'' Said Inoue, who has managed a trading
firm in Beijing for four years.
   ``The protests last spring seem to have brought some of those
groups out into the open here in China, too,'' he said, referring to
organizations such as the Blood-Bright Dare to Die Squad.
   Some Japanese say the threats have cast a pall over living and
working in China.
   ``We don't expect anything to happen, but the threats make it
impossible for us to move around freely. It makes life here rather
grim,'' said JAL's Suetsugu. ``It would be a lie to say I'm not
worried. It's creepy.''
</TEXT>
