   An airport official, speaking with the condition he not be
identified, said nine rockets hit the airport and did minor damage
to the runway. Amani said only three rockets hit the airport and the
runway was ``not damaged even slightly.''
   Reporters trying to enter the airport were turned away by
security guards.
   Moslem guerrillas, who began fighting the government after a
communist coup in April 1978, control most of the countryside around
Kabul and other cities. Soviet military forces entered the war in
December 1979, but completed a U.N.-mediated withdrawal Feb. 15.
   Amani said rockets destroyed two houses about half a mile from
the airport and others hit a bus station and shopping center.
   The airport sources said several rockets landed in front of and
behind the main passenger terminal of the civilian section during
the busy morning hours when several flights were arriving and
departing. No information was available on damage or casualties in
the military section.
   All passengers in the terminal were safe but departing flights
were delayed, one airport official said.
   Amani said 299 rockets have hit the city in four weeks, killing
188 civilians and injuring 483, not counting casualties from
Tuesday's attacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
