<SECOND>AM-Bush-Interest Rates,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Endorses Budget Director's Comments on Fed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday endorsed complaints
made by Budget Director Richard Darman that the Federal Reserve was
keeping interest rates so high that the central bank was impeding
economic growth.
   ``I don't know of any president, now or in the past, who doesn't
favor lower interest rates,'' Bush said in response to a question at
a news conference.
   ``I can feel very comfortable with his (Darman's) sallying forth
and saying that,'' Bush said. ``I think I've said essentially the
same thing in the past.''
   Darman on Sunday criticized the Federal Reserve for pursuing
interest rate policies which he said could be pushing the country
toward a recession. He said the central bank should ease credit
further to keep the 6{-year-old economic expansion alive.
   Darman said that if the country does suffer a recession it will
be because the Fed ``erred on the side of caution'' in keeping
interest rates high in an effort to guard against inflation.
   Bush sidestepped a question on whether he agreed with Darman's
assessment on who would bear the blame for a recession, saying he
would take that question ``under advisement.''
</TEXT>
