<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Wallenberg     08-15 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Wallenberg,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening of Wallenberg Files Raises Hopes of Solving Mystery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet offer to open files on Raoul
Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat missing since World War II, has
raised hopes of unraveling the mystery about his fate. But an
official in Moscow said Tuesday the material will show Wallenberg is
dead.
   Wallenberg, who was credited with saving tens of thousands of
Jews from Nazi concentration camps, vanished after his arrest by
Soviet troops entering Budapest, Hungary, in January 1945.
   The Soviets say files discovered in 1957 showed Wallenberg, who
would be 77 today, died of a heart attack in prison 30 months after
his arrest. But Soviet dissident sources have reported seeing the
Swedish diplomat in labor camps during this decade.
   The Stockholm-based Raoul Wallenberg Association said Monday it
has been invited to send a four-member delegation, including
Wallenberg's closest relatives, to Moscow for talks on his
disappearance.
   The group is to travel to Moscow in mid-October.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh
said Wallenberg's relatives ``probably will have the opportunity to
acquaint themselves with all the materials we have on the Wallenberg
case, including the materials on his death in 1946.''
   There was no explanation for Gremitskikh's reference to 1946 for
Wallenberg's death, given previously as July 1947.
   Wallenberg issued Swedish passports to 20,000 Hungarian Jews
slated for Nazi death camps. His intervention with German
authorities was credited for the survival of another 100,000
Hungarian Jews.
   The Soviets never explained why he was arrested but many
historians believe he he was mistaken for an American spy.
</TEXT>
