<HEAD>Court Will Hear North's Appeal Next February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's appeal of his convictions in the
Iran-Contra scandal will be heard next Feb. 6 before a three-member
panel of judges.
   Reviewing the North case will be U.S. Court of Appeals judges
Abner Mikva, Laurence Silberman and David Sentelle, according to a
notice issued by the court.
   Mikva is a Carter administration appointee while Silberman and
Sentelle were appointed during the Reagan administration.
   The court notice was signed last week and made available Tuesday.
   North was convicted May 4 of aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, destruction of National Security Council documents and
accepting an illegal gratuity.
   He was fined $150,000, given two years probation and ordered to
serve 1,200 hours of community service.
   He has decided to proceed with the community service while
appealing the three felony convictions.
