<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1833EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Smith     08-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smith,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Search For Clues In Crash That Killed Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators hauled twisted
portions of a light plane to Keesler Air Force Base in Biloxi
Tuesday in hopes of determining what caused a crash that killed Rep.
Larkin Smith and his pilot.
   ``So far we don't have any significant findings. The wreckage is
being removed for further examination,'' George Prellezo, regional
director for the National Transportation Safety Board, said from
Miami.
   ``The preliminary examination did not reveal anything
significant. So basically we don't have anything to suggest what may
have caused the crash.''
   Searchers on Monday found the body of Smith, 45, along with that
of pilot Chuck Vierling, 58. Authorities said the pair's
single-engine Cessna 177 crashed about 9:30 p.m. Sunday into a dense
south Mississippi forest.
   Smith, a freshman Republican from Mississippi's 5th District,
threw out the first pitch in a youth baseball tournament in
Hattiesburg and was returning to his home in Gulfport, a Gulf Coast
city about 70 miles to the south.
   Prellezo said volunteers from Keesler used a path cut by a
bulldozer during the search to remove wreckage.
   A Perry County Sheriff's Department deputy, who declined to give
his name, said no portions of the plane were found intact.
   Prellezo said an NTSB investigator was being assisted by about
five other people, including personnel from the Federal Aviation
Administration and the aircraft's manufacturer.
   He said they were interviewing witnesses and would examine the
plane's engine. Nothing about the positioning of the crash debris
offered any clues about its cause, Prellezo said.
   ``There was nothing significant about the wreckage itself,
nothing strange, nothing extraordinary,'' he said.
   There was no indication that foul play had been involved in the
crash, but it had not been ruled out, Perry County Sheriff Carlos
Herring said.
   But Prellezo said, ``We have no reason to suspect foul play at
this point.''
   Officials say the plane apparently clipped a 70-foot-tall pine
tree and disintegrated on impact.
   Smith will be mourned at a two-day public memorial Wednesday and
Thursday at the Mississippi Coast Coliseum and Convention Center in
Biloxi, officials said.
   The gray-haired former sheriff and police chief went to
Washington with a hard-line stance against crime gained in 22 years
of law enforcement experience and quickly impressed colleagues with
his knowledge of the law.
   Smith won a position on the House Judiciary Committee, breaking a
Republican tradition of appointing only lawyers to the panel.
   ``Because of his background and hard-working manner he gave every
indication of becoming a star,'' said Alan Coffey, chief Republican
counsel for the Judiciary Committee.
   ``I'm just absolutely heartsick to lose somebody like (Smith),''
said Gov. Ray Mabus, who ordered state flags flown at half staff.
``Our hearts and prayers go out to his family. He and I were real
good friends, even though we were in different (political) parties.
He was easy to work with.''
   Smith was the second congressman in as many weeks to die in a
plane crash. Earlier Sunday, the wreckage of a plane carrying Rep.
Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and 15 other people were found in Ethiopia
with no survivors. That plane disappeared Aug. 7 on a flight to a
remote village.
   Smith's survivors include his wife, Sheila, a daughter, Tracy,
and a grandson.
</TEXT>
