<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial     08-15 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests in Helmsley Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution in the tax evasion and extortion
trial of hotel queen Leona Helmsley rested its case Tuesday after
six weeks of testimony in which former employees called her a
penny-pinching tyrant.
   But even before the last witness had completed his testimony,
attention was focused on the defense presentation.
   At issue is an accounting report that claims Mrs. Helmsley and
her husband, Harry, are actually owed $681,000 in tax refunds during
1983-85, the years charged in the indictment.
   In arguments at the start of the day, Assistant U.S. Attorney
James DeVita said defense attorneys had given him a copy of the
report Monday afternoon. He complained to U.S. District Judge John
Walker that the rules of evidence mandate that the defense turn over
such documents at a much earlier date.
   Walker, who appeared upset at the development, admonished Mrs.
Helmsley's attorney, Gerald Feffer.
   ``I am extremely disappointed in defense counsel for not
furnishing this earlier,'' Walker said. ``To me, it is inexcusable
and I can't understand why it didn't happen.''
   Walker said that if he allows the report to be admitted into
evidence, the trial could take a month longer than expected because
the government would need to rebut its conclusions.
   The judge also indicated that he may grant the government a delay
to review the report and its underlying documents. If he does this,
the trial could continue into September.
   He reserved his decision on whether to admit the report into
evidence.
   The government ``needs to have absolute and complete disclosure
of every aspect of this offer of proof,'' Walker said. ``That
includes finding out from the accountants when they were retained,
what they had to say and what the basis is for their testimony.''
   The report itself has not yet been made public. But Feffer and
another lawyer for Mrs. Helmsley, James A. Bruton III, have
described it during arguments.
   They said two outside accounting firms reviewed the tax returns
of several Helmsley-owned partnerships from 1983-85 and found that
the accountants who prepared the returns had incorrectly calculated
the depreciation of property.
   These alleged oversights, the lawyers claim, resulted in an
overstatement of the Helmsleys' personal income.
   Bruton said the report concluded that the Helmsleys overpaid
$90,000 in taxes in 1983, $13,000 in 1984 and $578,000 in 1985.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is charged with evading about $1 million in
federal taxes by charging about $4 million in personal expenses to
Helmsley-owned businesses. Two former aides, Frank Turco and Joseph
Licari, are being tried for assisting in the scheme.
   Mrs. Helmsley and Turco are additionally charged with conspiracy
to extort payoffs and merchandise from vendors doing business with
the Helmsley organization.
   Mrs. Helmsley's husband, Harry, 80, was also charged but was
severed from the trial for health reasons.
   The last of 42 witnesses to testify was Gus Lesnevich, a
handwriting expert hired by the prosecution to review invoices,
memorandums and other documents submitted during the trial.
   Lesnevich identified the initials and writing of Mrs. Helmsley
and her co-defendants on the documents.
   When DeVita stood and said the government had rested its case,
Mrs. Helmsley smiled and appeared relieved.
   Previous witnesses had portrayed Mrs. Helmsley as an abusive boss
who sometimes forced suppliers to charge her personal expenses to
her business. Even her attorney conceded that she was ``demanding''
and ``abrasive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
