<DOCNO> AP890815-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Cuomo     08-15 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cuomo,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Tries to Sell Bush on Anti-Shoreham Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo tried and failed
Tuesday to change the federal mind and win presidential approval for
his plan to dismantle a new nuclear power plant.
   ``I don't think anything was done to change the governor's mind.
I don't think anything was done to change the president's mind,''
Deputy Energy Secretary W. Henson Moore said outside the White House.
   ``We haven't seen anything new in the information the governor
gave us.''
   President Bush, Moore, White House chief of staff John Sununu and
Bush aide Andrew Card met with Cuomo for nearly an hour Tuesday
after Cuomo said he wanted to see the president personally to make
his case for dismantling, rather than mothballing, the Shoreham
plant 50 miles east of New York City on Long Island's northern shore.
   Cuomo left the president with a 2-inch-thick binder of
information on Shoreham and a list of 10 questions he would like the
administration to answer about Shoreham and nuclear energy. The
questions generally expressed great skepticism about the feasibility
of mothablling the plant.
   ``We left it that the (administration's) energy planners would
talk to my planners, that the president would ask people at Energy
and presumably his staff as well to read the book, to read the 10
questions, and to get back to us with answers,'' Cuomo said. ``He
was precise about saying that we were entitled to answers and we
would get answers.''
   The governor declined to characterize Bush's reaction to the
presentation, but said it was a positive sign that the president had
even agreed to the meeting.
   Cuomo said the federal government's attempt to derail the tearing
down of the Long Island nuclear power plant amounted to usurpation
of state's rights.
   ``The Department of Energy is presuming to tell the state of New
York what plants it can build, whether or not it should mothball the
plants, whether or not it needs environmental impact statements,''
he said. ``There's no such authority in the Department of Energy,
nor has anybody ever attempted anything like that in all the years
of this federal government.''
   But Moore disagreed, calling Cuomo's argument ``a red herring.''
   ``The Congress has charged the Department of Energy with
fashioning a national energy policy,'' he said. ``The law says that
we're supposed to speak up, we're supposed to make decisions, we're
supposed to do what we can to see to it that the American people
have affordable energy and have the supplies of it that they need.''
   The Energy Department argues that the 813 megawatts that Shoreham
can produce are needed to ease possible power shortgaes in the
Northeast, and that replacement power would mean burning more
environmentally harmful fossil fuels.
   Cuomo asked in July for a meeting with Bush after White House
chief of staff Sununu said the plant should be mothballed, not
dismantled.
   ``We want to wait for the people of Long Island to realize that
the plant is needed,'' Sununu said in an interview with Newsday, a
Long Island newspaper.
   Cuomo said at the time he did not expect to be granted an
audience with the president because it would put Bush in the
embarrassing position of admitting he was ill-informed. But at a
meeting of the National Governors Association in Chicago earlier
this month, Bush told Cuomo they could get together.
   The federal-state debate over Shoreham's fate has been running
since Bush appointed Sununu and Energy Secretary James Watkins, both
of whom have been strongly pro-nuclear and pro-Shoreham.
   The Democratic governor blasted the administration for its
``unjustified and arrogant interference'' in trying to block a
shutdown settlement negotiated between the state and the Long Island
Lighting Co., which built Shoreham. The state has long maintained
that the area around Shoreham could not be safely evacuated in the
event of a nuclear accident.
   Under the settlement, the state will buy the $5.5 billion plant
for $1 and have it dismantled at the company's expense. In return,
the company has been guaranteed annual rate increases of about 5
percent for at least a decade. Long Island homeowners and businesses
already pay the highest electricity rates in the country.
   Although the deal has been approved by various state agencies and
company stockholders, the Department of Energy has said it would
seek to prevent it from going through by opposing transfer of
Shoreham's license. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission must approve
the transfer, and the department has tried to slow that process by
asking the commission to order its own environmental review of the
impact of closing Shoreham and freeze staffing there.
   Last week, the Energy Department also joined a private lawsuit
that challenges the Shoreham shutdown on environmental grounds.
</TEXT>
