<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `In the ...,' of 2nd item to DELETE incorrect
reference to Ellsberg.</UNK>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Watergate figure G. Gordon Liddy says he
isn't worried about being typecast as a bad guy.
   In the early 1970s, the former Nixon aide concocted a campaign of
dirty tricks against Democratic presidential candidates and
masterminded the break-in at the Watergate headquarters of the
Democratic National Committee.
   Liddy, 58, was in Tacoma recently filming ``Nowhere Man,'' in
which he plays a character who fakes his death as part of a scheme
to throw the cops off his trail so he can make a huge drug score.
   The sordid role suits him fine, Liddy said.
   ``If you are seen by producers, directors and casting people as a
credible villain, you're fortunate indeed, because we waste a
villain a week on every show,'' he said speaking of television and
movies in general. ``It's a big market for villains, a far bigger
market than for the guy with the capped teeth who gets the girl.''
   In another, as-yet-unreleased movie, ``Street Asylum,'' Liddy
says he plays ``a corrupt megalomaniac, a former police official now
running for mayor who has formed a sinister alliance with a female
mad scientist.
   ``I am also a sexual pervert,'' he says of the role. ``There's
absolutely no redeeming social value whatsoever in that character.''
   Liddy says his wife agrees he fits the mold.
   ``Mrs. Liddy says, `You don't have to act,''' Liddy said. `` `You
just go up there and be yourself, and you're the perfect villain.'''
</TEXT>
