<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     08-15 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Police Academy with Mortars, Rockets, Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL ESPINO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked a newly
built police academy Tuesday with mortars, rockets, dynamite bombs
and rifle fire, wounding two policemen and five cadets, authorities
reported.
   The attack, which began with a mortar barrage early Tuesday,
awakened residents in El Espino, located just west of San Salvador,
and two nearby communities.
   A rebel spokesman telephoned local radio stations and said 25
guerrillas carried out the assault. He gave no report of rebel
casualties.
   He said the raid was part of an offensive he called ``The armed
struggle for democracy will not be detained.'' He read a communique
that said the academy, where several hundred recruits are trained,
was turning out ``agents of repression.''
   The armed forces press office said several buildings in the
complex were damaged.
   An army helicopter gunship arrived shortly after the attack began
and illuminated the area with dozens of red flares.
   As they withdrew the guerrillas left mines that were removed by
bomb-disposal teams.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front have
been fighting since 1980 to overthrow the government. It is
estimated that about 70,000 people have been killed in the war.
   Both the 11-week-old rightist government of President Alfredo
Cristiani and the rebels have indicated a willingness to begin
negotiations on ending the conflict but no peace talks are scheduled.
</TEXT>
