<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan-Elections     08-15 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan-Elections,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan Schedules First Elections for Parliament in 22 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan's first general parliamentary
elections in 22 years will be held Nov. 8, Prime Minister Zeid Bin
Shaker said Tuesday.
   His announcement, carried by the official Jordan News Agency,
said the date was set by the 26-member Cabinet in accordance with
King Hussein's election decree earlier this month.
   Interior Minister Salem Massadeh said about 1,400 candidates
would run for a parliament of 80 seats and candidate registration
would start Saturday.
   A ban on political parties, in effect since a coup attempt in
1957, remains in force so candidates will run as individuals
although they can be members of political organizations.
   Massadeh said more than a million voters registered in a 15-day
period that ended Tuesday. About 1.2 Jordanians are eligible to vote.
   He said committees would begin examining the registration lists
Wednesday and the procedure would take a week.
   Since the early 1950s, parliaments have been evenly divided
between the east and west banks of the Jordan River, but voting on
both banks has not been possible since Israel captured the West Bank
in the 1967 Middle East war. A few district elections were held in
1984 to replace lawmakers who had died.
   King Hussein suspended the old 60-member parliament last year
after relinquishing sovereignty over the West Bank to the Palestine
Liberation Organization. Election of the mew parliamewnt solely from
Jordan will help seal the country's separation from the
Israeli-occupied territory.
   The king approved a law April 17 calling for a 72-member body
representing only the East Bank. After four days of rioting over
price increases later that month he promised elections by the end of
the year.
   Political activists said the April election law did not
distribute seats fairly according to population and it was amended
in July to add eight seats for major population centers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
