<FIRST>r i AM-France-Lebanon     08-15 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Lebanon,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Dispatches Destroyer, Pursues Diplomacy on Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France said Tuesday it is sending a destroyer to the
eastern Mediterranean to be in a position to aid French citizens in
Lebanon while pursuing diplomatic actions aimed at a cease-fire in
the civil war.
   Premier Michel Rocard's office said the 5,000-ton destroyer
Duquesne, equipped with surface-to-air Exocet missiles, was ordered
out of port early Tuesday.
   The statement said France also was ``pursuing and intensifying
her diplomatic actions in nearby concerned capitals and with
international organizations to achieve an immediate halt in the
fighting'' in Lebanon.
   It said the destroyer was being sent to provide ``all assistance
that could be asked and to be in a position to aid the French
community.'' The statement noted that the French ambassador's
residence in Beirut has been hit several times during the artillery
duels between Lebanese Christian and Syrian forces.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas has spoken with U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar several times recently on
the Lebanese conflict and sent Thierry de Beauce, secretary of state
for international cultural relations, to capitals throughout the
Middle East.
   About 7,000 French citizens live in Beirut and 85 percent have
dual nationality, the Foreign Ministry said. Six hundred French
soldiers serve with the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon.
   France administered Lebanon for 20 years, withdrawing in 1943,
and has been active in seeking a solution to the 14-year-old
sectarian civil war.
</TEXT>
