<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker 1stLd-Writethru a0675 08-15 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0675,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sought in Juror's Death Kills Self</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with suicide victim identified,
details; pickup 13th graf pvs, The judge ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought in the death of a ``Night
Stalker'' trial juror committed suicide Tuesday and admitted in a
note to killing the juror during a domestic dispute, authorities
said.
   Hours earlier, Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan sent the jury
home to recover from the shock of Phyllis Singletary's death. Tynan
said he hoped the jury could resume deliberations Wednesday, and
lawyers for both sides said they wanted to avert a mistrial in the
year-old trial.
   James Cecil Melton, 51, shot himself in the head at 10:30 a.m. at
a motel in suburban Carson after sheriff's deputies received an
anonymous phone tip that he was there, said Deputy Bill Wehner.
   ``He came out of his room onto the balcony, put a fully loaded
unidentified caliber handgun to his head, and shot himself,'' said
Wehner. ``He died at the scene.''
   Melton had been sought for questioning in the killing of
Singletary, 30, his live-in girlfriend, who was shot at the couple's
Carson home, Wehner said.
   In a note, Melton admitted killing Ms. Singletary in a domestic
dispute, but the note did not elaborate, the deputy said.
   Defense and prosecution lawyers said they believed the jury, with
an alternate replacing Ms. Singletary, could continue working toward
verdicts on the serial murder charges against Richard Ramirez.
   Ramirez, 29, a drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged with 13
counts of murder and 30 other felonies. Prosecutors contend Ramirez
is the devil-worshiping ``Night Stalker'' who raped, robbed and
murdered victims in a 1985 rampage that terrorized Southern
California.
   ``Mr. Ramirez doesn't want a mistrial. He wants to go forward,''
said attorney Ray Clark. ``He's like the rest of us. Nobody's happy
about this. It's a very sad thing.''
   Some of the jurors were in tears as they arrived in court Tuesday.
   ``I think there is a tear in the eyes of a lot of us,'' Tynan
told the panel. But he stressed that Ms. Singletary's slaying ``had
nothing to do with this case.''
   Ms. Singletary's battered body was found Monday after she had
failed to show up for jury deliberations that morning. Wehner said
she had been beaten before she was shot many times.
   Neighbors told police the couple had fought over the weekend and
one woman said she heard gunshots.
   The judge selected an alternate to replace Ms. Singletary.
   ``It is tragic,'' the judge said. ``But what happened to her does
not add or diminish to the evidence of whether Mr. Ramirez is guilty
or innocent.
   ``I do not mean to be callous,'' he said, ``but we have business
to do.''
   He recessed court for the day.
   ``I think we all have been terribly affected,'' he said.
   It was the second time in five days that a deliberating juror had
to be replaced. On Friday, a juror was dismissed for sleeping during
the talks and an alternate was substituted.
   In addition to the 12 regular jurors seated from the beginning of
the trial, 12 alternates were chosen. As of Tuesday, five had been
sent in as regular jurors.
</TEXT>
