<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Rain for the East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened the East Coast, portions of
the Great Lakes region and the central Plains on Tuesday, while the
rest of the nation enjoyed fair skies.
   Precipitation was most widespread along the middle and south
Atlantic Coast, Georgia, Alabama and the southern Appalachians.
   Half an inch to an inch of rain fell during a two-hour period in
Knox County, Ky. A thunderstorm produced a half-inch of rain in 30
minutes at Springfield, Vt.
   Strong thunderstorms were expected over portions of the lower
Great Lakes and over parts of Montana and northern Wyoming. Pea-size
hail struck Flint, Mich.
   Locally heavy rain fell on portions of the central Plains as an
upper level disturbance and a slow moving cold front produced
thunderstorms over central Nebraska and northern Kansas. Two inches
of rain accumulated in central Nebraska.
   Afternoon temperatures were mostly in the upper 60s and 70s in
Michigan, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Great Plains
and the northern Rockies. Readings were in the lower 60s in upper
Michigan, northern lower Michigan and northern Wisconsin.
   Most of the eastern United States had temperatures in the 80s,
with a few 90s near the Gulf Coast.
   There were also a few readings in the 90s over Utah and interior
valleys of California, with temperatures over the 100-degree mark in
the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 105 degrees at Needles, Calif. The
nation's low was 29 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms in the East Coast states, the Appalachians, the Ohio
and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf Coast states, the northern Rockies
and the northern High Plains.
   Widely scattered thunderstorms were expected in the mountains of
the Southwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s and lower 90s across
most of the nation. Highs were forecast in the 70s in Maine, the
Great Lakes region, the northern Rockies, Washington state and the
Pacific Coast.
   Readings were to reach the upper 90s in parts of Utah and Nevada,
near 105 degrees in the interior valleys of California and near 110
degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
