<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     08-15 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Members of Disbanded Police Unit Confined to Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibia's administrator on Tuesday
ordered that 1,200 policemen who had served in a paramilitary unit
be confined to their bases for retraining.
   Adminstrator-general Louis Pienaar said the policemen had been
members of a disbanded counter-insurgency group known as
``Koevoet,'' the Afrikaans-language word for ``crowbar.''
   He said the action was designed to ease tensions as the
territory, also known as South-West Africa, heads toward
independence.
   Pienaar said the relative calm in Namibia allowed the policemen
to be ``confined to bases where they will undergo reorientation and
retraining to equip them for roles that are to be redefined.''
   ``If the situation should in any way deteriorate ... I shall
consider the steps that would need to be taken in order to restore
law and order,'' he added.
   United Nations officials, including Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar, had said that former Koevoet members were
intimidating civilians in northern Namibia and should be removed
from the 6,000-member Namibian police force.
   U.N. military and civilian personnel are in Namibia to monitor
the transition to independence. The territory has been administered
by South Africa since World War I under a mandate from the defunct
League of Nations.
   Koevoet squads played a leading role in the South African-led
security forces battle against guerrillas of the South-West Africa
People's Organization (SWAO).
   Most Koevoet members were black Namibians. Some civilians accused
the unit of brutality and atrocities. It was disbanded in January.
   Many ex-Koevoet members have been integrated into the regular
police force. Pienaar had argued the ex-Koevoet fighters were needed
to guard against possible attacks by SWAPO guerrillas.
   Under a U.N.-backed regional peace accord, South Africa agreed to
free the territory beginning April 1. But on that date, some 1,000
SWAPO guerrillas crossed into northern Namibia from southern Angola,
setting off three weeks of fighting that threatened to derail the
independence plan.
   But the peace process is back on track and SWAPO is favored to
win pre-independence elections in November.
   Pienaar said he decided to confine the ex-Koevoet members to the
bases after U.N. officials assured him that the threat of a SWAPO
attack had subsided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
