<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1959EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   08-15 0969</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0665,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Anti-Drug Effort Will Get More Federal Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 17: ``Some law,'' with three grafs to note congressional
requirement and give Biden comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday promised a
``balanced, decisive, effective and achievable'' national drug plan,
backed by more federal money, to meet Americans' demand for action.
   He declined to say where the money would come from ``because the
final decisions haven't been made.''
   Bush said he would not raise taxes, ``but we are going to expand
federal expenditures.'' He added, ``We will have to do some
reallocation of resources.''
   Bush focused on the anti-drug campaign on his last day at the
White House before leaving for a three-week vacation in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   He told reporters at a news conference that his drug policy
coordinator William Bennett has given him an outline of the
developing national drug strategy.
   ``It's balanced, decisive, effective and achievable, and it will
target all aspects of the problem. It will call for commitment and
sacrifice and understanding, but it's clear to me that the American
people demand no less,'' he said.
   He said final details of the plan will be worked out over the
next several weeks before he announces the specifics on Sept. 5.
   Bennett's proposal would target drug users, as well as strengthen
enforcement. A draft of the plan obtained by The Associated Press
calls for users to be arrested and fined and to lose their driver's
licenses, their cars, their federal grants if they have any.
   Bush discussed whether to put federal financial muscle behind
such proposals in a meeting Tuesday with his Domestic Policy Council
of advisers.
   As drafted, the plan would withhold federal highway funds from
states that did not revoke drug offenders' licenses, and it would
withhold federal criminal justice funds from states that don't
perform drug tests on people in the criminal justice system. Schools
receiving federal money would have to have firm prevention programs.
   White House spokeswoman Alixe Glen said Bush was still weighing
those ideas.
   During his presidential campaign, Bush supported revocation of
drug offenders' driver's licenses.
   The draft strategy would seek a 49 percent increase in federal
treatment money for 1990, to $925 million; $1.2 billion for new
prison construction; a $200 million increase for state and local law
enforcement, and $50 million for the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, most of it for security improvements at public housing
projects.
   The president, asked Tuesday if he planned to cut other programs
to fund the anti-drug war, said he could not state where the money
would come from, ``because the final decisions haven't been made.
But we will have to do some reallocation of resources, there's no
question about that.''
   Pressed on how he would come up with the funds, he added, '`We're
in a period of hard times in the sense that we don't have all the
money that we would like to spend in several areas.''
   At the same time he expressed determination to reduce the federal
budget deficit and stay within the spending limits set by
congressional budget writers.
   Some law enforcement professionals and members of Congress have
criticized the anti-drug plan being developed by Bennett under the
legislation that established his job as too reliant on enforcement
solutions.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, criticized Bush's resolve not to raise taxes to fight
drugs.
   ``To make real progress on this issue, it is going to take a
massive commitment of resources to law enforcement, drug treatment
programs, drug education, and more. If that means raising taxes to
pay for drug-fighting measures, so be it,'' Biden said Tuesday. ``We
should not let the politics of `read-my-lips' stand in the way of a
full scale effort to arrest the drug epidemic.''
   Bennett told reporters Tuesday that his plan will lay out ``terms
of accountability for all aspects of this problem, whether it's the
treatment side or the education side or the law enforcement side,
and we're holding ourselves accountable.''
   ``We're saying in 10 years, there's going to be a lot less drug
use,'' said Bennett.
   Bush on Tuesday met with two groups of community anti-drug
activists to get their opinions on what must be done.
   Among them were the parents of a Texas college student killed by
members of a drug cult.
   Jim and Helen Kilroy, among about three dozen people meeting with
Bush and Bennett, later said tougher enforcement is needed. Their
son's body was found in a mass grave outside Matamoros, Mexico.
   Drug treatment experts said after the meeting that they didn't
dwell on where to get the money for the anti-drug fight.
   Geraldine Sylvester, head of New Hampshire's Drug Rehabilitation
Services, said, ``I don't know how the funds are going to be
reallocated. But I know there is a total commitment to fight this
war on drugs on all levels and, if there has to be some shuffling of
resources, I'm certain they are astute enough to figure out exactly
how to do that.''
   The president, in his remarks, was asked if drug-producing
countries should be penalized if they fail to cooperate in stemming
the flow of drugs.
   ``I wouldn't be opposed to that, provided they were able to
cooperate with us,'' the president said.
   But he said he has ``a certain responsibility to look at the
problems that are facing some of these countries with limited armed
forces of their own, with very complicated insurgencies in their
countries and to formulate a foreign policy that takes these things
into consideration.''
   He expressed the view that Colombia's leadership wants to help,
for example, but that its effort is hindered because Colombia ``has
been ripped asunder by the drug cartels,'' with many judges and
officials assassinated.
</TEXT>
