<HEAD>Columnist Sues Biographer</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS one graf at end with Washington Times editor comment; also
SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Feld is, to show Feld claims threat led to dropping
of column</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated gossip columnist Karen Feld filed a
lawsuit Tuesday alleging that biographer Kitty Kelley and a
photographer tried to drive her out of business.
   Feld is seeking $50 million dollars in damages from Kelley and
Time Inc. photographer Stanley Tretick for threatening to file a
lawsuit which Feld says resulted in her losing her syndicated column
at The Washington Times.
   In the lawsuit in District of Columbia Superior Court, Feld
alleged that Kelley and Tretick ``engaged in wanton, outrageous and
unjustifiable conduct, causing grave injury to Feld, including
severe emotional distress.''
   In June, Feld wrote a column saying Kelley appeared at the
funeral of the daughter of former Reagan aide Lyn Nofziger
``disguised as one of the bereaved.'' The article speculated that
Kelley, who is writing a biography of Nancy Reagan, attended only to
get access to Reagan insiders.
   Kelley told Washingtonian Magazine that she had been invited by
the Nofzigers, who confirmed the invitation, and threatened to sue
Feld. That suit was never filed.
   Feld's publicist, Samantha Dean of Samantha Dean &amp; Associates
Inc. in New York City, said that Feld stands by her column.
   Kelley did not immediately return a telephone call seeking
comment.
   Times Managing Editor Wesley Pruden said Feld's column was not
dropped because of Kelley's complaint. ``We dropped her column for a
number of reasons. It just doesn't fit in with what we want to do,''
he said.
