<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SmogCleanup     08-15 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smog Cleanup,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Adopts Southern California Clean Air Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jananne is cq in 8th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials Tuesday approved a
far-reaching blueprint to clear the polluted skies of Southern
California so the state can meet federal standards by the year 2007.
   Harriet Wieder, an Orange County Supervisor serving on the
nine-member Air Resources Board, characterized the board's plan to
clean the nation's smoggiest air as a ``leap into a `Brave New
World.'''
   ``But it's either that leap, or we wake up one morning and
discover that it's `The Day After,' and that we did it to
ourselves,'' said Brian P. Bilbray, a board member and San Diego
County Supervisor.
   The board voted 8-0 to adopt the plan, despite industry
opposition that prompted the board two months ago to request
additional information from the regional agencies that developed the
program.
   The plan was branded ``Texas justice'' by William T. Huston, a
commercial developer leading a coalition of business and labor
interests battling to revise the smog cleanup effort.
   ``They're acting as their own judge, jury and executioner,''
Huston said.
   But while two reports were presented to clarify questions raised
by business and political interests, the Air Resources Board made no
changes in adopting the plan.
   ``Those people who oppose the plan are going to have to look at
how they plan to accomplish the same goals,'' said ARB Chairwoman
Jananne Sharpless. ``So far, the alternatives offered have come up
very short of the goals, or they don't have any authority for doing
what they want to do.''
   The unprecedented plan represents a comprehensive approach to
improving air quality, using land-use planning, transportation
programs and stricter standards for industry smokestacks, automotive
emissions and petroleum-based fuels.
   It was finalized last March, following more than five years in
development, by the South Coast Air Quality Management District and
the Southern California Association of Governments.
   The first part of the three-phase program calls for enacting more
than 120 rules that would require, for example, the chemical
reformulation of aerosol sprays and stricter controls on industry
smokestacks.
   Existing smog-control rules were incorporated in the plan, but it
also serves as a blueprint for the future by outlining the process
for adopting new rules and by planning for the use of anti-pollution
technologies yet to be perfected.
   The Los Angeles basin has the worst air pollution in the nation,
and has been working under a court order to comply with standards
set by the federal Clean Air Act and enforced by the Environmental
Protection Agency.
   Air quality measurements for El Monte Tuesday showed ozone levels
at about 15 hundred parts per million, an unhealthy level, said Tom
Eichhorn, a spokesman for the South Coast Air Quality Management
District.
   ``It was unhealthful, but for August in Southern California it
was pretty good,'' Eichhorn said.
   Following the board action, state and two regional agencies can
begin enacting the plan's clean air provisions, even though the EPA
has yet to give its approval, said Bill Sessa, a spokesman for the
Air Resources Board.
   California is the only state with its own standards for vehicle
emissions, and has led the nation in reducing smog by pioneering new
standards and such devices as the catalytic converter, Sessa said.
   Last June, for example, the board tightened its emission
standards, which exceed federal standards for several pollutants,
for automobiles to be produced in 1993 and afterward.
   The board also plans to require improvements in computerized
pollutant control equipment in cars, tighten state smog check
requirements and set new standards for petroleum-based fuels.
   Huston refused to say whether his group, the Community Air
Quality Task Force, plans to file a legal challenge to the plan,
although he said that's an option to be considered.
</TEXT>
