<FIRST>r w AM-Dorfman-USNews     08-15 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dorfman-US News,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Mum on Report That Columnist Dan Dorfman Being Investigated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Language in 7th graf may be objectionable to some readers. Also
on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission declined
on Tuesday to confirm or deny a published report that it is
investigating USA Today financial columnist Dan Dorfman.
   According to the newsweekly U.S. News &amp; World Report, the SEC is
looking into ``whether Dorfman wittingly or unwittingly is being
used by individuals who give him information in order to manipulate
the stocks he writes about.''
   William R. McLucas, an associate director in the SEC's
enforcement division, declined to comment on the report Tuesday,
citing commission policy against confirming or denying reports of
investigations.
   Dorfman denied that he had been a party to any manipulation.
   ``I'm so careful and sensitive about what I do,'' he said Monday
night when reached at his home for comment.
   Dorfman, who also is a commentator on Cable News Network's
``Moneyline'' program, said he knew nothing about any investigation.
   ``I have not been contacted by the SEC, the New York Stock
Exchange or anybody else,'' he said. ``I think it's a lot of crap.''
   Tom Petruno, Dorfman's editor at USA Today, also said he knew of
no investigation.
   ``We have no idea where U.S. News got this information or who its
sources are,'' he said.
   Citing unidentified sources, the magazine said in its issue dated
Aug. 21 that the SEC probe deals with Centaur Partners, a
Maryland-based investment partnership that Dorfman has written about
repeatedly in the past 14 months.
   U.S. News said the SEC is investigating whether Centaur, in
establishing initial positions in several prominent companies, may
be manipulating the market in the companies' stock.
   When Dorfman reported that Centaur bought shares in these
companies, the companies' stock price rose. The question is whether
Centaur is selling shares in these companies to investors, leaving
those investors holding the bag when takeover bids don't
materialize, the magazine said.
   Maryland businessman Melvyn Estrin, president of one of the
limited partnerships that make up Centaur, denied to the magazine
that Centaur tried to manipulate stock prices or that it ever gave
Dorfman any information.
</TEXT>
