<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CannibalVictims     08-15 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibal Victims,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains of 5 Suspected Victims of Cannibal Reburied</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd cq in lede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bones of the five suspected victims
of cannibal Alferd Packer were reburied Tuesday in a simple yellow
pine coffin as a minister prayed for all victims of ``crime and
evil.''
   In a ceremony devoid of flowers or music, the scientists who dug
up the bones last month placed them in five compartments inside the
4-foot-by-4-foot corduroy-lined coffin.
   Four Lake City clergymen spoke briefly to a crowd of about 150
gathered at the hilltop grave before the coffin was lowered 8 feet
into the ground. A steel plate was placed over the coffin to
discourage vandals.
   Packer was the only survivor of a snowbound party of Utah
gold-seekers that was trapped in the San Juan Mountains in southwest
Colorado during the winter of 1874.
   Packer claimed one member of the party killed the other four and
Packer was forced to kill him in self-defense. He said he ate their
remains to survive.
   He eventually was convicted of manslaughter and served time in
prison, but maintained his innocence until his death.
   Dr. James Starrs, a George Washington University law professor
who wanted to separate fact from legend about Packer, led a research
team that dug up the bones last month.
   The bones and other artifacts found in the common grave were
transported to the Arizona State Museum in Tucson for analysis. But
time and money shortages forced the reburial of the bones earlier
than the scientists had hoped.
   Last week, Starrs and Walter Birkby, curator of physical
anthropology at the Arizona State Museum, said they found at least
four of the victims were bludgeoned to death in butcher fashion and
then were carefully defleshed. They also said there was no visible
evidence that any had suffered gunshot wounds.
   Birkby said Tuesday that the only answer scientists found in
their examination of the remains was that the victims were murdered
and cannibalized.
   ``We found nothing to corroborate or refute anything Packer
said,'' Birkby said Tuesday. ``We'll never know who did it based on
any solid physical evidence. We're never going to know.''
   When the bones were dug up in July, the expedition took on the
air of a light-hearted historical circus. Reporters descended on the
community and T-shirts with slogans such as ``have a friend for
dinner'' and ``taste the high country'' sold briskly.
   On Tuesday, the Rev. Jeff Light of the Presbyterian Community
Church began the reburial ceremony with a prayer for victims of
``crime and evil.''
   Three other ministers, representing the other religious
communities of Lake City, population about 400, addressed the
gathering of local residents and tourists. Then the scientists
placed the bones in the coffin compartments and served as
pall-bearers.
   Sandra Jarman, who owns the property on which the remains were
buried, placed five grapevines and eucalyptus leaves on the coffin
before it was lowered into the common grave.
   Dressed in a black jogging suit and black tennis shoes, Jarman
said she's pleased the bones have been returned to the place where
they were dumped in burlap sacks 115 years ago.
   ``They've become my little friends,'' she said.
   A headstone erected on the site in 1928 or 1929 was to be
restored to its place and the site opened to tourists Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
