<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus-Protest     08-15 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Protest,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriots March to Protest Turkish Occupation of Famagusta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHERENIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 Greek Cypriots holding
lighted candles marched Tuesday to the U.N.-policed Green Line to
protest the Turkish occupation of Famagusta, once a flourishing
tourist resort.
   The Green Line divides the island into Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot zones.
   The marchers, led by Famagusta's former Mayor Nikos Voyatzis,
walked through Dherenia, a suburb of the now-deserted port city, to
a checkpoint. There they handed a U.N. officer a petition calling
for Greek Cypriot refugees to be allowed to return home.
   ``Greeks and Turks must live together,'' the demonstrators
shouted.
   The demonstration marked the day in 1974 that Turkish troops
seized Famagusta after invading Cyprus. The Turks invaded after a
short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking to unite the island with
with Greece.
   Before the march, a message from President George Vassiliou, the
Greek Cypriot leader, was read, saying ``We reiterate our
determination to return to our homes in the Turkish-occupied north,
but we are trying to achieve this through peaceful means.''
   Vassiliou referred to U.N.-sponsored talks being conducted with
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash aimed at reunifying the island
as a two-zone federated state.
   The Green Line that splits the island is guarded by a
2,300-member U.N. peacekeeping force that has served in Cyprus since
violence flared in 1963.
</TEXT>
