<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSTest     08-15 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Test,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gay Men's Group Urges Consideration of AIDS Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay Men's Health Crisis on Tuesday urged New
Yorkers who may have AIDS to seriously consider being tested for the
disease, a change of emphasis that the group said was based on
medical and political developments.
   While the organization has been skeptical about testing in the
past, its director, Richard Dunne, said it was reassured by a state
confidentiality law and encouraged by evidence some drugs can extend
the lives of AIDS patients.
   ``We've always said think about it,'' said Dunne. ``The
difference is that if you thought about it in 1985 you probably
wouldn't want to get tested. If you think about it in 1989, you
probably will want to get tested.''
   The organization was not recommending the test be taken, Dunne
said, because the decision was a personal one.
   GMHC placed ads headlined, ``Think about it,'' in the city's four
major daily newspapers Tuesday. They noted that the drug AZT can
slow development of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and
treatments such as aerosolized pentamidine can prevent some
AIDS-related illnesses.
   GMHC provides counseling for people with AIDS and lobbies in
their behalf.
</TEXT>
