<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonValdez     08-15 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valdez Moving Into Drydock For Nine Months Of Repairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipyard workers on Tuesday began moving the
Exxon Valdez from a pier to a dock where the tanker that caused the
nation's worst oil spill will be repaired over the next nine months.
   Tugboats helped guide the 987-foot ship into the repair dock,
which is only 3 feet wider than the 166-foot-wide Valdez, National
Steel and Shipbuilding Co. officials said.
   Workers plannd to tow the Valdez from its current berth at a
NASSCO pier into San Diego Bay, then turn and back it stern-first
into the dock.
   The vessel was launched three years ago from the same dock, which
resembles a huge swimming pool separated from the bay by a moveable
gate.
   The crippled ship was returned to NASSCO from Alaska, where it
ran aground March 24 in Prince William Sound, spilling nearly 11
million gallons of crude into the sound's wildlife-rich waters.
   Repairs to the ship and its shredded hull were expected to cost
about $25 million.
   Dockmaster Frank Russell, a veteran of more than 40 dockings,
said he would use up to eight tugs to coordinate the ship's movement
while monitoring the tanker's position through a team of divers and
surveying instruments.
   Shipyard workers were not expected to start repairs this week
because it will take about six days to remove all the water from the
dock.
   ``I suspect there will be a two-week period in which the only
people in there will be lawyers and engineers,'' said NASSCO senior
vice president Al Lutter.
   Once inside, the gate will be closed and NAASCO crews will start
draining water from the repair dock. After lowering the water level
about six feet, which takes about four hours, the Valdez will come
to rest on blocks and supports that will hold the ship while it's
being repaired.
   Five clusters of 24 adjustable jacks, each having a 250-ton
capacity, have been installed to maintain an even keel when the ship
is lowered. A level landing was crucial because the tanker otherwise
might slide off the blocks and damage itself and the repair dock,
Russell said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. officials have said they plan to return the
tanker to service, though possibly under a different name, after
repairs are completed.
   The Valdez arrived off the San Diego coast July 10 after being
towed more than 2,000 miles from Prince William Sound. But its entry
into the bay was delayed three weeks after oil slicks were sighted
near the vessel. The ship pulled into the NASSCO yard on July 31.
</TEXT>
