<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Leland-Caucus     08-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-Caucus,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland Funeral Services Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of Rep. Mickey Leland said Tuesday the
best way to honor the late congressman would be to continue his
life's work to fight world hunger.
   In a statement released Tuesday, family members expressed thanks
to President Bush, the Ethiopian government and others who worked to
find Leland and the 15 others who perished in a remote mountainside
plane crash a week ago.
   The family also announced that a burial Mass would be held at 10
a.m. Saturday at St. Anne's Catholic Church in Houston. A community
memorial service was scheduled Friday at Texas Southern University.
   ``We take great comfort in knowing that Mickey died living his
passion: To end world hunger,'' Houston City Councilor Rodney Ellis
said, reading from the family's statement. ``The legacy of Mickey
Leland asks that each of us to continue to share in his vision, not
only of ending world hunger and homelessness, but also of a world
where all nations and their people are at peace.''
   Leland and his party of 15, including eight other Americans, died
when their twin-engine plane crashed into a rugged mountainside in
Ethiopia while en route to a refugee camp near the Sudan border. The
plane disappeared Aug. 7 and was discovered early Sunday morning.
   Leland, 44, was head of the House Select Committee on Hunger.
   The Houston Democrat's family said they wanted to complete
Leland's work ``by making sure that every child in every nation has
an opportunity to grow to a healthy adulthood.'' They asked that
donations in Leland's honor be made to InterAction, an international
hunger relief organization, or by contacting a food bank.
</TEXT>
