<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--JewishPrisoners     08-15 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Jewish Prisoners,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Clears Way for Jewish Sabbath Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Tuesday that
Jewish inmates at the State Prison of Southern Michigan should be
allowed to travel between complexes at the prison site so they can
attend weekly Sabbath services.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously rejected claims by Michigan prison officials that
permitting the inter-complex travel by six Jewish inmates would pose
security problems. The inmates accused prison officials of violating
their civil rights.
   The appeals court's decision reverses a ruling by U.S. District
Judge Horace Gilmore, who upheld the prison officials' position and
barred travel of the prisoners for the weekly services.
   The appeals court upheld another portion of Gilmore's order which
requires the prison officials to permit an annual Passover Seder
observance at the prison.
   The inmates filed suit in April 1986.
   The Michigan facility once was operated as a single 4,500-bed
prison, but has since been split into three separate complexes,
according to testimony.
</TEXT>
