<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLandings     08-15 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landings,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Jets Make Emergency Landings; No Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines jet made an emergency landing in St. Louis
Tuesday when a warning light indicated a problem with the landing
gear, and an American Trans Air jet landed in Chicago after the
pilot shut down an engine, officials said.
   No one was injured in either incident, said spokesman Mort
Edelstein of the Federal Aviation Administration's Chicago office.
   United Flight 673, en route from Chicago to St. Louis with 83
people aboard, notified the Lambert-St. Louis International Airport
control tower about 11:30 a.m. that the left main landing gear might
not be fully extended, said Tony Boos, a spokesman for the St. Louis
Airport Authority.
   ``We do not know what was wrong, but we do know the landing gear
held firm on contact,'' said United spokeswoman Sara Dornacker.
   The Boeing 737 circled the airport for nearly an hour to burn off
as much fuel as possible, Boos said.
   Mechanics were working to determine the problem.
   Several hours later, the American Trans Air jet landed at
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport after rescue crews were put
on emergency standby.
   The American Trans Air charter flight was carrying only a crew of
three.
   Authorities have not determined why the pilot shut down the rear
engine on the three-engine Boeing 727 jet, the FAA said.
   On Sunday, the rear engine of a Continental Airlines Boeing 727
bound for Portland, Ore., disintegrated as the plane was taking off
from Denver, forcing the pilot to abort the takeoff.
