<HEAD>Troops Kill 16 Inmates in Escape Attempt; Five Hostages Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 9 grafs to ADD report that Australian missionary raped
before being slain; Pickup 6th pvs, ``The standoff...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVAO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers rushed a prison Tuesday
and shot to death 16 convicts who had been holding members of
religious group hostage for three days. Five hostages, including a
9-year-old boy, were killed.
   Among the slain hostages was an Australian missionary who one of
the freed captives said had been raped at knifepoint the night
before she was killed.
   Officials reported it was decided to storm the prison after some
of the 15 hostages escaped and told them the would-be escapees had
killed other captives.
   ``We were not ... dealing with reasonable people,'' said Justice
Undersecretary Silvestre Bello, who was involved in negotiations
with the convicts. ``We had to authorize a military operation,
especially since there was an urgent need to save the five living
hostages.''
   The attack began about 3 p.m. Troops rushed forward firing
automatic weapons and secured the downtown jail in Davao City, 610
miles southeast of Manila, after about 40 minutes, witnesses and
officials said.
   A few hours earlier, the convicts had tried to escape by using
hostages as shields. During the confusion, a captive was killed and
five others fled. They told police four other hostages had been
slain.
   Jacqueline Hamill, a missionary from Sydney, was among those
slain by the convicts. Her body was found dumped outside the
detention center with a bullet wound in the chest.
   The Rev. Fred Castillo, one of the freed hostages, said Miss
Hamill and some of the nine other women hostages were raped. Other
freed hostages said they heard the women screaming on Monday night.
   ``Jackie told me about the incident,'' Castillo said Tuesday.
   The standoff began Sunday at the Metropolitan District Command
Center in Davao City. Bello said inmates overpowered a guard during
a Bible session at the prison and then looted additional weaons from
an armory.
   All the hostages were members of the Joyful Assemblies of God, a
Protestant group.
   The leader of the convicts was identified as Mohammed Naser
Samparani, a former air force soldier convicted of murder. He had
threatened to kill Miss Hamill unless authorities provided a getaway
vehicle by 4 p.m. Tuesday. Bella said.
   Samparani then changed his mind and said the inmates wanted to
flee the prison immediately.
   The convicts emerged a few minutes later with their captives and
began firing, the military said.
   Samparani and a 16-year-old female hostage were killed then. The
remaining inmates withdrew into the compound with the other hostages.
   Five hostages escaped in the next hour and told authorities at
least four other captives were dead.
   They included Miss Hamill, 36, who had been in Davao City one
month, and a 9-year-old boy.
   Officials quoted them as saying the captors also raped some of
the female hostages.
   Brig. Gen. Mariano Baccay, the regional military commander, said
none of the hostages was killed in the military assault.
   Police said most of the inmates had escaped in April from the
Davao Penal Colony and seized several hostages to protest conditions
at the prison.
   They surrendered after being promised they would be transferred
to the Muntinlupa prison, in a Manila suburb, but they were not
moved.
