<HEAD>Crack Addict Charged With Killing Woman Whose Screams Were Ignored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack addict was arrested Tuesday in the
stabbing death of woman whose screams were ignored by neighbors
until an hour after the attack allegedly began, police said.
   Franklin Rivera, a 21-year-old handyman, was taken into custody
at a subway station in the New York City borough of Brooklyn, said
Deputy Chief Francis X. Smith.
   Rivera allegedly broke through a rear window of Ruth Velez's
apartment in a three-story house to commit a burglary about 10 p.m.
Saturday, Smith said.
   Velez, 39, pulled out a kitchen knife to defend herself, and the
intruder grabbed it from her, stabbed her in the stomach and beat
her around the head, Smith said.
   Neighbors heard screams but did not call the police until shortly
after 11 p.m., Smith said.
   Rivera had worked for 10 weeks for a contractor who stored
equipment in the garage of the house where Velez lived, Smith said.
   Smith said neighbors should not be blamed for not calling police
right away.
   ``They misevaluated the degree of urgency of the screams,'' he
said.
   Rivera told detectives he had been taking crack for the last four
or five days, Smith said.
