<DOCNO> AP890815-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:ChorusMaster Adv17   08-15 0971</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Chorus Master, Adv 17,0998</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs, Aug. 17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Unsung Hero of Opera</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there can be an unsung hero in opera,
especially in a monumental extravaganza such as ``Die Meistersinger
von Nuremberg,'' it would have to be the chorus master.
   Despite the central role of the 97 singers, the largest chorus in
any Seattle Opera production to date, the man charged with welding
them into a crisp ensemble with flawless diction and perfect pitch
gets no major billing and takes no bows.
   What George Fiore does take is unabashed pride in his work.
   ``I'm always in charge, because I have to be,'' he said. ``I get
very good results with the chorus.''
   In an interview at a rehearsal earlier this month, Fiore waxed
enthusiastic during a parade scene that brings more than 100 people
on stage in the third act.
   ``You see that? Active, energetic. They really are the populace,
not just 100 sticks, people singing notes,'' he said.
   The 63-year-old Fiore became chorus master five years ago after
occasional work as associate chorus master, coach for principal
singers and other jobs with the opera dating to 1968.
   ``I brought him in,'' said Speight Jenkins, general director of
the Seattle Opera. ``I don't think there's a better chorus master in
the country.''
   Jenkins, who spent two years as host of the television series
``Live From the Met'' and eight as music critic for the New York
Post, said Fiore's crowning achievement was a fight scene with 135
people on stage in the second act.
   ``For three minutes they are in a wild melee, singing and
fighting on stage. Then the night watchman's horn is heard, and
everyone vanishes,'' Jenkins said.
   The libretto calls for 16 separate vocal lines _ for example,
four soprano sections _ each exchanging epithets. In previous modern
stagings, Jenkins said, ``they simply have each line of people sing
all the words.''
   Director Francois Rochaix, however, decided that to be true to
Wagner's libretto, half the singers in each line should sing one
epithet and the other half the response.
   ``People are going to hear a difference, a clarity of lines, I
hope,'' Jenkins said. ``George has done such extraordinary work that
the people are able to do this. He taught it to them (to sing)
faster than he ever thought Hermann (Michael) could conduct it.''
   With the slightest breakdown in timing, anything less than
perfect pitch and diction, the music would sink into cacophany.
   ``I think we've rehearsed that fight scene 30 or 40 times. It
hasn't fallen apart yet,'' Jenkins said.
   ``Die Meistersinger,'' one of the longest operas at six housrs,
poses other challenges as well. Total costs are likely to exceed
$1.6 million for seven performances Aug. 3-19.
   ``A (new) production on the scale of ours has not been done since
the Met's (The Metropolitan Opera) in 1962,'' Jenkins said.
``Everybody likes to do `Die Meistersinger.' It's just that they
can't afford to produce it.''
   A quarter or more of the cost goes for costumes, sets and other
one-time expenses.
   Under a contract with the American Guild of Musical Artists,
full-time choristers get $8 an hour for rehearsal time, plus a
performance fee, for a total of about $1,200 for ``Die
Meistersinger,'' while auxiliaries earn as little as about $100
total, said Monte Jacobson, a soprano in the chorus since the
company was founded 25 years ago.
   ``They all have jobs like anybody else,'' Fiore said. `Some of
them are housewives, of course, but that's a full-time job, too.''
   Regulars, including those from past seasons, must survive an
audition every two years. About 190 singers were heard in special
auditions to choose the 61 auxiliary choristers in ``Die
Meistersinger.''
   The chorus, which began rehearsals May 18, sings the opening and
closing lyrics, and ``Die Meistersinger'' is one of handful of
operas in which ``the people'' comprise a central role.
   ``Wagner composed this opera as a strong statement of the German
people,'' Jenkins said. ``In each of the acts, the people have a
very strong role to play.''
   Set in 16th-century Nuremberg, the opera tells the story of Hans
Sachs, a cobbler and master singer who winds up serving as principal
judge in a song contest among the town's apprentice master singers.
To the victor goes the hand and fortune of Eva, the beautiful
daughter of the town's wealthy goldsmith and the object of Sach's
own unrequited love.
   The cast includes Roger Roloff as Sachs, soprano Helen Donath as
Eva, and Julian Patrick, Benn Heppner and Bergitta Svenden in other
lead roles.
   ``Die Meistersinger'' is the seventh new Wagner production for
Jenkins. Since he took over in 1983, the Seattle Opera has risen to
No. 6 in attendance nationwide, and Wagner News has declared it
``without a doubt the leading Wagner company in America.''
   The company is best known for annual stagings of Wagner's
four-part ``Der Ring des Niebelungen'' from 1975 to 1987, the first
nine years in English as well as German.
   Jenkins, hired largely to overhaul the Ring, presided over new
productions of ``Die Walkure'' in 1985 and of ``Das Rheingold,''
``Siegfried'' and ``Die Gotterdammerung'' in 1986.
   Despite the company's overall financial health, annual
productions ended in 1988 because of persistent operating deficits
for the $3.5 million summer extravaganza and what Jenkins saw as a
lack of sufficient local corporate and individual donations. He has
said he hopes to revive the Ring for performances every two or three
years, starting in 1991.
   The Ring's legacy is evidence this year with the return of
Michael as conducter, Rochaix as director, Joan Sullivan as lighting
director and soloists Patrick and Roloff, who sang Wotan in 1984,
1986 and 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Thurs Aug. 17</NOTE>
