<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-15 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0867</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock price kept rising amid
unconfirmed reports that several suitors have expressed interest in
buying the airline company.
   UAL rose $1.50 to close at $258.50 a share Monday in New York
Stock Exchange trading. The increase followed a gain of about 56
percent last week following a $240-a-share takeover proposal to UAL,
parent of United Airlines, from Los Angeles investor Marvin Davis.
   The New York leveraged buyout firms Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co
and Forstmann Little &amp; Co. also reportedly have expressed interest
to UAL officials in buying the Chicago-based company, while
officials of New York-based Pan Am Corp. have stated they were
interested in a possible merger.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in June
as business sales fell 0.3 percent, the government said. Analysts
said the report indicated slow but continued economic growth with
low inflation.
   Inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as
production exceeds demand, a process that sometimes leads to a loss
of jobs as businesses cut their output. Economists, however, said
the inventories reported Monday are not unusually large in
proportion to sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction of houses, apartments and
condominiums fell 8 percent in the second quarter to the lowest rate
in more than six years, said the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill
Information Services Co.
   Residential starts during the year's second three months totaled
388,926 units, down from 420,843 units during the same period a year
earlier, the business research company said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush selected White House aide
Richard C. Breeden, an attorney and banking specialist, to be
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Breeden, 39, has served in a variety of capacities under Bush,
most recently as White House point man on the savings-and-loan
restructuring legislation. The SEC nomination, announced Monday,
requires Senate confirmation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former trader in the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange's yen futures pit became the 13th futures trader to plead
innocent to charges stemming from the federal probe of suspected
fraud in the world's largest futures markets.
   Michael Sidel, 42, of suburban Lake Forest, stood silently before
U.S. District Judge George M. Marovich as his lawyer entered the
plea Monday.
   Sidel, accused of defrauding his customers at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, is charged with one count of violating the
Commodities Exchange Act and one count of mail fraud.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation that will
speed $897 million in assistance to farmers whose crops he said had
been battered this year by ``the forces of nature.''
   The bulk of the aid _ $400 million _ will go to wheat farmers
whose winter harvest in Kansas and other states was devastated by
drought.
   At the other extreme, the Disaster Assistance Act signed Monday
will compensate farmers in the South and elsewhere whose rice,
soybean, cotton and other crops were wiped out by rain, wind and
floods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. Chairman Colby Chandler testified
he knew getting into instant photography could mean a lawsuit from
competitor Polaroid Corp. but said he was convinced his company
would win.
   Chandler was called to testify Monday in a U.S. District Court
trial to determine how many dollars in damages his company will have
to pay Polaroid. An earlier federal court decision established that
Kodak infringed on patents of Polaroid, the Cambridge, Mass.-based
pioneer of instant photography.
   Polaroid is seeking nearly $12 billion, while Kodak has argued it
should pay $177 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has agreed to pay
$975,000 in fines to 10 states in an effort to clear its name and
operate freely around the country despite a guilty plea to federal
securities crimes, officials said.
   Drexel said Monday it expects to pay $11.5 million overall to
settle with the states, avoid litigation and retain its ability to
do business, but some states still want to revoke the New York
investment firm's brokerage licenses, according to securities
regulators.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers and school administrators got their
first look at Turner Broadcasting System Inc.'s daily news show for
use in the classroom, a commercial-free alternative to the sponsored
news program that Whittle Communications plans to launch next spring.
   The first program of CNN Newsroom was carried early Monday on
Cable News Network. Teachers are being encourged to record the show
and use it in the classroom to help augment their course plans.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks retreated further in quiet trading Monday from near-record
levels reached last week, as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
fell 6.07 points to 2,677.92.
   Bond prices plummeted in a second straight selloff.
   The dollar finished higher against major foreign currencies in
brisk trading, extending last week's strong rally.
   Copper prices surged, grain and soybean prices dropped, energy
futures were mostly lower, precious metals rose modestly, and meat
and pork futures fell.
</TEXT>
