<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HousingConstruction     08-15 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Construction,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Housing Construction Fell 8 Percent in 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction of houses, apartments and
condominiums fell 8 percent in the second quarter, according to the
F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.
   Residential starts during the second three months of the year
totaled 388,926 units, down from 420,843 units during the same
period a year earlier, the McGraw-Hill Inc. division said Monday.
   The second-quarter construction rate was the lowest in more than
six years, the result of a surge in mortgage rates, George A.
Christie, vice president and chief economist for F.W. Dodge, said in
a news release.
   ``Although rates have fallen sharply since spring, building
activity will remain sluggish for a few more months until
inventories are pared down. We're looking for a fourth-quarter
pickup in housing starts,'' Christie said.
   Here is a list of the top 10 metropolitan areas in order of the
number of dwelling units started during the second quarter, followed
by the percentage change from a year earlier.
   1. Riverside-San Bernardino, Calif., 12,729, down 20 percent.
   2. Washington, D.C., 12,325, down 6 percent.
   3. Los Angeles-Long Beach, Calif., 11,197, down 12 percent.
   4. Atlanta, 8,469, down 34 percent.
   5. Chicago, 7,121, up 3 percent.
   6. Detroit, 5,872, down 25 percent.
   7. West Palm Beach-Boca Raton-Delray Beach, Fla., 5,869, up 29
percent.
   8. Las Vegas, 5,723, down 15 percent.
   9. Philadelphia, 5,662, down 8 percent.
   10. Baltimore, 5,538, up 32 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
