<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     08-15 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in several
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 8.01 percent, up from 7.94 percent last
week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.83 percent, up from 7.70 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 8.09
percent on July 24 and six-month bills averaged 8.08 percent on June
19.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.29 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,797.50 and 8.26 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,604.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.12
percent last week, up from 7.73 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
