<FIRST>r f PM-AutoPrices     08-15 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Prices,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan Sets Some '90 Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for 1990 models of the Nissan Sentra, 240SX
and Maxima cars will rise an average of 1.5 percent, or $124, over
the price of comparably equipped 1989 models, the Japan-based
automaker said.
   The $13,249 base price for the five-speed 240SX coupe will remain
the same as for 1989, R.J. Thomas, vice president of Nissan Motor
Corp. in U.S.A., the U.S. marketing arm of Nissan Motor Corp., said
Monday.
   The base price of the Maxima, Nissan's top-of-the-line offering,
will rise an average of 1.1 percent to $17,699, and the price for
the base Sentra will go up 4.3 percent to $7,299.
   Prices for the rest of Nissan's 1990 cars and trucks will be
announced later, the company said.
</TEXT>
