<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Dorfman-U.S.News     08-15 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dorfman-U.S. News,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Columnist Dan Dorfman Under Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Language in 9th graf may be objectionable to some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
investigating whether USA Today financial columnist Dan Dorfman
wittingly or unwittingly was used by individuals who gave him
information in order to manipulate stock prices, according to U.S.
News &amp; World Report.
   The SEC investigation deals with Centaur Partners, a
Maryland-based investment partnership that Dorfman has written about
repeatedly in the past 14 months, the weekly news magazine reports
in its Aug. 21 issue, quoting unidentified sources.
   The SEC is investigating whether Centaur, in establishing initial
positions in several prominent companies, may be manipulating the
market in the companies' stock, U.S. News said.
   When Dorfman reported that Centaur bought shares in these
companies, the companies' stock price rose. The question is whether
Centaur is selling shares in these companies to investors, leaving
those investors holding the bag when takeover bids don't
materialize, the magazine reported.
   Maryland businessman Melvyn Estrin, president of one of the
limited partnerships that make up Centaur, denied to the magazine
that Centaur tried to manipulate stock prices or that it ever gave
Dorfman any information.
   Dorfman also denied that he had been a party to any manipulation.
   ``I'm so careful and sensitive about what I do,'' he said Monday
night when reached at his home for comment.
   Dorfman, who also is a commentator on Cable News Network's
``Moneyline'' program, said he knew nothing about any investigation.
   ``I have not been contacted by the SEC, the New York Stock
Exchange or anybody else,'' he said. ``I think it's a lot of crap.''
   Tom Petruno, Dorfman's editor at USA Today, also said he knew of
no investigation.
   ``We have no idea where U.S. News got this information or who its
sources are,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the SEC told the magazine that the agency could
not confirm or deny any such investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
