<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-15 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Share Prices Also Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar climbed today against the Japanese
yen for the fourth consecutive trading day, and share prices on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange also gained.
   The dollar closed at 142.20 yen, up 0.27 yen from Monday's close
of 141.93 yen. It opened at 142.40 yen and moved between 142.20 yen
and 142.70 yen.
   The dollar now has gained 3.35 yen over the last four trading
days.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which declined
41.34 points Monday, climbed 139.07 points, or 0.40 percent, on
Tuesday, closing at 34,810.69.
   The dollar opened higher following a rising trend overseas and
moved upward during the morning session.
   At one point, the Bank of Japan sold about $200 million in
efforts to check the dollar's rise, said a dealer from Mitsubishi
Bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Dollar-buying cooled in the afternoon, he added.
   A trader at Nippon Kangyo Kakumaru Securities said stock trading
was relatively brisk even though many market participants are taking
summer vacations this week.
   ``Even though the volume was only 400 million shares, the cost of
the amount bought and sold was much higher than that traded at the
same time last year,'' he said.
   The trader said the buying of high-priced stocks such as Sony and
TDK, which had been the focus of Monday's trading, had ended during
the morning.
   Steel shares attracted buyer attention for some time, he added.
</TEXT>
