<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0739EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-15 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar consolidated at higher levels in
early European trading today.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was very quiet.
Financial institutions were closed in Italy for a national holiday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose for the fourth consecutive trading day, closing up
0.27 yen at 142.20 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 142.30
yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.9443 West German marks, up from 1.9395; 1.6770
Swiss francs, up from 1.6760; 6.5710 French francs, up from 6.5535;
2.1885 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1832; 1.1785 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1775.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5771 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5840 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at $364.85 a troy ounce, compared with late
Monday's $364. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $364.70.
   In Zurich, the bid was $364.60, compared with $363.50 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.42 to close at $365.72.
   ``There's nothing going on,'' said one bullion dealer in London.
`` Gold is still in the doldrums.''
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.21 a troy ounce, unchanged from
late Monday.
</TEXT>
