<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BreedenProfile     08-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Breeden Profile,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Richard C. Breeden: Lawyer, Banking Specialist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SEC-Breeden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you ask people about Richard C. Breeden,
the savvy Washington lawyer nominated to head the Securities and
Exchange Commission, they always start off by calling him ``very
intelligent'' or ``extremely bright.''
   ``He has the experienced, good mind that will stand him in good
stead,'' former SEC Chairman Roderick M. Hills said Monday after the
nomination of Breeden, an architect of the savings and loan industry
bailout, was announced.
   Even people who question the wisdom of the appointment, like Sen.
Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich, start their criticism with ``Mr.
Breeden is highly intelligent and did fine work on the S&amp;L reform
package ...''
   One industry source, who did not wish to be identified, said that
because of his keen mind Breeden does not ``suffer fools gladly''
and could be abrasive.
   But when Breeden was gathering information for a task force
chaired by then-Vice President George Bush, on what financial
regulatory rules needed to be amended or scrapped, said the source,
``We sent him some very difficult, complicated stuff.
   ``Usually, people in that position read it and don't understand
it or pass it on to someone else to read it. But when we met with
him it was obvious he had read it and understood it all.''
   Industry observers believe Breeden's wide-ranging experience will
be an asset in the SEC position.
   ``He comes to this job with a fairly broad knowledge of the
financial services industry,'' said Joseph R. Hardiman, president of
the National Association of Securities Dealers, which oversees
over-the-counter stock trading.
   A 1972 graduate of Stanford University and a 1975 graduate of
Harvard Law School, Breeden practiced securities law on Wall Street
with the prestigious firm Cravath, Swaine &amp; Moore. He also worked
for the Washington office of the politically powerful Texas law firm
Baker &amp; Botts.
   From 1981-82, Breeden was an executive assistant to the
undersecretary of labor.
   ``He's been a practitioner. He's been in government. He knows
banking,'' said the industry source. ``He may get rid of a lot of
junk along the way but he'll be doing his job.''
   The White House announcement ended months of speculation about
who would succeed departing SEC Chairman David S. Ruder who
announced in May he was stepping down.
   In contrast to Ruder, 60, an academic and legal expert who
managed to keep his distance from the free-market philosophy of the
Reagan administration, Breeden, 39, is known as a fierce fighter for
the policies of George Bush.
   Breeden helped write the Bush plan for bailing out the nation's
ailing savings and loan industry and then shepherded through
Congress the plan to spend more than $150 billion over three decades
to deal with the nation's biggest money problem since the Depression.
   Before that, Breeden, a Manhattan Beach, Calif., native who now
lives in the Virginia suburbs outside Washington, worked for and
with Bush in a number of capacities.
   Breeden, now a presidential assistant for issues analysis, also
helped fashion administration policy in dealing with the Exxon
Valdez oil spill.
   He helped candidate Bush prepare for the 1988 presidential
debates with Michael Dukakis.
   From 1982 to 1985, he was deputy counsel to Bush as vice
president. Breeden also served as staff director on the task force
Bush chaired to reform the financial regulatory system.
   ``I'm not sure if he's a regulator or a deregulator,'' said
Gordon Macklin, chief executive officer of the San Francisco
investment banking firm of Hambrecht and Quist.
   Macklin, who has known Breeden since 1984, said the wiry and
intense lawyer is `` interested in efficient, cost effective
regulation. He knows the inter-relationships in the world of
financial services, he has a broad view of what's out there and an
extensive knowledge.''
</TEXT>
