<SECOND>PM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Stock Higher Amid Reports Of More Suitors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf with UAL no comment, edits to conform; Picks
up 18th graf, Officials of ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of UAL Corp. shares continued to rise
with unconfirmed reports that several additional suitors were
interested in aquiring the airline company.
   UAL rose $1.50 to $258.50 a share Monday in New York Stock
Exchange trading. The increase followed a gain of some 56 percent
last week following a $240 a share takeover proposal to UAL, parent
of United Airlines, from Los Angeles investor Marvin Davis.
   The New York leveraged buyout firms Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
and Forstmann Little &amp; Co. also reportedly have expressed interest
in buying the company, while officials of New York-based Pan Am
Corp. have stated they were interested in a possible merger.
   ``It basically says the sophisticated players in the market ...
believe that there will be other bidders for the company,'' said
Robert Joedicke, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York. He said the amount of money that will be needed to take over
UAL limits the number of potential bidders.
   ``It's not something anybody and everybody will become involved
in,'' Joedicke said.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in its editions today that the
airline, which is negotiating on a new contract with its pilots
union, is also considering a possible management-led employee buyout.
   Weekend talks between UAL and the pilots apparently were aimed at
determining whether the airline's unions might agree to enough
concessions to make an employee buyout bid viable, the Journal said.
UAL would also have to win the support of the machinists union and
other employees.
   United's pilots in the past have expressed an interest in buying
the company.
   Kathy Hardin, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association
unit at United, said Monday the union's financial and legal advisers
were studying efforts to take over the company.
   UAL spokesman Robert Doughty said today the airline had no
comment on the report. ``It is our policy not to confirm or deny
negotiations,'' he said.
   Analysts have said UAL could fetch as much as $6.75 billion and
prospective bids likely would include a management buyout plan.
   The Journal has quoted officials it did not name as saying UAL
had received nibbles from several groups, including companies that
showed interest in Eagan, Minn.-based NWA Inc., parent of Northwest
Airlines.
   In addition to Davis; Kohlberg Kravis, Forstmann Little and Pan
Am were among those who unsuccessfully made takeover proposals for
NWA, which was sold to a group headed by Los Angeles investor Alfred
Checchi for $3.65 billion.
   Officials of UAL refused to comment Monday on the report of
additional bidders.
   ``We neither confirm or deny any other bids,'' UAL spokesman
Doughty said Monday.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts also remained silent on the issue.
   ``The firm has said nothing and haven't made any comment'' on
whether it is interested in acquiring UAL, said spokesman Tom Daly.
   Officials of Forstmann Little also declined comment.
   Pan Am said it would make an offer if UAL's board asked it to.
   ``They have not publicly said they were up for sale,'' said Pan
Am spokeswoman Elizabeth Manners. ``My understanding is that they
did say they were going to explore some alternative.''
   Last week, in response to Davis' overture, UAL's board of
directors announced it would explore all possible financial and
strategic alternatives open to the company.
</TEXT>
