<FIRST>b f PM-WallStreet10am     08-15 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0259</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened higher today behind a
firming bond market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 9.29 points at
2,687.21 after 30 minutes of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Advancing issues outpaced declines by about 7 to 5 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 369 issues up, 258 down and 391 unchanged
in early going.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.11 million shares.
   Wall Street observers said investors were taking their cue from a
strengthening bond market.
   ``As the bond market goes so goes the stock market,'' said Larry
Wachtel, vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``A firm
bond market helped stocks open higher.''
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.51 to 191.88.
   The American Stock Exchange market value index had gained 0.27 to
379.27.
   On Monday, the stock market retreated in quiet trading as the
bond market slumped following recent reports that suggested the
economy is not as weak as expected. Analysts said the reports
diminished chances that the Federal Reserve would lower interest
rates.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 6.07 points to finish at
2,677.92.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
986 issues down, 473 up and 532 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 142.01 million shares, down from 197.55
million in the previous session.
