<HEAD>Weather Service's 30-day Forecast Boosts Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures opened higher today on
the Chicago Board of Trade after getting a boost from the National
Weather Service's 30-day forecast.
   The forecast issued Monday called for below-normal precipit`tion
and above-norlal temperatures in major crop areas.
   An Agriculture Department report that noted some detdrioration in
soybean crop quality may have contributed to today's early gains.
   Analysts said the good showing in the soybean and corn pits
should spill over into the wheat market.
   Wheat also should get support from Algeria's bid for U.S. wheat
under the export bonus program, which subsidizds grain sales to
foreign nations, the analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was a { cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.99{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 3\ cents higher with September at $2.31 a bushel; oats were
} cent to 2 cents higher with September at $1.38 a bushel; soybeans
were 3{ cents to 11{ cents higher with August at $6.14 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .23 cent lower with August at 74.37
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .27 cent lower with
August at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to .37 cent
lower with August at 47.07 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.40 cent to .60 cent a pound with August at 24.75 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mostly lower and pork futures were
mixed in Monday's trading.
