<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market slipped from earlier highs and
turned mixed in moderate trading today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 4.36 points to
2,682.28 at noon EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 6.64 points an
hour earlier.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by a margin of about 10 to
9 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 657 issues down, 611 up and
555 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 72.99 million shares.
   Analysts said the market opened higher in response to a firming
bond market after declining on Monday.
   The stock market has moved in tandem with bonds since Friday,
when the credit market plunged in response to a rise in retail sales
that renewed inflationary concerns and diminished hopes that
interest rates would go lower.
   But the stock market began to slip late this morning in what
analysts said was a continuation of the correction phase after its
recent runup.
   The market has climbed more than 10 percent since late June and
about 30 percent since last fall. Wall Street analysts say the
current market is now overbought and could drift for several
sessions before resuming an upward march.
   ``We could see some more zigzagging today without any sustained
movement either way until the market works out the overbought
condition,'' said Philip Roth, analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.16 at 191.53.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index stood at
379.05, a gain of 0.05.
