<FIRST>u f BC-AutoPrices     08-15 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Prices,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Tentative Car Prices Up Average of 5 Percent for '90</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said today tentative
prices for its 1990 cars will increase an average of 5 percent over
comparably equipped 1989 models.
   Nearly half the boost is caused by the installation of
driver-side air bags in all of Chrysler's U.S.-made cars, expected
to be about 1 million vehicles in the 1990 model year, spokeswoman
Karen Stewart said.
   She said the average air bag will cost a consumer $450, less than
what Chrysler pays to buy and install them. She refused to say
exactly what the automaker is spending on the systems.
   The rest of Chrysler's price increase stems from economic
reasons, including higher material and labor costs, she said.
   The federal government requires driver-side air bags or automatic
seat belts on all cars made in the United States after Sept. 1.
   Earlier this month, General Motors Corp. announced a tentative
average price increase of 3.4 percent and Ford Motor Co. said its
car prices could go up as much as 4.8 percent for the coming model
year.
   Stewart said a few of the 1990-model cars offered by the nation's
No. 3 automaker will decrease in price while the rest will increase
between 2.8 percent and 6.9 percent. She said she did not have a
list of all models and their price increases.
   Chrysler's final retail prices will be announced in September or
October, she said.
</TEXT>
