<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Ashton-Tate     08-15 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ashton-Tate,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Software Maker Announces Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORRANCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Software maker Ashton-Tate Corp. said
Tuesday it would lay off at least 15 percent of its employees, or
about 260 workers, and cut other costs in the face of expected
additional losses.
   Last month, Ashton-Tate reported a $19.8 million second-quarter
net loss on revenue of $59.5 million. Its president and chief
operating officer, Luther J. Nussbaum, resigned and his duties were
assumed by board chairman Edward M. Esber Jr.
   ``The (workforce) reduction will be a minimum of 15 percent,''
according to Ashton-Tate spokeswoman Linda Duttenhayer, who said the
company now has 1,731 employees worldwide.
   Ashton-Tate, once a top manufacturer of computer software,
recently has faced intense competition in its core business of
software for the storage and retrieval of information in personal
computers.
   It said reduced revenues, together with anticipated job-cutting
costs and other expenses, may result in a larger operating loss for
the third quarter, which ends Sept. 30, than in the second quarter
that ended June 30.
   The company said its previously announced program to reduce
inventories on the shelves of U.S. distributors and resellers is
continuing.
   Ashton-Tate also is going through a transition to a newer version
of its dBASE IV software, and said shipments of the current version
are expected to decline as customers wait for the new version.
   Esber said he will directly oversee the database business.
   ``This is another important step in restoring Ashton-Tate's
profitability,'' Esber said. ``The company's cost-reduction program
will result in greater focus and execution on projects with the
biggest impact on near-term revenues.''
</TEXT>
