<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1309EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     08-15 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Penney, Dayton Hudson Post Earnings Gains for Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. said Tuesday that improved sales in its
fashion apparel business helped it post a 21.2 percent profit
increase in the second quarter, while earnings doubled for another
retailer, Dayton Hudson Corp.
   The Dallas-based Penney reported it earned $98 million, or 74
cents per share, in the three months ended July 29, compared with
$81 million, or 61 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 5.1 percent to $3.51 billion from
$3.34 billion.
   ``We expect to build on the current strong sales momentum,
particularly in apparel lines, during the second half,'' said Penney
Chairman William R. Howell. ``Our significant sales growth has shown
that our reputation for fashion apparel is growing.''
   In the first half of the year, Penney earned $226 million, or
$1.71 per share, up 6.8 percent from $212 million, or $1.57 a share,
a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose 4.5 percent to $6.92 billion from $6.62
billion a tear earlier.
   From Minneapolis, Dayton Hudson said it earned a record $56
million, or 72 cents a share, in the three months ended July 29, up
from $28 million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue increased 15 percent to $3.10 billion from
$2.69 billion a year ago.
   ``Strong performance by our three major operating companies led
to the record earnings,'' Kenneth A. Macke, chairman and chief
executive of Dayton Hudson, said in a statement.
   Its Mervyn's chain had an 18 percent increase in revenue from the
1988 second quarter, followed by Target stores at 17 percent and
Dayton Hudson Department Store Co. at 7 percent. Lechmere stores'
revenue was about the same as during last year's second quarter, the
company said.
   Pretax earnings were $10 million higher than they otherwise would
have been because costs related to the closing of its Branden's
stores were higher than the company had provided for in the fourth
quarter 1988.
   Six-month net earnings rose 62.7 percent to $96 million, or $1.23
per share, versus $59 million, or 70 cents a share, for the same
period in 1988. Revenue for the first six months increased 13
percent to $5.92 billion from $5.24 billion a year ago.
   Dayton Hudson operates 675 stores in 38 states.
</TEXT>
