<FIRST>r f BC-CoalStrike-Nun     08-15 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coal Strike-Nun,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Charge Dismissed Against Nun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABINGDON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contempt charges have been dismissed against
a nun accused of delaying coal trucks during a miners' strike by
driving slowly.
   Sister Bernadette Kenny was among several people charged July 12
in Dickenson County with impeding Pittston Coal Group trucks in
violation of a court order. The United Mine Workers have been on
strike against Pittston since April 5.
   U.S. District Judge Jackson Kiser on Monday ruled that the
government had failed to show that the truck behind the nun's motor
home was a Pittston vehicle.
   The nun, who was delivering medical supplies at the time of her
arrest, said she was not trying to block coal trucks but was driving
slowly because of the size of her vehicle and the narrow, winding
road.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
