<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-15 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0234</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market continued mixed in afternoon
trading with blue-chip issues registering the biggest gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 9.11 points to
2,687.03 at 2 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 4.36 points
at noon.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 107.01 million shares.
   A spate of buying by institutions was pushing blue-chip shares
higher, but the broader market lagged. Traders said Ford Co. and
General Motors Corp. stocks had come alive after recent lackluster
performances.
   The market opened higher today in response to a firming bond
market after declining on Monday.
   Prices slumped late in the morning in what analysts said was
ongoing consolidation after its recent rally.
   The market has climbed more than 10 percent since late June and
about 30 percent since last fall. Wall Street analysts say the
current market is now overbought and is drifting before resuming an
upward march.
   ``We could see some more zigzagging today without any sustained
movement either way until the market works out the overbought
condition,'' said Philip Roth, analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.44 at 191.81.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.38
to 379.38.
</TEXT>
