<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Stronger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar headed higher Tuesday in light
European trading. Gold prices also rose.
   Trading was subdued due to the closure of markets in France,
Italy and Belgium in observance of the Assumption Day religous
holiday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose for the fourth consecutive trading day to 142.20
Japanese yen from 141.93 yen. Later, in London, it edged up to
142.30 yen.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5735 from $1.5840 late
Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.9500 West German marks, up from 1.9395; 1.6790 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6760; 6.5835 French francs, up from 6.5535; 2.1905 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1832; and 1.1822 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1775.
   Gold gained in London to a late bid price of $365.75 a troy
ounce, up from $364.00 bid Monday. In Zurich, gold jumped to $366.25
an ounce from $363.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.42 to $365.72 an ounce.
   Silver settled in London at $5.24 a troy ounce, up from $5.21 bid
late Monday.
</TEXT>
