<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Due to computer problems, some market information has been delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back slightly but
continued mixed in lackluster trading today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.12 points to
2,683.04 at 3 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 9.11 at 2 p.m.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 125.49 million shares.
   The market opened higher today in response to a firming bond
market after declines in the previous two sessions.
   After zigzagging through the morning, late-comers and
computerized buying strategies helped push blue-chip shares higher
shortly after midday. But the broader market lagged and the market
began retreating.
   ``It's mostly random action today. The market is continuing a
seesaw action,'' said Michael Metz, vice president and technical
analyst for Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Traders said new economic data due out later in the week,
including housing starts, merchandise trade and consumer prices,
could put a spark back in the market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.19 at 191.56.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was 0.36
higher at 379.36.
</TEXT>
