<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-MaquiladoraStrike     08-15 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Maquiladora Strike,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Retake Assembly Plants Closed By Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYNOSA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of workers tore down black and
red strike flags, unlocked gates and poured back to their jobs
Tuesday at American-owned assembly plants closed over a union power
struggle.
   ``We're waiting for the other union to come and try to take us
out,'' said Alberto de la Torre, 22, an assembly line worker at the
Nibco valve plant in this northern border city.
   ``We've been inactive for three weeks. We need our jobs,'' said
Marco Antonio Becerra, a Nibco section chief.
   Maquiladoras are foreign-owned plants that take advantage of
Mexico's lower wage rates to assemble products to sell in the United
States.
   About 900 workers, both men and women, defied a rival union and,
unlocking gates, reopened 15 American plants closed July 25 when one
union leader attempted to take control from another.
   Rafael Morales put up strike banners and locked the gates of
plants organized under leader Abel Hernandez.
   About 2,000 workers were idled by the strike, although they said
the companies continued to pay their salaries.
   Morales argued that Hernandez no longer could legally represent
the workers because Hernandez had withdrawn from the Federation of
Mexican Laborers, or CTM.
   But the workers said Tuesday that they want Hernandez as their
union leader whether or not he's allied with the CTM.
   They're tired, they said, of waiting for government and judicial
authorities to end the strike.
   ``We want the government to intervene. We want them to respect
the contract we have with Hernandez,'' said Aurelio Veraza, a Nibco
supervisor.
   Hernandez, who had called for workers to return to their jobs,
said Tuesday that he did so because ``they don't have any reason to
stay out.''
   Morales was not immediately available for comment.
   No American manager was on the premises of any of the plants as
the workers calmly walked past the two or three guards at each gate.
   Once inside, each person went to work at his or her station,
taking orders only from the supervisors involved in the retaking of
the plants.
   The workers contend that Morales acted illegally when he forced
the plants closed.
   ``Only workers have the right to strike,'' said Veraza. ``We're
happy with the work the Americans give us. They're giving us chances
to advance.''
   The state labor arbitration board had ruled in favor of Morales,
but the plants took the case to federal court asking that Hernandez
be declared the official representative.
   The federal court has yet to issue a ruling in the case.
   All the workers interviewed said they expected Morales supporters
to attempt to remove them from the plants.
   No action had been taken by the rival union, however, hours after
the plants reopened.
   Two American companies, Invacare Corp. of Elyria, Ohio, and
Pilling de Mexico of Pennsylvania, have said they'll pull out of
Mexico before being forced to sign a contract with Morales.
   And the workers said Tuesday that they're concerned that if the
plants aren't in operation, they'll close down.
   ``If the plants close down nobody is going to make sure we have
jobs. We're not taking action against anybody. We just want to hold
on to our jobs,'' said Nibco's Alonso Rivera.
   Salinas has not made a statement favoring one union leader or the
other.
   Plant managers have made several trips to Mexico City seeking an
end to the conflict through the federal government.
   No decision had come Tuesday from either the courts or government
officials.
   Don King, plant manager for the newly opened West Bend plant,
said Tuesday that the workers' action proves their loyalty to
Hernandez.
   ``It's a loud signal from the Mexican people to the government
that they want their jobs and they want to work and work under the
representation of Abel Hernandez,'' said King, contacted in at the
Economic Development Corp. in McAllen, Texas, just across the border
from Reynosa.
   Asked when the American managers would return to the plants, King
said, ``We have to wait and see what happens. We are continuing to
try to solve this legally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
