<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-15 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deteriorated Soybean and Corn Crop Boosts Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, with the rise triggered by reports of
deteriorating crop conditions.
   Monday's crop ratings from the Department of Agriculture showed a
decline in the condition of the soybean crop, particularly in Iowa
and Illinois, due to lack of moisture.
   ``There was also a strike overnight in Brazil,'' said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago. ``While it did
not affect Brazilian soybean shipments, the psychology of that
didn't hurt the beans.''
   Soybean prices were also supported by the National Weather
Service's 30-day forecast _ released Monday _ which calls for
below-normal precipitation and above-normal temperatures.
   Corn futures were boosted by the announcement that Mexico would
be in the market for 400,000 metric tons of corn and rumors that the
Soviet Union would also enter the market.
   Wheat futures were helped by light commercial purchases by
Algeria and carryover from the other markets, Gidel said.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.99 a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 5} cents higher with September at $2.33{ a bushel; oats
were 3{ cents to 3} cents higher with September at $1.40 a bushel;
soybeans were 7 cents to 15 cents higher with August at $6.17{ a
bushel.
</TEXT>
