<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TCI     08-15 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-TCI,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Giant Posts Larger Loss in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest
cable television systems operator, said Tuesday its second-quarter
loss widened to $63.6 million, citing higher interest expenses and
increased losses by its affiliates.
   The company's loss for the three months ended June 30 was three
times larger than its $21.9 million loss in the second quarter of
1988.
   Revenue for the second quarter rose 31.8 percent to $726.4
million from $551.0 million in the second quarter of 1988.
   The company said the increase in revenue was due to new cable
television subscribers, increases in rates and acquisitions.
   TCI said its operating income rose to $142.6 million from $125.4
million a year earlier.
   Interest expenses, however, climbed to $205.9 million from $138.8
million a year earlier, and its share of losses by affiliates rose
to $29.7 million from $400,000 in the second quarter of 1988.
   ``Consummation of the purchase of a 42.5 percent indirect
interest in SCI Holdings Inc. and the business combination involving
United Cable Television Corp. and United Artists Communications Inc.
have had a negative impact on TCI's earnings due to the cost of
servicing the indebtedness incurred to finance the transactions and
the resulting increase in depreciation and amortization,'' the
company said.
   For the first six months of the year, TCI recorded a net loss of
$115 million compared with a loss of $29.2 million in the first half
of 1988.
   Six-month revenue rose 31.4 percent to $1.38 billion from $1.05
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
