<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   08-15 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebuilding Carrier Boosts Schedule; Cuts Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with new grafs 1-10 to UPDATE with details of new fares,
schedule change; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, Eastern union ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, trying to rebuild from a crippling
strike and financial problems, on Tuesday expanded its schedule and
cut its already discounted fares while adding the lure of refundable
tickets.
   A union leader, meanwhile, said the new fare cuts for fall travel
by Eastern's healthier competitors would badly hurt Eastern's
efforts to rebuild without its unions.
   The discounts of up to $160 on a roundtrip fare were announced
Sunday by Trans World Airways and matched over the next two days by
carriers including Eastern, Delta Air Lines, Pan American World
Airways, United Airlines, American Airlines, Northwest Airlines,
Continental Airlines and USAir Group.
   George Brennan, Eastern's vice president for marketing, said
Eastern had already planned new discounts before the other carriers
and he said Eastern's fall promotion offers tickets that ``are much
easier to use and a much better value in most cases.''
   Besides competitive rates, Brennan said, Eastern's discounted
fares, beginning Sept. 7, have fewer restrictions and unlike the
other carriers, allow full refunds on unused tickets.
   ``We've been ... planning a major initiative for some time. Our
fares are very, very different. Our fares are like going to an ATM
(automatic teller machine) and theirs are like trying to get a
mortgage,'' Brennan said.
   Eastern will require only three- to-seven-day advance purchase
and its low fares are available nearly every day and carry no
restrictive penalties.
   The fares will affect all domestic markets, Eastern said.
   The carrier increased Tuesday from 350 to 390 daily flights by
adding 40 flights connecting Atlanta and destinations mostly in the
South and said it would fly 600 daily flights starting Sept. 7.
Eastern's rebuilding plan proposed to its creditors calls for 800
daily flights by year's end and an airline about two-thirds its
pre-strike size.
   While Eastern says it has hired enough new pilots and is keeping
up with maintenance despite its strike, it has been leasing five
planes and crews from sister carrier Continental Airlines. Brennan
said more planes and crews will be leased from Continental, owned by
Texas Air Corp. as is Eastern, to meet the September expansion but
that the practice is only temporary.
   Eastern union leaders, in their sixth month on strike, say the
airline's claims to be coming back are misleading because their
fares, as low as $39 one way, make it impossible to make money.
   ``The more they fly, the more they lose,'' Machinists District
100 President Charles Bryan told a rally in Miami on Saturday.
   Matell said Eastern's priority is winning back customers and the
company is pleased at 75 percent load figures as its tries to come
out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   ``Indications are we're getting a warm welcome back,'' Matell
said. ``That's not to say that after a 5-month strike operating 10
percent of our service that there isn't a major challenge in
rebuilding the airline.
   ``You have to first win back your customer base. We said in our
business plan we would lose hundreds of millions of dollars between
the comeback and the end of the year,'' Matell said.
   Bryan said in an interview Tuesday that consumers are going to go
with the other airlines because ``they are very reliable, first-line
carriers. They're not having phantom flights and people don't have
to worry about losing their money.
   ``If Eastern tries to go even lower than the rest of the
carriers, that's just going to compound their problems. It's going
to doom the rebuilding plan, which was already doomed,'' Bryan said.
   Before the strike that started March 4, Eastern normally had
around $1 billion in revenue per quarter. Last quarter, Eastern
posted $89.6 million in revenue.
   Management last week hurdled a major barrier to its rebuilding
efforts when a split in pilots union ranks resulted in at least 250
more pilots returning to work, boosting to 650 the union crossovers.
Eastern said with its own recruitment and training program it now
has the 1,700 pilots needed for its rebuilding plan.
   Eastern is still hiring flight attendants and mechanics to
replace strikers.
   The unions are backing a buyout bid by Chicago businessman Joseph
Ritchie and are lobbying in Washington for presidential and
congressional intervention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
