<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-15 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed in choppy trading Tuesday
following a modest rise overseas.
   Gold prices firmed. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery closed up $3.60 at $370.70 a troy
ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold
at $368.50 an ounce, up $3.80 from Monday.
   Dealers said the dollar remained locked into a fairly narrow
trading range in anticipation of new data that should shed more
light on the economy and the short-term outlook for U.S. interest
rates.
   The government is scheduled to release reports on industrial
activity and housing starts for July on Wednesday, merchandise trade
in June on Thursday, and the consumer price index on Friday.
   Some economists are predicting those reports will show continued
economic growth, lessening the possibility of lower interest rates.
   The dollar has been boosted in recent days on speculation that
interest rates won't fall any time soon. When rates remain firm,
dollar-denominated securities, such as bonds, become more attractive
to foreigners, and that increases the need for those investors to
exchange their currencies for dollars.
   The dollar headed higher in Europe, although trading was subdued
Tuesday due to the closing of markets in France, Italy and Belgium
in observance of the Assumption Day religous holiday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose for the fourth consecutive trading day to 142.20
Japanese yen from 141.93 yen. It traded at 142.30 yen in London and
at 142.15 yen in New York, up from 141.925 Monday.
   The British pound weakened in London, falling to $1.5735 from
$1.5840 late Monday. Sterling fetched $1.5768 in New York, down from
$1.5770.
   Other dollar rates at Tuesday's close compared with late Monday,
included: 1.9437 West German marks, down from 1.9485; 1.6748 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6805; 1.18025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17955;
6.5675 French francs, down from 6.5780; and 1,395.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,399.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Monday: 1.9500 West
German marks, up from 1.9395; 1.6790 Swiss francs, up from 1.6760;
6.5835 French francs, up from 6.5535; 2.1905 Dutch guilders, up from
2.1832; and 1.1822 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1775.
   Gold gained in London to a late bid price of $365.75 an ounce, up
from $364.00 bid Monday. In Zurich, gold jumped to $366.25 an ounce
from $363.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.42 to $365.72 an ounce.
   Silver prices rose. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.242 a troy ounce from $5.195 late
Monday. Silver settled at $5.24 an ounce in London, up from $5.21.
</TEXT>
