<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1743EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-15 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deteriorated Soybean and Corn Crop Boosts Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade on reports of deteriorating crop
conditions.
   On other markets, copper futures continued to rally, energy
issues were up, precious metals prices climbed, livestock were down
and pork futures prices were mixed.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 5} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.99\ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 6{
cents higher with September at $2.34\ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents
to 4 cents higher with September at $1.39{ a bushel; soybeans were
11 cents to 20 cents higher with August at $6.22{ a bushel.
   Analysts say Monday's crop ratings from the Department of
Agriculture showed a decline in the condition of the soybean crop _
particularly in Iowa and Illinois _ due to a lack of moisture.
   ``There was also a strike overnight in Brazil,'' said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago. ``While it did
not affect Brazilian soybean shipments, the psychology of that
didn't hurt the beans.''
   Soybean prices were also supported by the National Weather
Service's 30-day forecast _ released Monday _ which calls for
below-normal precipitation and above-normal temperatures.
   Corn futures were boosted by the announcement that Mexico would
be in the market for 400,000 metric tons of corn and rumors that the
Soviet Union also will enter the market.
   Wheat futures were helped by light commercial purchases by
Algeria and carryover from the other pits, Gidel said.
   Copper continued its climb on New York's Commodities Exchange,
amid fears of a shortage in supplies.
   In addition to a strike that has idled Peru's copper mines, the
strike at Canada's Highland Valley copper mine in British Columbia
continues, as does the shutdown of mines in Bougainville, Papua New
Guinea, due to landowner terrorism.
   ``There is some speculative buying as the demand numbers out of
Japan and the United States are strong,'' said Fred Demler, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Rumors of a strike in Mexico also boosted copper prices.
   Copper was 1.25 cents to 1.50 cents higher with August at $1.218
a pound.
   Bargain hunting pushed precious metals futures up on the Comex,
Demler said.
   The climb in prices were due to a weaker dollar resulting from
intervention by the central banks of several major industrial
nations.
   Gold was $3.60 to $4.30 higher with August at $370.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 4.7 cents to 5 cents higher with August at $5.242
a troy ounce.
   Energy futures were up in lifeless trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``The market is looking for something to shake it out of its
lethargy,'' said Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D. &amp; F. Man
International Futures Inc. in New York. ``It doesn't appear as
though there is anything on the horizon that will do that.''
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 2 cents to 10 cents higher
with September at $18.68 a barrel; heating oil was .02 cent to .24
cent higher with September at 50.28 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .03 cent lower to .20 cent higher with September at
52.06 a gallon.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures were pressured by commercial selling and
anticipation of the Department of Agriculture's cattle-on-feed
report. Analysts say the report, due out Thursday, is expected to
show lighter placements in feed and heavier marketings than last
year.
   Pork futures were pressured by increased hog receipts and falling
cash prices.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .45 cent lower with August at 74.07
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .90 cent lower with
August at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent to .35 cent
lower with August at 46.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.28 cent lower to .12 cent higher with August at 24.87 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
