<DOCNO> AP890815-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1813EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   08-15 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car, Truck Sales Up 8.2 Percent In Early August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of cars and light trucks rose 8.2 percent in
early August compared with last year, partly because of buying by
consumers seeking to avoid price increases for 1990 cars, the
companies reported Tuesday.
   Vehicles assembled by the eight major automakers in the United
States sold at an average daily rate of 33,660 during the Aug. 1-10
period this year, compared with a rate of 31,118 during the same
time last year.
   Car sales rose 7.4 percent and truck sales were up 9.4 percent
from the year-earlier period.
   In the last two seeks, the Big Three automakers have outlined
tentative price hikes for cars in the model year that generally
begins in October. General Motors Corp. said its tentative prices
will be about 3.4 percent above 1989 levels, Ford Motor Co. said its
prices will be about 4.8 percent higher and Chrysler Corp.'s 1990
prices will be about 5 percent up from 1989.
   The companies said some of the increases are due to costs
stemming from governmental requirements that they install passive
restraint systems _ air bags or automatic seat belts _ in 1990 model
cars.
   Some consumers may be pushing their 1990 car buying plans up a
few months to miss the price boosts.
   ``I think in all probability there are people buying a little
earlier than usual, but not many,'' said analyst Ron Glantz of
Montgomery Securities Inc. of San Francisco.
   He said the picture would become a clearer later in the month as
more sales reports are issued.
   Consumers also were lured by incentives, which automakers would
like to drop during the coming model year.
   ``Car sales are a little stronger than I expected,'' said analyst
David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New York. ``I would
say it is the attractive rebates on the '89s and the fear of costs
of air bags.''
   For Jan. 1 through Aug. 10, car and truck sales were 3.6 percent
behind last year's pace, falling to an average daily rate of 38,063
this year from a rate of 39,500 last year. Car sales were off 4.8
percent and truck sales were down 1.5 percent during the period.
   GM car sales during the 10-day August period dropped 2.7 percent
to a daily rate of 9,368 this year from 9,631 a year earlier. GM's
sales for the year to date were 8.6 percent behind last year's pace.
   GM's truck sales in early August were up 9.2 percent and for the
year to date were 2.2 percent behind last year's pace.
   Ford's early August car sales rose to a rate of 6,826 a day, 17.6
percent up from a rate of 5,804 in the year-earlier period. For the
year-to-date period, Ford's car sales were down 1.6 percent.
   Ford truck sales in early August were up 5.1 percent over last
year. For the year through Aug. 10, Ford's truck sales were down 2.8
percent from last year's pace.
   Chrysler's early August car sales rose 5.6 percent to a daily
rate of 2,835 this year from 2,685 daily a year earlier. Chrysler's
car sales for the year to date were 14.1 percent behind last year's
pace.
   Truck sales were up 16.8 percent in early August for Chrysler,
while falling 0.2 percent from a year earlier for the Jan. 1-Aug. 10
period.
</TEXT>
