<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-15 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished mostly higher Tuesday
in continued dull trading, buoyed mainly by technical market
factors, traders said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September-delivery
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, closed 10 cents higher at $18.68 per 42-gallon barrel.
Contract months for later delivery posted smaller advances.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded regular
gasoline for September delivery slipped 0.3 cent to 52.06 cents a
gallon. Most contracts for later delivery rose, however.
   Heating oil futures, which led the market higher last week,
posted moderate gains. The September contract jumped 0.24 cent to
finish at 50.28 cents a gallon.
   ``It's been very, very quiet in the market,'' said Jerry Samuels,
a vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The market gained some momentum when the September crude contract
hit the $18.50-per-barrel level, but other than that technical
factor there was little to move prices, he said.
   The oil market has been in the summer doldrums for some time.
Traders are looking forward to Labor Day for a pickup in activity
and beyond that to the next scheduled meeting, on Sept. 23, of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
