<FIRST>u f AM-Hammer 1stLd-Writethru   08-15 0994</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hammer, 1st Ld-Writethru,1018</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armand Hammer, Elated Over Bush Pardon, Usually Gets What He Wants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf, All the, with Oliver North
group calling for pardon; picks up 15th graf pvs, Born in .... Also moved
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armand Hammer, elated over his pardon by
President Bush for a Watergate-era crime, won a 13-year battle to
clear his name with the same persistence and political savvy that
made him a multibillionaire industrialist and intimate of world
leaders.
   Hammer, 91, said on Monday he had been pardoned for making
illegal contributions to President Nixon's re-election campaign in
1972. Hammer had pleaded guilty to the charges in 1976, and was
sentenced to one year's probation and fined $3,000.
   White House officials confirmed that Bush had pardoned Hammer and
nine other unidentified people on Monday, but refused to give
details. Repeated efforts to reach presidential counsel C. Boyden
Gray were unsuccessful Tuesday.
   ``Having spent my lifetime fighting injustice, this vindication
reinforces my abiding faith in the American system of justice,''
Hammer said in a statement from his Los Angeles home. ``I deeply
appreciate President Bush's action in clearing my name.''
   A spokesmen said Tuesday that Hammer, chairman of Occidental
Petroleum Corp., would have no further comment.
   Hammer spent several years seeking a pardon. President Reagan is
known to have considered granting Hammer's wish before he left
office last January, but nothing came of it.
   ``I'm pleading (guilty) because I'm guilty,'' Hammer had declared
in federal court in 1976. But Hammer had blamed former Gov. Tim
Babcock of Montana, a former vice president of an Occidental
subsidiary, through whom the $54,000 in illegal payments were made.
   Hammer argued that he funneled the money through Babcock to
maintain anonymity, but that Babcock did not deliver the funds until
after a new federal law went into effect in April 1972 which
prohibited making campaign contributions in someone else's name.
   Babcock was sentenced to four months in prison and fined $1,000
for concealing the identity of Hammer as the actual donor. A federal
judge later set aside Babcock's prison term, partly because Hammer
was given probation instead of a prison term because of his age and
poor health.
   Leaving his hospital bed as a heart patient for sentencing 13
years ago, Hammer expressed regret over the first crime he had ever
committed. He told the judge that ``I trust, in the time that may be
left me, your honor will allow me to continue being a useful member
of society.''
   Since his brush with the law, Hammer has circled the globe in his
specially outfitted Boeing 727 hobnobbing with presidents, kings and
prime ministers, pushing for U.S.-Soviet summit talks, providing aid
to earthquake victims, giving away chunks of his vast art collection
and trying to raise $1 billion to find a cure for cancer.
   ``I've had two dreams, two ambitions in life, and I hope to
accomplish both of them,'' he once said. They are peace between East
and West and a cure for cancer.
   All the while, Hammer has guided Occidental Petroleum's growth
from a struggling oil company worth $34,000 in 1956, when he made
his first investment, into a colossus of oil, chemicals, coal and
foods with a book value of more than $6 billion.
   His pardon was not universally applauded, however.
   A group called the Friends of Oliver North decried the pardon for
the man they said ``has been trying to encourage communist expansion
through his open business dealings with the Soviet Union.'' The
group called on Bush to ``muster the courage'' to pardon North, the
former White House aide convicted of charges in the Iran-Contra
affair.
   Born in New York as the grandson of a Russian Jewish immigrant,
Hammer became a millionaire while still studying at Columbia
University, when he took over his physician father's faltering
pharmaceutical business and turned it into a money-maker.
   At 23, he was fresh out of medical school but unwilling to wait
six months to begin his internship at New York's Bellevue Hospital.
So in 1921, Hammer made his first trip to the Soviet Union to help
alleviate a typhus epidemic.
   Once there, Hammer decided the Russian people needed food more
than medical assistance. He quickly announced a deal that brought a
shipload of surplus American wheat valued at $1 million in return
for Russian furs, hides and caviar.
   That deal caught the attention of V.I. Lenin, the first of many
Soviet leaders Hammer has known. Lenin encouraged the young American
entrepreneur to take over an abandoned asbestos mine near western
Siberia, the first Soviet concession ever granted to a foreigner.
   Hammer developed the mine into a profitable enterprise, and soon
obtained sales concessions for such leading American firms as Ford
Motor Co., U.S. Rubber, Allis-Chalmers and Underwood Typewriter. He
also opened the Soviet Union's first pencil factory, which posted $1
million in profits in the first year.
   Hammer left the Soviet Union in 1930, taking his profits in the
form of paintings, tapestries, silver and jewels, which formed the
start of his multimillion-dollar art collection. He owns two art
galleries in New York City.
   During the 1940s, Hammer netted a $7.5 million profit from a
$100,000 investment by developing a way to turn surplus potato crops
into commercial alcohol and marketing a blended whiskey under his
own label. He accumulated seven distilleries and later sold his
entire whiskey interests to the Schenley group.
   He also made fortunes in livestock feed and cattle, and held the
nation's first million-dollar purebred Angus cattle sale. Even
today, he is reaping fat profits from a $20 billion chemical
fertilizer deal with the Soviets, and has joint coal mining and
phosphoric acid ventures under way in China.
   Commenting on his reputation as a worldwide wheeler-dealer,
Hammer once said: ``I am first a catalyst. I bring people and
situations together. That's the big thing _ bringing the deal
together.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890815-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Congress-BoeingComputer     08-15 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Boeing Computer,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Says Government Was Charged $5.9 Million Too Much</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Congress-Computer Services listed on AM-Late News
Advisory. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing Corp. subsidiary overcharged the
government by $5.9 million on five computer projects between 1983
and 1987, a House committee said Tuesday.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., chairman of the House Government
Operations Committee, released a report from the General Accounting
Office, the congressional auditing agency, detailing the overcharges
by Boeing Computer Services Co. Like GAO, Conyers said he was asking
the Air Force to seek recovery of the money.
   Spokesmen for Boeing Computer Services in Seattle had no
immediate comment on the report.
   Conyers also said he received a related but separate report from
the GAO Tuesday suggesting that the Software Productivity
Consortium, a group of 14 of the nation's leading defense firms
established to develop tools and techniques to improve the
productivity of military software, may have overcharged the
government by $22.5 million for their participation in the
consortium.
   In both cases, the House Government Operations Committee said,
the improper charges stemmed from misclassification of projects as
``manufacturing and production engineering,'' a category of expense
for which contractors can be fully reimbursed by the government.
   The GAO, however, concluded that both Boeing Computer Services
and the Software Productivity Consortium should have classified
their activities as ``independent research and development''
expenditures, a classification of expenses for which the government
contribution is limited.
   ``In this era of $300-billion military budgets and
half-billion-dollar airplanes, $6 million may not seem like much,
but that money could give 2,225 youngsters a chance in life by
putting them through one year of Head Start,'' Conyers said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
