<FIRST>u f AM-SeaContainersBid     08-15 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Containers Bid,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Raises Bid for Sea Containers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock price for Sea Containers Ltd. surged
Tuesday after a bidder pursuing the equipment leasing and shipping
concern raised its unsolicited takeover offer by about $200 million
to more than $1 billion.
   The bidder is Temple Holdings Ltd., a company jointly owned by
Stena Holding AG, a Swedish shipping concern, and Tiphook PLC, a
British concern that provides containers to the shipping industry.
   Temple said it was raising its tender offer for Sea Containers'
common stock to $63 a share from $50 a share and boosted its offer
for the company's convertible preferred shares to $101.43 a share
from $80.50 a share.
   The offer values Sea Containers at about $1.02 billion, up from
$824 million under the previous offer was launched May 26.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Sea Containers rose
$4.12{ a share to $67.12{.
   Sea Containers had said last week that it was considering
recapitalizing as an alternative to the original takeover offer.
   The company, which is based in Hamilton, Bermuda, and its New
York-based public relations firm could not be reached after business
hours for comment on the higher offer.
   The three companies reportedly met Aug. 3 to discuss the
possibility of a sale of certain assets of Sea Containers' ferry
services and container businesses to Stena and Tiphook.
Subsequently, Stena and Tiphook said they may sell all or part of
their 8 percent stake in Sea Containers.
   Temple extended the expiration date of the latest tender offer to
Aug. 28.
   It said that under terms of its original offer, which was to have
expired Monday, approximately 103,500 shares of common stock had
been tendered.
</TEXT>
