<FIRST>r f AM-UAW-Diamond-Star     08-15 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW-Diamond-Star,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diamond-Star Reaches Tentative Agreement With UAW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diamond-Star Motors Corp. announced Tuesday
it has reached a tentative agreement with the United Auto Workers
union on the company's first three-year labor contract.
   Diamond-Star is a joint venture of Chrysler Motors and Mitsubishi
Motors, which are equal partners and have a joint management team at
the $650 million factory built west of town.
   Neither the company nor the union would discuss terms of the
contract, which must be ratified by 2,300 assembly line and
maintenance workers at the year-old factory.
   ``Negotiations concluded today,'' Robin Skiles, Diamond-Star
spokeswoman, said Tuesday. ``The two sides began talking March 29
and negotiations have continued since then.''
   Frank Joyce, UAW spokesman in Detroit, described the talks as
``protracted'' and said they recently intensified.
   Joyce said he expects the proposed contract to be put up for a
ratification vote within a week.
   The company employs about 2,600 people in the assembly of
two-door sports coupes marketed as the Plymouth Laser and the
Mitsubishi Eclipse.
   Diamond-Star also builds high-performance versions of the Laser
and Eclipse, which are four-wheel drive specialty coupes to be
distributed as the Eagle Talon and Mitsubishi Eclipse GSX.
   Plans call for the company to build a four-door sedan, called the
Eagle Summit and Mitsubishi Mirage, later this fall.
   Production at the plant began last September and workers voted to
join the UAW in December.
