<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 2343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0288 08-15 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0288,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Share Prices Climb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, dollar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened lower and edged down relative
to the Japanese yen Wednesday, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange continued their ascent for the second day.
   The dollar opened at 141.70 yen, down 0.50 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.20 yen. It moved in the range of 141.40 to 141.75 yen
and finished the morning session at 141.60 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 139.07 points
Tuesday, rose 193.32 points or 0.56 percent to finish the morning
session at 35,004.01.
   Dealers said the dollar started lower following dollar selling in
the Singapore and Sydney foreign exchange markets.
   Minoru Ozawa, a foreign exchange dealer with the Taiyo Kobe Bank,
said dealers were positioning themselves before announcements later
Wednesday of U.S. housing starts and investment utilization rates
for July.
   ``There were no other reasons to sell,'' he said.
   On the stock exchange, Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities said
stocks were performing well in all sectors.
   He said that stock traders also were waiting for the U.S. figures
from Washington, but were optimistic.
   Blue chips as well as laggard issues attracted buyer attention,
Shimoyama said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
